window.MM=window.MM||{};window.MM.med_p2_haemo=[{"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 24-year-old woman presents with progressive fatigue, exertional dyspnea, brittle nails and craving for ice for the last 6 months. Her Hb is 8.4 g/dL, MCV 66 fL, serum iron low, TIBC high and ferritin markedly reduced. Which pathophysiological mechanism best explains her anemia?", "a": "Impaired heme synthesis due to mitochondrial iron trapping", "b": "Absolute depletion of body iron stores", "c": "Defective globin chain synthesis", "d": "Decreased erythropoietin production", "ans": "B", "e": "Absolute depletion of body iron stores is the mechanism; markedly reduced ferritin with low serum iron, high TIBC, and pica directly reflects empty iron stores.<br><br>Iron deficiency anaemia features microcytic hypochromic anaemia with elevated RDW. Treatment with oral iron (ferrous sulfate) for 3-6 months. IV iron for malabsorption or oral intolerance. Combined with addressing underlying cause (menorrhagia, occult GI loss).<br><br>Mitochondrial iron trapping (option A) is sideroblastic anaemia; defective globin synthesis (option C) is thalassaemia; decreased erythropoietin (option D) is renal anaemia, all distinct from this absolute iron-store depletion pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 50-year-old male presents with chronic fatigue. Labs show Hb 10 g/dL, MCV 72 fL, ferritin normal-high, serum iron low and TIBC decreased. He has long-standing rheumatoid arthritis. The most important mediator responsible for this hematological pattern is:", "a": "Hepcidin", "b": "Haptoglobin", "c": "Erythropoietin", "d": "Transferrin", "ans": "A", "e": "Hepcidin is the key mediator in anaemia of chronic disease; rheumatoid arthritis inflammation elevates hepcidin which blocks ferroportin trapping iron in macrophages.<br><br>This produces low serum iron, low TIBC, and normal-high ferritin (sequestered iron). Treatment addresses the underlying inflammatory disease. Iron supplementation usually ineffective unless concurrent iron deficiency. EPO therapy for severe symptomatic anaemia.<br><br>Haptoglobin (option B) binds free haemoglobin in haemolysis; erythropoietin (option C) drives erythropoiesis; transferrin (option D) transports iron, none acting as the principal regulator of ACD iron sequestration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child with lifelong anemia has Hb 9.8 g/dL, MCV 64 fL, RBC count elevated, normal ferritin and normal RDW. Peripheral smear shows target cells. Which parameter is most helpful to confirm the diagnosis?", "a": "Reticulocyte index", "b": "Serum ferritin", "c": "Hb electrophoresis", "d": "Bone marrow iron stain", "ans": "C", "e": "Hb electrophoresis is most helpful here; microcytic anaemia with elevated RBC count, target cells, and normal ferritin/RDW strongly suggests thalassaemia requiring electrophoresis confirmation.<br><br>Beta thalassaemia trait shows HbA2 over 3.5 percent. Alpha thalassaemia trait shows normal HbA2 with possible HbH inclusions. Combined with genetic counselling for affected couples. No iron therapy needed unless concurrent iron deficiency documented.<br><br>Reticulocyte index (option A) is for haemolysis assessment; serum ferritin (option B) is already normal excluding iron deficiency; bone marrow iron stain (option D) is for sideroblastic, all less specific than electrophoresis here.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A pregnant woman in third trimester has microcytic anemia with increased RDW and low ferritin. After starting oral iron, which hematological change appears first?", "a": "Increase in hemoglobin", "b": "Reticulocytosis within days", "c": "Increase in ferritin", "d": "Rise in MCV", "ans": "B", "e": "Reticulocytosis within days is the earliest haematological response to iron therapy; bone marrow responds rapidly to restored iron availability before haemoglobin change.<br><br>Reticulocyte response peaks at 5-10 days. Haemoglobin rises by 1 g/dL per week thereafter. MCV normalises over weeks. Ferritin replenishment takes months. Continue iron 3-6 months after Hb normalisation to restore stores.<br><br>Haemoglobin rise (option A) takes 1-2 weeks; ferritin rise (option C) takes months reflecting stores; MCV rise (option D) takes weeks, all slower than the early reticulocyte response.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A chronic kidney disease patient has microcytic anemia with high ferritin and low transferrin saturation. Iron therapy alone fails. The most appropriate therapy is:", "a": "Erythropoiesis stimulating agent", "b": "Splenectomy", "c": "Vitamin B6", "d": "Packed RBC transfusion", "ans": "A", "e": "Erythropoiesis stimulating agent is appropriate; chronic kidney disease produces reduced renal EPO production with functional iron sequestration unresponsive to iron alone.<br><br>High ferritin with low transferrin saturation in CKD reflects inflammatory iron block. Treatment with epoetin alfa or darbepoetin targets target Hb 10-11.5 g/dL. Combined with iron supplementation often IV. Side effects include hypertension and thrombosis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including nephrologist.<br><br>Splenectomy (option B) is for hereditary spherocytosis; vitamin B6 (option C) is for sideroblastic; transfusion (option D) reserved for severe symptoms, none being first-line CKD-anaemia treatment.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 7-year-old child develops severe anemia 6 months after birth requiring repeated transfusions, with frontal bossing and hepatosplenomegaly. The anemia primarily results from:", "a": "Autoimmune RBC destruction", "b": "Peripheral hemolysis only", "c": "Chronic blood loss", "d": "Ineffective erythropoiesis with marrow expansion", "ans": "D", "e": "Ineffective erythropoiesis with marrow expansion drives the anaemia; beta thalassaemia major produces severe ineffective erythropoiesis with consequent marrow hyperplasia causing frontal bossing and hepatosplenomegaly.<br><br>Diagnosis by Hb electrophoresis showing predominant HbF with minimal HbA. Treatment includes regular transfusion programme, iron chelation (deferoxamine, deferasirox, deferiprone), and bone marrow transplantation in selected cases. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Autoimmune destruction (option A) features Coombs positivity; peripheral haemolysis alone (option B) lacks marrow expansion; chronic blood loss (option C) lacks skeletal changes, all distinct from this ineffective-erythropoiesis pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with pulmonary tuberculosis develops mild microcytic anemia. Iron stores are adequate but unavailable for erythropoiesis. The iron is mainly trapped in:", "a": "Enterocytes", "b": "Macrophages of reticuloendothelial system", "c": "Hepatocytes", "d": "Plasma transferrin", "ans": "B", "e": "Macrophages of reticuloendothelial system trap iron in anaemia of chronic disease; tuberculosis-driven inflammation elevates hepcidin blocking ferroportin and retaining iron within macrophages.<br><br>Iron stores adequate (normal-high ferritin) but unavailable for erythropoiesis. Treatment addresses underlying tuberculosis. Iron supplementation usually ineffective. EPO therapy for severe symptomatic anaemia. Combined with nutritional support. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Resolution follows infection control.<br><br>Enterocytes (option A) absorb iron from diet; hepatocytes (option C) store some iron normally; plasma transferrin (option D) transports iron, none being the principal sequestration site in ACD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A man with chronic alcoholism presents with dimorphic RBC population and bone marrow shows ring sideroblasts. The primary biochemical defect is failure of:", "a": "Erythropoietin receptor signaling", "b": "DNA synthesis in nucleus", "c": "Porphyrin synthesis in mitochondria", "d": "Globin translation", "ans": "C", "e": "Porphyrin synthesis in mitochondria fails in sideroblastic anaemia; alcohol toxicity impairs mitochondrial haem synthesis enzymes producing ring sideroblasts from iron-laden mitochondria around erythroblast nuclei.<br><br>Diagnosis by elevated serum iron, elevated ferritin, and ring sideroblasts on Prussian blue stain of bone marrow. Treatment with alcohol cessation, pyridoxine supplementation, and addressing underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>EPO receptor signalling (option A) is renal anaemia mechanism; DNA synthesis failure (option B) is megaloblastic; globin translation (option D) is thalassaemia, all distinct from this porphyrin synthesis defect.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 35-year-old female with menorrhagia presents with microcytic anemia. Which investigation best reflects total body iron stores?", "a": "Serum ferritin", "b": "Serum iron", "c": "Transferrin saturation", "d": "TIBC", "ans": "A", "e": "Serum ferritin best reflects total body iron stores; menorrhagia-associated iron deficiency requires ferritin measurement to confirm depleted stores.<br><br>Ferritin under 30 mcg/L confirms iron deficiency. Combined with low serum iron, high TIBC, and low transferrin saturation. Treatment with oral iron (ferrous sulfate 200 mg three times daily) for 3-6 months. Combined with gynaecological assessment for menorrhagia management.<br><br>Serum iron (option B) varies with diurnal rhythm and recent intake; transferrin saturation (option C) reflects circulating iron; TIBC (option D) reflects transferrin level, none reflecting body stores like ferritin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A laboratory report shows MCV 65 fL, HbA2 5.8%, normal ferritin and mild anemia. The most appropriate counseling for this patient is:", "a": "Avoid transfusion", "b": "Immediate splenectomy", "c": "Start lifelong iron therapy", "d": "Genetic counseling before marriage", "ans": "D", "e": "Genetic counselling before marriage is most appropriate; HbA2 5.8 percent with microcytosis and normal ferritin confirms beta thalassaemia trait requiring partner screening to prevent thalassaemia major offspring.<br><br>Antenatal diagnosis by chorionic villous sampling at 10-12 weeks if both partners affected. Combined with patient education about inheritance. No iron therapy needed. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including genetic counsellor.<br><br>Avoiding transfusion (option A) is unnecessary for trait; splenectomy (option B) is for major disease; lifelong iron (option C) is contraindicated risking overload, all inappropriate compared with genetic counselling for trait.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A strict vegetarian presents with fatigue. Hb 7 g/dL, microcytosis, high TIBC and low ferritin. The most common etiology in adult males with similar labs would be:", "a": "Hookworm infestation", "b": "Malabsorption syndrome", "c": "Occult gastrointestinal malignancy", "d": "Peptic ulcer bleeding", "ans": "C", "e": "Occult gastrointestinal malignancy is the most common aetiology in adult men with iron deficiency; colonic and gastric cancers commonly produce chronic occult blood loss.<br><br>Investigation requires upper and lower GI endoscopy in all men and post-menopausal women with iron deficiency. Treatment includes addressing underlying malignancy alongside iron supplementation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including gastroenterologist.<br><br>Hookworm (option A) common globally but less so in non-endemic adult men; malabsorption (option B) less common; peptic ulcer (option D) is one cause but malignancy must be excluded first as the most concerning common cause.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which feature best differentiates thalassemia trait from iron deficiency anemia in CBC indices?", "a": "High RBC count", "b": "Low MCV", "c": "Low hemoglobin", "d": "High RDW", "ans": "A", "e": "High RBC count differentiates thalassaemia trait from iron deficiency; thalassaemia features microcytosis with preserved or elevated RBC count due to increased compensatory erythropoiesis.<br><br>Mentzer index (MCV divided by RBC count) under 13 suggests thalassaemia, over 13 suggests iron deficiency. Combined with ferritin and HbA2 confirms diagnosis. Treatment depends on cause. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Low MCV (option B) occurs in both; low haemoglobin (option C) occurs in both; high RDW (option D) suggests iron deficiency over thalassaemia, none being as specific as the elevated RBC count in thalassaemia trait.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In anemia of chronic disease, transferrin saturation is low mainly because:", "a": "Increased urinary iron loss", "b": "Increased RBC destruction", "c": "Increased iron absorption", "d": "Reduced transferrin production", "ans": "D", "e": "Reduced transferrin production lowers transferrin saturation in anaemia of chronic disease; inflammatory cytokines suppress hepatic transferrin synthesis reducing TIBC.<br><br>Combined with hepcidin-mediated iron sequestration producing low serum iron with normal-high ferritin. Treatment addresses underlying disease. Iron supplementation usually ineffective. EPO therapy for severe symptomatic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Urinary iron loss (option A) is uncommon; RBC destruction (option B) is haemolysis with reticulocytosis; increased iron absorption (option C) is opposite, none explaining the low transferrin saturation in ACD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child presents with severe pallor, jaundice, and chipmunk facies. Which complication is most feared long-term?", "a": "Renal failure", "b": "Iron overload cardiomyopathy", "c": "Stroke", "d": "Aplastic crisis", "ans": "B", "e": "Iron overload cardiomyopathy is the most feared long-term complication; thalassaemia major requires regular transfusions producing iron deposition in myocardium with cardiac failure.<br><br>Cardiac iron load assessed by cardiac MRI T2 measurement. Treatment with intensive iron chelation (combination therapy with deferiprone and deferoxamine) prevents and reverses cardiac iron deposition. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including cardiologist. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Renal failure (option A) less common; stroke (option C) is in sickle cell disease; aplastic crisis (option D) is parvovirus B19 complication, none being the principal mortality cause in thalassaemia major.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which parameter will most likely be normal in thalassemia trait but abnormal in iron deficiency anemia?", "a": "RDW", "b": "MCV", "c": "Hemoglobin", "d": "Peripheral smear", "ans": "A", "e": "RDW is the differentiating parameter; iron deficiency produces elevated RDW from variable RBC sizes while thalassaemia trait shows uniform microcytosis with normal RDW.<br><br>Combined with ferritin (low in iron deficiency, normal in thalassaemia), serum iron, TIBC, transferrin saturation, and HbA2 (elevated in beta thalassaemia trait) confirms diagnosis. Treatment depends on cause.<br><br>MCV (option B) is low in both; haemoglobin (option C) is low in both; peripheral smear (option D) shows microcytosis in both though target cells favour thalassaemia, none being as specific as RDW.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient treated with isoniazid develops microcytic anemia. The drug interferes with synthesis of:", "a": "Erythropoietin", "b": "DNA polymerase", "c": "Pyridoxine-dependent enzymes", "d": "Folate metabolism", "ans": "C", "e": "Pyridoxine-dependent enzyme synthesis is impaired; isoniazid antagonises vitamin B6 reducing ALA synthase activity (the pyridoxine-dependent first step in haem synthesis) producing sideroblastic anaemia.<br><br>Treatment with pyridoxine supplementation (50-100 mg daily) prevents and reverses anaemia during isoniazid therapy. Diagnosis supported by elevated serum iron, elevated ferritin, and ring sideroblasts on bone marrow. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Erythropoietin synthesis (option A) is renal; DNA polymerase (option B) is megaloblastic mechanism; folate metabolism (option D) is for methotrexate, none being the isoniazid-specific mechanism causing this anaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In severe iron deficiency anemia, epithelial changes like glossitis occur due to:", "a": "Autoimmune reaction", "b": "Hemolysis", "c": "Increased bilirubin", "d": "Reduced oxygen delivery to rapidly dividing cells", "ans": "D", "e": "Reduced oxygen delivery to rapidly dividing cells produces glossitis; iron-dependent rapid epithelial turnover requires adequate oxygen for tongue mucosa renewal.<br><br>Other epithelial features include angular cheilitis, koilonychia, and oesophageal webs (Plummer-Vinson syndrome). All resolve with iron supplementation. Treatment includes oral iron (ferrous sulfate 200 mg three times daily) for 3-6 months. Combined with addressing underlying cause.<br><br>Autoimmune reaction (option A) is for atrophic gastritis; haemolysis (option B) is uncommon; increased bilirubin (option C) is haemolysis, none explaining the iron-deficiency epithelial change mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A microcytic anemia patient has ferritin high, CRP elevated, and low TIBC. The best initial management is:", "a": "Blood transfusion", "b": "Treat underlying inflammation", "c": "Folic acid", "d": "IV iron infusion", "ans": "B", "e": "Treating underlying inflammation is the best initial management; high ferritin with elevated CRP, low TIBC indicates anaemia of chronic disease where addressing inflammation reverses the iron block.<br><br>Treatment addresses underlying disease (rheumatoid arthritis, chronic infection, malignancy). Iron supplementation usually ineffective unless concurrent iron deficiency documented (very low ferritin uncommon). EPO therapy for severe symptomatic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Blood transfusion (option A) reserved for severe; folic acid (option C) is for megaloblastic; IV iron (option D) inappropriate with already-elevated ferritin, none addressing the underlying inflammatory cause.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which RBC morphology is most suggestive of iron deficiency anemia?", "a": "Spherocytes", "b": "Schistocytes", "c": "Target cells", "d": "Pencil cells", "ans": "D", "e": "Pencil cells are most suggestive of iron deficiency; elongated narrow erythrocytes form when severely iron-deficient red cells are produced.<br><br>Combined with hypochromia, microcytosis, anisocytosis, and target cells on peripheral smear. Diagnosis confirmed by low ferritin, low transferrin saturation, elevated TIBC, and elevated RDW. Treatment includes oral iron (ferrous sulfate) for 3-6 months and addressing underlying cause.<br><br>Spherocytes (option A) suggest hereditary spherocytosis or warm AIHA; schistocytes (option B) suggest microangiopathic haemolysis; target cells (option C) suggest thalassaemia or liver disease, none being as specific as pencil cells for iron deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hydrops fetalis occurs in:", "a": "Alpha thalassemia major", "b": "Iron deficiency anemia", "c": "Beta thalassemia minor", "d": "Sideroblastic anemia", "ans": "A", "e": "Alpha thalassaemia major (Hb Bart hydrops fetalis) causes hydrops fetalis; deletion of all four alpha genes produces severe fetal anaemia and intrauterine death.<br><br>Diagnosis by absent alpha chains with Hb Bart (gamma tetramers) on cord blood electrophoresis. Treatment is genetic counselling, antenatal diagnosis by chorionic villous sampling, and intrauterine transfusion in selected cases. Most cases incompatible with life beyond infancy.<br><br>Iron deficiency anaemia (option B) is acquired; beta thalassaemia minor (option C) is mild trait; sideroblastic anaemia (option D) is acquired, none causing hydrops fetalis like alpha thalassaemia major.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with microcytic anemia has Mentzer index of 11. Likely diagnosis:", "a": "Chronic disease anemia", "b": "Iron deficiency anemia", "c": "Thalassemia trait", "d": "Lead poisoning", "ans": "C", "e": "Thalassaemia trait fits Mentzer index of 11; this calculation (MCV divided by RBC count) under 13 suggests thalassaemia where microcytosis is disproportionate to preserved RBC count.<br><br>Combined with normal ferritin, target cells, and HbA2 over 3.5 percent (beta trait) or normal HbA2 (alpha trait). Treatment is genetic counselling for affected couples.<br><br>Chronic disease anaemia (option A) has elevated Mentzer; iron deficiency anaemia (option B) has Mentzer over 13; lead poisoning (option D) shows basophilic stippling, none matching the Mentzer index of 11 thalassaemia pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Lead poisoning anemia occurs due to inhibition of:", "a": "Pyruvate kinase", "b": "Ferrochelatase and ALA dehydratase", "c": "Hexokinase", "d": "Spectrin", "ans": "B", "e": "Ferrochelatase and ALA dehydratase inhibition produces lead poisoning anaemia; lead binds sulfhydryl groups inhibiting these haem synthesis enzymes producing microcytic anaemia.<br><br>Diagnosis by elevated blood lead level, basophilic stippling on peripheral smear, and microcytic anaemia. Free erythrocyte protoporphyrin elevated. Treatment with chelation (succimer, EDTA, dimercaprol) and removing lead source. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Pyruvate kinase (option A) is glycolysis (PK deficiency anaemia); hexokinase (option C) is glycolysis; spectrin (option D) is membrane (hereditary spherocytosis), none being the lead poisoning enzyme targets.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which treatment is curative for transfusion-dependent thalassemia major?", "a": "Splenectomy", "b": "Iron chelation", "c": "Folic acid", "d": "Bone marrow transplantation", "ans": "D", "e": "Bone marrow transplantation is curative for thalassaemia major; HLA-matched sibling donor replaces defective haematopoiesis with normal donor stem cells.<br><br>Indications include severe transfusion-dependent disease in young patients with HLA-matched sibling. Mortality 5-10 percent in experienced centres. Combined with conditioning regimens. Survival rates 80-90 percent at 5 years. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Splenectomy (option A) reduces transfusion need but not curative; iron chelation (option B) prevents overload but not curative; folic acid (option C) is supportive, none being curative like marrow transplantation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with anemia of chronic disease has low serum iron but normal marrow iron stores. The marrow iron appears as:", "a": "Hemosiderin in macrophages", "b": "Absent", "c": "Free plasma iron", "d": "Ring sideroblasts", "ans": "A", "e": "Haemosiderin in macrophages characterises ACD bone marrow; hepcidin-mediated iron retention by macrophages produces increased macrophage iron stores visible as haemosiderin on Prussian blue stain.<br><br>Combined with reduced erythroid iron (low sideroblasts) reflecting unavailable iron for erythropoiesis. Treatment addresses underlying inflammatory disease. Iron supplementation usually ineffective. EPO therapy for severe symptomatic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Absent iron (option B) is iron deficiency; free plasma iron (option C) suggests haemolysis; ring sideroblasts (option D) are sideroblastic anaemia, none matching the ACD macrophage haemosiderin pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "After adequate oral iron therapy for 1 month, hemoglobin fails to improve. The next best step is:", "a": "Start transfusion", "b": "Evaluate compliance and malabsorption", "c": "Add folate", "d": "Increase dose", "ans": "B", "e": "Evaluating compliance and malabsorption is the next best step; oral iron failure most commonly results from non-compliance, GI intolerance, concurrent medications (PPI, antacids), or malabsorption (coeliac disease, atrophic gastritis).<br><br>Investigation includes assessing compliance, GI symptoms, concurrent medications, and screening for malabsorption (coeliac serology). IV iron for confirmed malabsorption or oral intolerance. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Transfusion (option A) reserved for severe symptoms; folate addition (option C) does not address iron failure; dose increase (option D) without addressing cause is suboptimal, none being the appropriate first-line evaluation step.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which index is typically elevated in iron deficiency but normal in thalassemia?", "a": "RBC count", "b": "Reticulocyte count", "c": "RDW", "d": "MCHC", "ans": "C", "e": "RDW is typically elevated in iron deficiency but normal in thalassaemia; iron deficiency produces variable RBC sizes while thalassaemia shows uniform microcytosis.<br><br>Combined with ferritin (low in iron deficiency, normal in thalassaemia), Mentzer index, and HbA2 (elevated in beta thalassaemia trait) confirms diagnosis. Treatment depends on cause. Distinguishing carriers from affected individuals.<br><br>RBC count (option A) is elevated in thalassaemia (opposite pattern); reticulocyte count (option B) is variable; MCHC (option D) is low in both, none being as specific as RDW for distinguishing iron deficiency from thalassaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The primary role of hepcidin in inflammation is to:", "a": "Enhance iron absorption", "b": "Block ferroportin", "c": "Increase transferrin", "d": "Stimulate erythropoiesis", "ans": "B", "e": "Hepcidin blocks ferroportin in inflammation; this binds ferroportin causing internalisation and degradation reducing iron release from enterocytes and macrophages.<br><br>Mechanism reduces both iron absorption from gut and iron release from macrophage stores producing functional iron deficiency despite adequate stores. Treatment addresses underlying inflammatory disease. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing functional from absolute iron deficiency guides therapy.<br><br>Enhanced iron absorption (option A) is opposite; transferrin increase (option C) is opposite (decreased in inflammation); erythropoiesis stimulation (option D) is EPO function, none being hepcidin's principal action.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child presents with splenomegaly, microcytosis and normal ferritin. HbA2 normal but HbF increased. Likely diagnosis:", "a": "Alpha thalassemia trait", "b": "Beta thalassemia major", "c": "Beta thalassemia intermedia", "d": "Iron deficiency anemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Beta thalassaemia intermedia fits; normal HbA2 with elevated HbF plus splenomegaly and microcytosis suggests intermediate severity between trait and major with partial beta-chain deficiency.<br><br>Diagnosis confirmed by Hb electrophoresis and beta-globin gene analysis. Treatment includes intermittent transfusion when needed, folate supplementation, hydroxyurea (induces HbF), and iron chelation if transfusion-dependent. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Alpha thalassaemia trait (option A) shows normal HbA2 and normal HbF; beta thalassaemia major (option B) features severe disease with infantile onset; iron deficiency anaemia (option D) features low ferritin, none matching this intermediate pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which condition produces dimorphic anemia?", "a": "Megaloblastic anemia", "b": "Hemolytic anemia", "c": "Acute blood loss", "d": "Sideroblastic anemia", "ans": "D", "e": "Sideroblastic anaemia classically produces dimorphic anaemia; mixed population of normocytic-normochromic and microcytic-hypochromic red cells reflects coexisting normal and defective erythropoiesis.<br><br>Diagnosis by elevated serum iron, elevated ferritin, and ring sideroblasts on Prussian blue stain. Causes include hereditary (X-linked ALAS2 mutation), drug-induced (isoniazid, chloramphenicol, alcohol), lead toxicity, and myelodysplastic syndrome. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Megaloblastic anaemia (option A) features macrocytosis not dimorphism; haemolytic anaemia (option B) features reticulocytosis; acute blood loss (option C) features normocytic anaemia, none producing the dimorphic pattern characteristic of sideroblastic.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Koilonychia develops due to:", "a": "Iron deficiency affecting epithelial cells", "b": "Vitamin C deficiency", "c": "Collagen defect", "d": "Calcium deficiency", "ans": "A", "e": "Iron deficiency affecting epithelial cells produces koilonychia; reduced oxygen delivery to rapidly dividing nail matrix epithelium causes spoon-shaped nail concavity.<br><br>Other epithelial features include glossitis, angular cheilitis, brittle nails, and Plummer-Vinson syndrome (oesophageal webs). All resolve with iron supplementation. Treatment includes oral iron (ferrous sulfate) for 3-6 months. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Vitamin C deficiency (option B) is scurvy with bleeding gums; collagen defect (option C) is Ehlers-Danlos; calcium deficiency (option D) is for tetany, none producing the iron-deficiency koilonychia pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Low serum iron, high ferritin, low transferrin saturation best fits:", "a": "Thalassemia", "b": "Anemia of chronic disease", "c": "Hemolytic anemia", "d": "Iron deficiency anemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Anaemia of chronic disease fits this lab profile; low serum iron with elevated ferritin and low transferrin saturation reflects hepcidin-mediated iron sequestration in macrophages.<br><br>Mechanism involves elevated hepcidin reducing ferroportin expression decreasing iron release. Diagnosis by elevated ferritin (over 100 mcg/L), low serum iron, low TIBC, and normal or low transferrin saturation. Treatment addresses underlying disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Thalassaemia (option A) features normal ferritin; haemolytic anaemia (option C) features elevated reticulocytes; iron deficiency anaemia (option D) features low ferritin, none matching this ACD-specific iron pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In thalassemia major, extramedullary hematopoiesis occurs mainly in:", "a": "Liver and spleen", "b": "Brain", "c": "Lymph nodes", "d": "Kidneys", "ans": "A", "e": "Liver and spleen are principal sites of extramedullary haematopoiesis in thalassaemia major; ineffective bone marrow erythropoiesis activates fetal haematopoietic sites.<br><br>Produces hepatosplenomegaly. Skull X-ray may show 'hair-on-end' appearance from skull marrow expansion. Treatment with regular transfusion suppresses extramedullary haematopoiesis. Iron chelation prevents overload. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Brain (option B) is not a haematopoietic site; lymph nodes (option C) are immune not erythropoietic; kidneys (option D) produce EPO not RBCs, none being the principal extramedullary haematopoiesis sites.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which investigation differentiates sideroblastic anemia from anemia of chronic disease?", "a": "TIBC", "b": "Ferritin", "c": "Hemoglobin", "d": "Bone marrow iron staining pattern", "ans": "D", "e": "Bone marrow iron staining pattern differentiates sideroblastic anaemia from ACD; Prussian blue stain shows ring sideroblasts in sideroblastic versus macrophage haemosiderin in ACD.<br><br>Sideroblastic features iron-laden mitochondria around erythroblast nuclei (ring sideroblasts). ACD features increased macrophage iron with reduced erythroid iron. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>TIBC (option A) is reduced in both; ferritin (option B) is elevated in both; haemoglobin (option C) is reduced in both, none being as specific as bone marrow iron staining pattern for distinguishing these conditions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with iron deficiency anemia is treated. What ferritin level indicates adequate repletion?", "a": "5 ng/mL", "b": "20 ng/mL", "c": ">50 ng/mL", "d": "10 ng/mL", "ans": "C", "e": "Ferritin over 50 ng/mL indicates adequate iron repletion after deficiency treatment; restored iron stores prevent recurrence.<br><br>Continue iron therapy 3 months after Hb normalisation to fully replenish stores. Combined with addressing underlying cause (menorrhagia, occult GI loss). Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing adequate from inadequate repletion guides duration of therapy.<br><br>5 ng/mL (option A) indicates severe deficiency; 20 ng/mL (option B) indicates partial repletion; 10 ng/mL (option D) indicates deficiency, none being the adequate repletion threshold like over 50 ng/mL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common physical sign of severe chronic thalassemia:", "a": "Frontal bossing", "b": "Petechiae", "c": "Clubbing", "d": "Cyanosis", "ans": "A", "e": "Frontal bossing is the most common physical sign of severe chronic thalassaemia; extramedullary haematopoiesis with skull marrow expansion produces frontal bone prominence.<br><br>Combined with malar prominence, maxillary overgrowth, and chipmunk facies. Treatment with regular transfusion suppresses extramedullary haematopoiesis and prevents skeletal changes. Iron chelation prevents overload. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Petechiae (option B) is thrombocytopenia; clubbing (option C) is chronic hypoxia or cardiac; cyanosis (option D) is hypoxia, none being the principal thalassaemia skeletal-expansion sign like frontal bossing.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which lab pattern suggests combined iron deficiency and anemia of chronic disease?", "a": "Very low ferritin only", "b": "High iron", "c": "Normal ferritin but high CRP and low saturation", "d": "High ferritin only", "ans": "C", "e": "Normal ferritin with elevated CRP and low saturation suggests combined iron deficiency and ACD; inflammation falsely elevates ferritin into normal range while iron deficiency lowers saturation.<br><br>Diagnosis supported by ferritin under 100 mcg/L with elevated CRP. Soluble transferrin receptor elevated. Trial of iron supplementation may help. Combined with addressing underlying inflammation. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Very low ferritin only (option A) is pure iron deficiency; high iron (option B) suggests sideroblastic or overload; high ferritin only (option D) suggests pure ACD, none matching the combined deficiency-with-inflammation pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Iron absorption mainly occurs in:", "a": "Ileum", "b": "Duodenum", "c": "Colon", "d": "Jejunum", "ans": "B", "e": "Duodenum is the principal site of iron absorption; specialised enterocytes use DMT1 to uptake ferrous iron from diet.<br><br>Mechanism involves ferrous iron uptake by DMT1 on apical membrane, oxidation to ferric iron, and release via ferroportin (regulated by hepcidin) on basolateral membrane. Proximal jejunum also contributes. Vitamin C enhances absorption.<br><br>Ileum (option A) absorbs vitamin B12 and bile acids; colon (option C) absorbs water; jejunum (option D) absorbs many nutrients including some iron but duodenum is principal, none being the principal iron absorption site like duodenum.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which drug is used to prevent iron overload in transfusion-dependent thalassemia?", "a": "Methotrexate", "b": "Hydroxyurea", "c": "Warfarin", "d": "Deferoxamine", "ans": "D", "e": "Deferoxamine prevents iron overload in transfusion-dependent thalassaemia; this chelator binds iron facilitating renal excretion.<br><br>Standard regimen subcutaneous infusion 8-12 hours nightly. Indicated when ferritin over 1000 mcg/L or after 10-20 transfusions. Deferasirox and deferiprone are oral alternatives. Side effects include ototoxicity, retinopathy, and growth retardation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Methotrexate (option A) is for autoimmune disease; hydroxyurea (option B) is for sickle cell HbF induction; warfarin (option C) is anticoagulant, none being iron chelators like deferoxamine.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Basophilic stippling with abdominal pain suggests:", "a": "Thalassemia", "b": "Chronic disease", "c": "Lead poisoning", "d": "Iron deficiency", "ans": "C", "e": "Lead poisoning fits basophilic stippling with abdominal pain; lead inhibits pyrimidine 5'-nucleotidase producing RNA accumulation visible as basophilic stippling, while colicky abdominal pain reflects neurotoxicity.<br><br>Diagnosis by elevated blood lead level, basophilic stippling on peripheral smear, microcytic anaemia, and elevated free erythrocyte protoporphyrin. Treatment with chelation (succimer, EDTA, dimercaprol) and removing lead source. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Thalassaemia (option A) features target cells; chronic disease (option B) lacks stippling; iron deficiency (option D) lacks stippling, none producing the basophilic stippling with abdominal pain pattern like lead poisoning.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Anemia of chronic disease primarily affects iron metabolism by:", "a": "Blocking utilization", "b": "Increasing excretion", "c": "Increasing storage", "d": "Reducing absorption", "ans": "A", "e": "Blocking iron utilisation is the principal mechanism in ACD; hepcidin sequesters iron in macrophages preventing utilisation for erythropoiesis despite adequate stores.<br><br>Mechanism involves elevated hepcidin reducing ferroportin expression decreasing iron release from macrophages. Treatment addresses underlying inflammatory disease. Iron supplementation usually ineffective. EPO therapy for severe symptomatic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Increased excretion (option B) is not the mechanism; increased storage (option C) is consequence not mechanism; reduced absorption (option D) is partial component, none being as specific as utilisation blockade.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A vegetarian adolescent girl with Hb 8 g/dL and low ferritin should receive therapy for at least:", "a": "Lifetime", "b": "3 months after Hb normalization", "c": "Until Hb normalizes", "d": "2 weeks", "ans": "B", "e": "Iron therapy continues 3 months after Hb normalisation; this ensures replenishment of iron stores beyond just correcting anaemia.<br><br>Mechanism reflects that Hb normalisation precedes complete store replenishment by months. Combined with addressing underlying cause (menorrhagia, dietary insufficiency). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing Hb correction from full store repletion.<br><br>Lifetime (option A) is excessive for typical deficiency; until Hb normalises only (option C) leaves stores depleted; 2 weeks (option D) is inadequate, none being the recommended 3-month post-normalisation duration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The most reliable indicator of response to iron therapy after one week is:", "a": "Hb rise", "b": "Ferritin rise", "c": "MCV rise", "d": "Reticulocyte surge", "ans": "D", "e": "Reticulocyte surge is the most reliable indicator of iron therapy response at one week; bone marrow responds rapidly to iron availability before haemoglobin changes.<br><br>Reticulocyte response peaks at 5-10 days. Haemoglobin rises by 1 g/dL per week thereafter. MCV normalisation takes weeks. Ferritin replenishment takes months. Continue iron 3-6 months after Hb normalisation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Hb rise (option A) takes 1-2 weeks; ferritin rise (option B) takes months; MCV rise (option C) takes weeks, all slower than the early reticulocyte surge at one week.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In thalassemia trait, severity of anemia is disproportionate to:", "a": "RBC count", "b": "MCV reduction", "c": "Reticulocyte count", "d": "Platelet count", "ans": "B", "e": "MCV reduction is disproportionate to anaemia severity in thalassaemia trait; marked microcytosis (MCV often under 70 fL) with only mild reduction in haemoglobin.<br><br>Combined with normal or elevated RBC count, normal RDW, target cells, and HbA2 over 3.5 percent (beta trait) or normal HbA2 (alpha trait). Treatment is genetic counselling. No iron therapy needed. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>RBC count (option A) is preserved (not disproportionate); reticulocyte count (option C) is variable; platelet count (option D) is normal, none showing the disproportionate microcytosis pattern in thalassaemia trait like MCV.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with microcytic anemia has high iron and high ferritin. Diagnosis:", "a": "Chronic disease anemia", "b": "Thalassemia trait", "c": "Iron deficiency anemia", "d": "Sideroblastic anemia", "ans": "D", "e": "Sideroblastic anaemia fits microcytic anaemia with high serum iron and high ferritin; impaired haem synthesis with iron-laden mitochondria produces this pattern.<br><br>Diagnosis confirmed by ring sideroblasts on Prussian blue stain of bone marrow. Causes include hereditary (X-linked ALAS2 mutation), drug-induced (isoniazid, chloramphenicol, alcohol), lead toxicity, and myelodysplastic syndrome.<br><br>Chronic disease anaemia (option A) features low iron with high ferritin; thalassaemia trait (option B) features normal ferritin; iron deficiency (option C) features low iron and low ferritin, none matching this high-iron high-ferritin sideroblastic pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Primary cause of anemia in thalassemia major:", "a": "Ineffective erythropoiesis", "b": "Autoimmune hemolysis", "c": "Iron deficiency", "d": "Blood loss", "ans": "A", "e": "Ineffective erythropoiesis is the primary cause of anaemia in thalassaemia major; severe beta-chain deficiency produces intramedullary destruction of erythroblasts.<br><br>Mechanism involves unstable alpha-chain tetramers precipitating and damaging erythroblasts within bone marrow. Combined with peripheral haemolysis from membrane damage. Treatment includes regular transfusion programme, iron chelation, and bone marrow transplantation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Autoimmune haemolysis (option B) features Coombs positivity; iron deficiency (option C) features low ferritin; blood loss (option D) lacks ineffective erythropoiesis, none being the principal thalassaemia mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which anemia improves dramatically with pyridoxine therapy?", "a": "Thalassemia", "b": "Chronic disease anemia", "c": "Isoniazid-induced sideroblastic anemia", "d": "Lead poisoning", "ans": "C", "e": "Isoniazid-induced sideroblastic anaemia improves dramatically with pyridoxine; isoniazid antagonises vitamin B6 (cofactor for ALA synthase) producing reversible sideroblastic anaemia.<br><br>Standard pyridoxine dose 50-100 mg daily during isoniazid therapy prevents and reverses anaemia. Hereditary X-linked sideroblastic anaemia (ALAS2 mutation) also responds. Other sideroblastic forms have variable response. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Thalassaemia (option A) does not respond to pyridoxine; chronic disease anaemia (option B) responds to addressing underlying disease; lead poisoning (option D) requires chelation, none responding dramatically to pyridoxine like isoniazid-induced sideroblastic.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Ferritin acts as:", "a": "Iron storage protein", "b": "Iron excretion molecule", "c": "Iron transport protein", "d": "Iron absorption enzyme", "ans": "A", "e": "Ferritin acts as the principal iron storage protein; this soluble intracellular protein binds up to 4500 iron atoms within its core.<br><br>Stored primarily in macrophages and hepatocytes. Serum ferritin reflects total body iron stores. Excess stored as haemosiderin (insoluble aggregates). Low ferritin confirms iron deficiency. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing storage from transport functions.<br><br>Iron excretion molecule (option B) is incorrect (no specific excretion molecule); iron transport (option C) is transferrin function; iron absorption enzyme (option D) is DMT1 function, none being storage like ferritin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most specific test to detect iron deficiency before anemia develops:", "a": "Peripheral smear", "b": "MCV", "c": "Hb", "d": "Serum ferritin", "ans": "D", "e": "Serum ferritin most specifically detects iron deficiency before anaemia develops; ferritin reflects body iron stores depleting before erythropoiesis impairment.<br><br>Ferritin under 30 mcg/L confirms iron deficiency even with normal haemoglobin. Combined with low transferrin saturation supports diagnosis. Treatment with oral iron prevents progression to anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Peripheral smear (option A) changes only with established deficiency; MCV (option B) changes with established deficiency; haemoglobin (option C) defines anaemia not pre-anaemia, none being as specific for early deficiency as ferritin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Repeated transfusions in thalassemia cause endocrine failure due to:", "a": "Infection", "b": "Folate deficiency", "c": "Iron deposition", "d": "Hypoxia", "ans": "C", "e": "Iron deposition causes endocrine failure in transfused thalassaemia; each unit of blood adds 200-250 mg iron with no excretion pathway producing organ iron deposition.<br><br>Endocrine organs particularly susceptible include pancreas (diabetes), pituitary (hypogonadism, growth retardation), thyroid (hypothyroidism), and parathyroid (hypoparathyroidism). Iron chelation prevents and reverses. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Infection (option A) is uncommon endocrine cause; folate deficiency (option B) is anaemia mechanism; hypoxia (option D) is general, none being the principal transfusion-related endocrine failure mechanism like iron deposition.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which finding strongly favors thalassemia over iron deficiency?", "a": "Microcytosis", "b": "Normal RDW with high RBC count", "c": "Hypochromia", "d": "Low MCV", "ans": "B", "e": "Normal RDW with high RBC count strongly favours thalassaemia over iron deficiency; thalassaemia features uniform microcytosis with compensatory erythropoiesis maintaining elevated RBC count.<br><br>Iron deficiency in contrast features elevated RDW from variable RBC sizes and reduced RBC count. Combined with Mentzer index, ferritin, and HbA2 confirms thalassaemia. Treatment is genetic counselling for trait.<br><br>Microcytosis (option A) occurs in both; hypochromia (option C) occurs in both; low MCV (option D) occurs in both, none being as specific as the combination of normal RDW with elevated RBC count for thalassaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 62-year-old vegetarian presents with progressive numbness in feet, difficulty walking and memory disturbance. Hb 8.2 g/dL, MCV 118 fL. Peripheral smear shows macro-ovalocytes and hypersegmented neutrophils. The neurological deficit is primarily due to accumulation of:", "a": "Homocysteine", "b": "Lactate", "c": "Methylmalonic acid", "d": "Bilirubin", "ans": "C", "e": "Methylmalonic acid accumulation causes B12-deficiency neuropathy; B12 is cofactor for methylmalonyl-CoA mutase, and deficiency disrupts myelin synthesis through abnormal fatty acid incorporation.<br><br>Diagnosis by low serum B12, elevated methylmalonic acid, and elevated homocysteine. Treatment with intramuscular hydroxocobalamin produces neurological recovery (often incomplete if longstanding). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including neurologist. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Homocysteine (option A) rises in both B12 and folate deficiency without specific neurotoxicity; lactate (option B) is anaerobic metabolism; bilirubin (option D) is haemolysis or liver disease, none being the specific B12 neuropathy mediator.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which microscopic finding most strongly supports vitamin B12 deficiency rather than folate deficiency?", "a": "Howell–Jolly bodies", "b": "Hypersegmented neutrophils", "c": "Subacute combined degeneration", "d": "Macro-ovalocytes", "ans": "A", "e": "Howell-Jolly bodies support B12 deficiency over folate deficiency; these basophilic nuclear remnants in red cells reflect more severe dyserythropoiesis in B12 deficiency.<br><br>Combined with macro-ovalocytes, hypersegmented neutrophils, and megaloblastic bone marrow. Diagnosis by low serum B12, elevated methylmalonic acid, and elevated homocysteine. Treatment with intramuscular hydroxocobalamin. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Hypersegmented neutrophils (option B) occur in both B12 and folate deficiency; subacute combined degeneration (option C) is clinical not microscopic; macro-ovalocytes (option D) occur in both, none being as specific for B12 deficiency as Howell-Jolly bodies.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient develops macrocytic anemia after total gastrectomy 2 years ago. The mechanism of anemia is failure of absorption due to deficiency of:", "a": "Pepsin", "b": "Intrinsic factor", "c": "Transcobalamin II", "d": "Gastrin", "ans": "B", "e": "Intrinsic factor deficiency causes post-gastrectomy macrocytic anaemia; total gastrectomy removes parietal cells that produce intrinsic factor required for ileal B12 absorption.<br><br>Treatment with lifelong intramuscular hydroxocobalamin 1 mg every 3 months. Oral B12 inadequate due to absent intrinsic factor. Combined with addressing other post-gastrectomy nutritional deficiencies. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including gastroenterologist. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Pepsin (option A) is for protein digestion; transcobalamin II (option C) is plasma transport not absorption; gastrin (option D) is acid secretion regulator, none being the absorption mechanism lost in gastrectomy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A strict vegan pregnant woman develops anemia but no neurological signs. Homocysteine high, methylmalonic acid normal. Diagnosis:", "a": "Iron deficiency", "b": "Vitamin B12 deficiency", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Folate deficiency", "ans": "D", "e": "Folate deficiency fits this pattern; elevated homocysteine with normal methylmalonic acid distinguishes folate deficiency from B12 deficiency, and absent neurological signs supports folate over B12.<br><br>Pregnancy increases folate demand. Diagnosis confirmed by low serum or RBC folate. Treatment with oral folic acid 5 mg daily for 4 months. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) is microcytic; vitamin B12 deficiency (option B) elevates methylmalonic acid; haemolysis (option C) features reticulocytosis, none matching the normal-MMA elevated-homocysteine folate-specific pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most specific confirmatory test for pernicious anemia:", "a": "Serum B12 level", "b": "Reticulocyte count", "c": "Anti–intrinsic factor antibodies", "d": "Elevated MCV", "ans": "C", "e": "Anti-intrinsic factor antibodies are most specific for pernicious anaemia; high specificity (over 95 percent) despite lower sensitivity.<br><br>Combined with anti-parietal cell antibodies (sensitive but less specific). Both should be tested. Atrophic gastritis on biopsy supports diagnosis. Treatment with lifelong intramuscular hydroxocobalamin. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Serum B12 level (option A) confirms deficiency but not aetiology; reticulocyte count (option B) is general response marker; elevated MCV (option D) confirms macrocytosis but not pernicious anaemia specifically, none being as specific as anti-intrinsic factor antibodies.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which site is responsible for vitamin B12 absorption?", "a": "Colon", "b": "Jejunum", "c": "Duodenum", "d": "Terminal ileum", "ans": "D", "e": "Terminal ileum is the site of B12 absorption; intrinsic factor-B12 complex binds to specific receptors (cubilin) on terminal ileal enterocytes for absorption.<br><br>Conditions affecting terminal ileum (Crohn disease, ileal resection, tropical sprue) impair B12 absorption. Treatment with lifelong intramuscular hydroxocobalamin in these patients. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Colon (option A) absorbs water; jejunum (option B) absorbs many nutrients but not B12; duodenum (option C) absorbs iron and folate, none being the B12-specific absorption site like terminal ileum.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hypersegmented neutrophils are defined as neutrophils having:", "a": "≥6 lobes", "b": "≥5 lobes", "c": "≥3 lobes", "d": "≥4 lobes", "ans": "B", "e": "Hypersegmented neutrophils have 5 or more nuclear lobes; classical hallmark of megaloblastic anaemia reflecting delayed nuclear maturation.<br><br>Combined with macro-ovalocytes (large oval red cells) and megaloblastic bone marrow. Diagnosis with B12, folate, homocysteine, and methylmalonic acid testing. Treatment with B12 or folate replacement produces rapid haematological response.<br><br>6 lobes (option A) defines severe hypersegmentation but the threshold for definition is 5; 3 lobes (option C) is normal; 4 lobes (option D) is normal upper range, none being the standard definition threshold of 5 lobes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A chronic alcoholic presents with macrocytosis but normal methylmalonic acid and no neuropathy. Most likely cause:", "a": "Folate deficiency", "b": "B12 deficiency", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Liver disease", "ans": "A", "e": "Folate deficiency fits chronic alcoholic with macrocytosis and normal methylmalonic acid; alcohol impairs folate metabolism, intake, and absorption while normal MMA excludes B12 deficiency.<br><br>Diagnosis by low serum or RBC folate, elevated homocysteine, and normal methylmalonic acid. Treatment with oral folic acid 5 mg daily for 4 months. Combined with alcohol cessation and addressing nutritional deficiencies.<br><br>B12 deficiency (option B) elevates methylmalonic acid; haemolysis (option C) features reticulocytosis; liver disease (option D) causes macrocytosis but with abnormal LFTs, none being as specific as folate deficiency for this normal-MMA alcoholic pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which biochemical reaction requires vitamin B12 as cofactor?", "a": "Conversion of glycine to serine", "b": "Conversion of iron to ferritin", "c": "Conversion of homocysteine to methionine", "d": "Conversion of pyruvate to lactate", "ans": "C", "e": "Conversion of homocysteine to methionine requires B12 as cofactor; methionine synthase uses methyl-B12 to transfer methyl group from methyl-THF to homocysteine.<br><br>Mechanism includes B12-dependent methionine synthase reaction. B12 deficiency traps folate as methyl-THF (folate trap hypothesis) and elevates homocysteine. Treatment with B12 replacement restores reaction. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Glycine to serine (option A) uses folate not B12; iron to ferritin (option B) is storage not B12-dependent; pyruvate to lactate (option D) is LDH-mediated, none requiring B12 as cofactor like the methionine synthase reaction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Failure to treat B12 deficiency before folate therapy may result in:", "a": "Irreversible neurological damage", "b": "Renal failure", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Thrombocytopenia", "ans": "A", "e": "Irreversible neurological damage may result from folate therapy in untreated B12 deficiency; folate corrects megaloblastic anaemia but allows B12 neurological disease to progress.<br><br>Always exclude B12 deficiency before starting folate. Replace B12 first if both deficient. Intramuscular hydroxocobalamin 1 mg every 2-3 days for 2 weeks (loading), then 1 mg every 3 months for life. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Renal failure (option B) is unrelated; haemolysis (option C) is unrelated; thrombocytopenia (option D) is unrelated, none being the specific risk of folate therapy in undiagnosed B12 deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A newborn of a malnourished mother develops neural tube defect. This is due to deficiency of:", "a": "Vitamin C", "b": "Folic acid", "c": "Vitamin B6", "d": "Vitamin B12", "ans": "B", "e": "Folic acid deficiency in malnourished mother causes neural tube defects in newborn; inadequate periconceptional folate impairs neural tube closure.<br><br>Standard supplementation 400 mcg daily pre-conception and through first trimester prevents most NTDs. Higher doses (5 mg daily) for women with previous affected pregnancy, diabetes, epilepsy on antiepileptics. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Vitamin C (option A) is for scurvy; vitamin B6 (option C) is for sideroblastic; vitamin B12 (option D) is uncommon NTD cause compared to folate, none being the principal NTD-prevention vitamin like folate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which lab finding differentiates B12 deficiency from folate deficiency?", "a": "Increased MCV", "b": "Low hemoglobin", "c": "Elevated homocysteine", "d": "Elevated methylmalonic acid", "ans": "D", "e": "Elevated methylmalonic acid differentiates B12 from folate deficiency; B12 is cofactor for methylmalonyl-CoA mutase, deficiency elevates MMA, while folate deficiency leaves MMA normal.<br><br>Combined with elevated homocysteine in both deficiencies. Useful for distinguishing causes and monitoring response. Treatment depends on cause (B12 vs folate replacement). Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Increased MCV (option A) occurs in both; low haemoglobin (option B) occurs in both; elevated homocysteine (option C) occurs in both, none being as specific for B12 versus folate deficiency as methylmalonic acid.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Peripheral smear in megaloblastic anemia shows:", "a": "Macro-ovalocytes", "b": "Spherocytes", "c": "Schistocytes", "d": "Target cells", "ans": "A", "e": "Macro-ovalocytes characterise megaloblastic anaemia peripheral smear; large oval red cells (MCV over 100 fL) reflect impaired DNA synthesis.<br><br>Combined with hypersegmented neutrophils (5+ lobes), Howell-Jolly bodies (B12 deficiency), and megaloblastic bone marrow. Diagnosis with B12, folate, homocysteine, and methylmalonic acid. Treatment with B12 or folate replacement. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Spherocytes (option B) suggest hereditary spherocytosis or warm AIHA; schistocytes (option C) suggest microangiopathic haemolysis; target cells (option D) suggest thalassaemia or liver disease, none being the megaloblastic-specific macro-ovalocyte morphology.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient on long-term metformin develops anemia. The mechanism is:", "a": "Reduced intrinsic factor secretion", "b": "Impaired ileal absorption of B12", "c": "Increased urinary excretion", "d": "Bone marrow suppression", "ans": "B", "e": "Impaired ileal absorption of B12 causes metformin-associated anaemia; metformin interferes with calcium-dependent B12-intrinsic factor binding in terminal ileum.<br><br>Long-term metformin use (over 2-4 years) increases risk. Treatment with B12 supplementation, often oral 1000 mcg daily effective. Combined with monitoring B12 status in patients on long-term metformin. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Reduced intrinsic factor (option A) is pernicious anaemia mechanism; increased urinary excretion (option C) is not principal; bone marrow suppression (option D) is uncommon, none being the metformin-specific mechanism of ileal absorption impairment.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Reticulocyte response after B12 therapy typically occurs in:", "a": "24 hours", "b": "2–3 days", "c": "5–7 days", "d": "3 weeks", "ans": "C", "e": "Reticulocyte response after B12 therapy occurs at 5-7 days; bone marrow recovery from megaloblastic state produces this early haematological change.<br><br>Haemoglobin rises within 1-2 weeks, normalises within 6-8 weeks. Hypersegmented neutrophils persist for 2 weeks. Hypokalaemia may complicate rapid haematopoiesis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>24 hours (option A) is too early; 2-3 days (option B) is too early for full peak; 3 weeks (option D) is too late, none being the typical 5-7 day reticulocyte response timing.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A Crohn disease patient with ileal resection develops anemia and paresthesia. Treatment:", "a": "Blood transfusion", "b": "Oral B12", "c": "Oral folate", "d": "Intramuscular B12", "ans": "D", "e": "Intramuscular B12 treats Crohn disease with ileal resection plus anaemia and paraesthesia; absent ileal absorption makes oral therapy inadequate.<br><br>Standard dose 1 mg intramuscularly every 2-3 days for 2 weeks (loading), then 1 mg every 3 months for life. Combined with addressing underlying Crohn disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including gastroenterologist.<br><br>Blood transfusion (option A) reserved for severe symptoms; oral B12 (option B) is inadequate for ileal absorption defect; oral folate (option C) is contraindicated in undiagnosed B12 deficiency, none being appropriate for this ileal-resection B12 deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which medication commonly causes folate deficiency anemia?", "a": "Methotrexate", "b": "Warfarin", "c": "Aspirin", "d": "Isoniazid", "ans": "A", "e": "Methotrexate commonly causes folate deficiency anaemia; this dihydrofolate reductase inhibitor blocks folate metabolism affecting DNA synthesis.<br><br>Folic acid supplementation (5 mg weekly) reduces side effects in low-dose methotrexate. Folinic acid (leucovorin) rescues high-dose methotrexate toxicity. Combined with addressing other causes of folate deficiency. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Warfarin (option B) is anticoagulant; aspirin (option C) is antiplatelet; isoniazid (option D) causes pyridoxine deficiency and sideroblastic anaemia, none being the folate antagonist like methotrexate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In megaloblastic anemia, bone marrow is typically:", "a": "Fibrotic", "b": "Hypercellular with nuclear-cytoplasmic asynchrony", "c": "Hypocellular", "d": "Normocellular", "ans": "B", "e": "Hypercellular bone marrow with nuclear-cytoplasmic asynchrony characterises megaloblastic anaemia; impaired DNA synthesis delays nuclear maturation while cytoplasmic haemoglobinisation proceeds normally.<br><br>Other features include megaloblasts, giant metamyelocytes, and hypersegmented neutrophils. Treatment with B12 or folate replacement produces rapid haematological response. Diagnosis usually clinical with B12, folate, homocysteine, and methylmalonic acid. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Fibrotic (option A) is myelofibrosis; hypocellular (option C) is aplastic anaemia; normocellular (option D) is many causes including normal, none being the megaloblastic-specific marrow pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Pancytopenia in macrocytic anemia occurs due to:", "a": "Infection", "b": "Peripheral destruction", "c": "Iron deficiency", "d": "Ineffective hematopoiesis", "ans": "D", "e": "Ineffective haematopoiesis causes pancytopenia in macrocytic anaemia; impaired DNA synthesis affects all three lineages with intramedullary cell destruction.<br><br>Diagnosis by megaloblastic bone marrow with megaloblasts, giant metamyelocytes, and hypersegmented neutrophils. Treatment with B12 or folate replacement produces rapid haematological response. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Infection (option A) is uncommon mechanism; peripheral destruction (option B) is haemolysis; iron deficiency (option C) is microcytic, none being the megaloblastic-specific pancytopenia mechanism like ineffective haematopoiesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which parameter rises in both B12 and folate deficiency?", "a": "TIBC", "b": "Ferritin", "c": "Homocysteine", "d": "Methylmalonic acid", "ans": "C", "e": "Homocysteine rises in both B12 and folate deficiency; reflects impaired methionine synthesis from folate-B12 interdependent pathway.<br><br>Combined with methylmalonic acid (elevated in B12 deficiency, normal in folate deficiency) for distinguishing causes. Useful for diagnosis and monitoring response. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>TIBC (option A) is iron metabolism marker; ferritin (option B) is iron stores marker; methylmalonic acid (option D) elevates in B12 deficiency only, none rising in both deficiencies like homocysteine.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Glossitis in megaloblastic anemia is caused by:", "a": "Infection", "b": "Hemolysis", "c": "Iron overload", "d": "Epithelial cell turnover failure", "ans": "D", "e": "Epithelial cell turnover failure causes glossitis in megaloblastic anaemia; impaired DNA synthesis prevents rapid tongue mucosal renewal.<br><br>Beefy red smooth tongue characteristic. Other features include angular cheilitis and oral aphthous ulcers. Resolves with B12 or folate replacement. Combined with addressing underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Infection (option A) is uncommon megaloblastic cause; haemolysis (option B) is general; iron overload (option C) is unrelated, none being the megaloblastic glossitis mechanism like impaired epithelial turnover.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with pernicious anemia is at increased risk of:", "a": "Gastric carcinoma", "b": "Lung cancer", "c": "Pancreatic cancer", "d": "Colon cancer", "ans": "A", "e": "Pernicious anaemia increases gastric carcinoma risk; chronic atrophic gastritis predisposes 2-3 times general population risk.<br><br>Surveillance endoscopy is controversial; symptomatic patients warrant investigation. Combined with autoimmune polyglandular syndrome assessment. Treatment with lifelong intramuscular hydroxocobalamin. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including gastroenterologist. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Lung cancer (option B) is unrelated; pancreatic cancer (option C) is unrelated; colon cancer (option D) is unrelated, none being the pernicious-anaemia-specific increased malignancy risk like gastric carcinoma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which transport protein carries vitamin B12 in plasma?", "a": "Albumin", "b": "Ferritin", "c": "Transcobalamin II", "d": "Transferrin", "ans": "C", "e": "Transcobalamin II carries vitamin B12 in plasma; this is the principal physiologically active B12 transport protein.<br><br>Holotranscobalamin (active B12) under 35 pmol/L suggests deficiency. Earlier marker of B12 deficiency than total serum B12. Combined with methylmalonic acid and homocysteine for assessment. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Albumin (option A) is general plasma protein; ferritin (option B) stores iron; transferrin (option D) transports iron, none being the B12-specific plasma transport like transcobalamin II.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which pregnancy complication is prevented by folic acid supplementation?", "a": "Placenta previa", "b": "Neural tube defects", "c": "Preeclampsia", "d": "Gestational diabetes", "ans": "B", "e": "Neural tube defects are prevented by folic acid supplementation; periconceptional folate is required for proper neural tube closure.<br><br>Standard supplementation 400 mcg daily pre-conception and through first trimester. Higher doses (5 mg daily) for women with previous affected pregnancy, diabetes, or epilepsy on antiepileptics. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician. Long-term follow-up is essential. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Placenta previa (option A) is implantation; preeclampsia (option C) is hypertensive disorder; gestational diabetes (option D) is metabolic, none being folate-preventable pregnancy complications like NTDs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A macrocytic anemia patient has normal B12 but low RBC folate. Diagnosis:", "a": "Folate deficiency", "b": "B12 deficiency", "c": "Hemolytic anemia", "d": "Iron deficiency", "ans": "A", "e": "Folate deficiency fits macrocytic anaemia with normal B12 and low RBC folate; tissue folate stores depleted.<br><br>Diagnosis by low serum or RBC folate, elevated homocysteine, and normal methylmalonic acid. Causes include pregnancy (high demand), poor diet, malabsorption, alcoholism, methotrexate. Treatment with oral folic acid 5 mg daily for 4 months. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>B12 deficiency (option B) features low B12; haemolytic anaemia (option C) features reticulocytosis; iron deficiency (option D) is microcytic, none matching the macrocytic-normal-B12-low-folate pattern of folate deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which neurological pathway is primarily affected in B12 deficiency?", "a": "Cerebellar cortex only", "b": "Basal ganglia", "c": "Corticospinal and dorsal columns", "d": "Spinothalamic tract", "ans": "C", "e": "Corticospinal and dorsal columns are affected in B12 deficiency; subacute combined degeneration of spinal cord targets these pathways.<br><br>Features include peripheral neuropathy, ataxia, position sense impairment, hyperreflexia, and Babinski sign. Treatment with intramuscular hydroxocobalamin produces neurological recovery (often incomplete if longstanding). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including neurologist. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Cerebellar cortex (option A) is partial; basal ganglia (option B) is movement disorders; spinothalamic tract (option D) is pain and temperature, none being the B12-specific dorsal-column corticospinal subacute-combined target.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "An alcoholic with poor diet develops anemia after 2 months. Most likely deficiency:", "a": "Iron", "b": "B12", "c": "Copper", "d": "Folate", "ans": "D", "e": "Folate deficiency develops in alcoholic with poor diet in 2 months; folate stores deplete rapidly (4-5 months total body store) and alcohol impairs folate metabolism.<br><br>Diagnosis by low serum or RBC folate, elevated homocysteine, and normal methylmalonic acid. Treatment with oral folic acid 5 mg daily for 4 months. Combined with alcohol cessation. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Iron (option A) has years of stores; B12 (option B) has years of stores (3-5 years); copper (option C) is uncommon, none depleting as rapidly as folate in alcoholic poor diet 2-month timeframe.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "MCV 122 fL, LDH high, indirect bilirubin elevated in macrocytic anemia indicates:", "a": "Renal disease", "b": "Ineffective erythropoiesis with intramedullary destruction", "c": "Hemolysis due to membrane defect", "d": "Blood loss", "ans": "B", "e": "Ineffective erythropoiesis with intramedullary destruction fits MCV 122 with high LDH and indirect bilirubin; megaloblastic state produces apparent haemolysis pattern from intramedullary cell breakdown.<br><br>Distinguishing from true haemolysis through bone marrow examination and reticulocyte count (low in megaloblastic, high in true haemolysis). Treatment with B12 or folate replacement. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Renal disease (option A) produces normocytic anaemia; haemolysis due to membrane defect (option C) features reticulocytosis; blood loss (option D) is normocytic, none matching the megaloblastic pseudohaemolysis pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which test best reflects long-term folate status?", "a": "RBC folate", "b": "Homocysteine", "c": "Serum folate", "d": "MCV", "ans": "A", "e": "RBC folate best reflects long-term folate status; red cell folate represents months of incorporation reflecting tissue stores.<br><br>Serum folate reflects recent intake (short-term). Combined with B12 and homocysteine for full assessment. Treatment depends on cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Homocysteine (option B) is non-specific marker; serum folate (option C) is short-term; MCV (option D) is consequence not folate measure, none being as specific for long-term folate status as RBC folate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A strict vegan with neuropathy and anemia should receive:", "a": "Oral iron", "b": "Erythropoietin", "c": "Oral folate only", "d": "Intramuscular vitamin B12", "ans": "D", "e": "Intramuscular vitamin B12 treats vegan with neuropathy and anaemia; dietary B12 deficiency with neurological involvement requires parenteral therapy for adequate repletion.<br><br>Standard dose 1 mg intramuscularly every 2-3 days for 2 weeks (loading), then 1 mg every 3 months. Oral B12 (1000 mcg daily) alternative for dietary deficiency without neurology.<br><br>Oral iron (option A) does not address B12 deficiency; erythropoietin (option B) is for CKD anaemia; oral folate only (option C) is contraindicated in B12 deficiency, none being appropriate for vegan B12 deficiency with neuropathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which parasite predisposes to B12 deficiency?", "a": "Entamoeba histolytica", "b": "Giardia lamblia", "c": "Diphyllobothrium latum", "d": "Hookworm", "ans": "C", "e": "Diphyllobothrium latum (fish tapeworm) predisposes to B12 deficiency; this parasite competes with host for B12 absorption.<br><br>Diagnosis by stool examination for ova. Treatment with praziquantel. Combined with B12 replacement. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing parasitic from other causes of B12 deficiency. Geographic distribution mainly Northern Hemisphere.<br><br>Entamoeba histolytica (option A) causes amoebic colitis; Giardia lamblia (option B) causes diarrhoea and malabsorption but not B12 specifically; hookworm (option D) causes iron deficiency, none being the B12-specific parasitic association.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which cell line is affected earliest in megaloblastic anemia?", "a": "Lymphocytes", "b": "Neutrophils", "c": "Erythrocytes", "d": "Platelets", "ans": "B", "e": "Neutrophils are affected earliest in megaloblastic anaemia; hypersegmentation appears before macrocytosis or anaemia develops.<br><br>Mechanism involves impaired DNA synthesis affecting rapidly dividing cells preferentially. Combined with macro-ovalocytes appearing later and pancytopenia in severe disease. Treatment with B12 or folate replacement produces rapid haematological response. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Lymphocytes (option A) are not first affected; erythrocytes (option C) develop macrocytosis later; platelets (option D) reduce in severe disease, none being affected as early as neutrophil hypersegmentation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Failure of DNA synthesis in megaloblastic anemia results from deficiency of:", "a": "Cytosine", "b": "Adenine", "c": "Thymidine", "d": "Guanine", "ans": "C", "e": "Thymidine synthesis fails in megaloblastic anaemia; folate (and thus B12-dependent folate cycling) is required for thymidylate synthesis from dUMP to dTMP.<br><br>Mechanism includes thymidylate synthase requiring methylene-THF. B12 deficiency traps folate as methyl-THF preventing thymidylate synthesis. Treatment with B12 or folate replacement restores DNA synthesis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Cytosine (option A) synthesis is unaffected; adenine (option B) synthesis is unaffected; guanine (option D) synthesis is unaffected, none being folate-dependent like thymidine synthesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which therapy is contraindicated alone in suspected B12 deficiency?", "a": "Transfusion", "b": "Folate", "c": "Erythropoietin", "d": "Iron", "ans": "B", "e": "Folate alone is contraindicated in suspected B12 deficiency; corrects anaemia but allows B12 neurological disease to progress causing irreversible damage.<br><br>Always exclude B12 deficiency before starting folate. Replace B12 first if both deficient. Intramuscular hydroxocobalamin 1 mg every 2-3 days for 2 weeks (loading), then 1 mg every 3 months for life. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Transfusion (option A) is appropriate for severe symptoms; erythropoietin (option C) is for CKD; iron (option D) is for iron deficiency, none being contraindicated in suspected B12 deficiency like folate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Macrocytosis without anemia is commonly seen in:", "a": "Iron deficiency", "b": "Thalassemia", "c": "Lead poisoning", "d": "Alcoholism", "ans": "D", "e": "Alcoholism commonly produces macrocytosis without anaemia; alcohol directly toxic to erythroblasts producing macrocytosis with or without folate deficiency.<br><br>Combined with other macrocytosis causes including B12 or folate deficiency, hypothyroidism, liver disease, and myelodysplasia. Treatment includes alcohol cessation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Standard supportive care guides management. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) is microcytic; thalassaemia (option B) is microcytic; lead poisoning (option C) is microcytic, none producing macrocytosis like alcoholism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient develops anemia after prolonged PPI use. Mechanism:", "a": "Reduced gastric acid leading to impaired B12 release", "b": "Increased renal excretion", "c": "Marrow suppression", "d": "Reduced intrinsic factor activity", "ans": "A", "e": "Reduced gastric acid impairs B12 release from food protein; PPI suppression of acid prevents enzymatic cleavage of B12 from dietary protein.<br><br>Long-term PPI use (over 2 years) increases risk. Diagnosis by low serum B12 and elevated methylmalonic acid. Treatment with B12 supplementation or oral B12. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Increased renal excretion (option B) is not principal mechanism; marrow suppression (option C) is uncommon; reduced intrinsic factor (option D) is pernicious anaemia not PPI mechanism, none being the PPI-specific acid-mediated mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The Schilling test historically assessed:", "a": "Hemolysis", "b": "Iron absorption", "c": "Folate absorption", "d": "Vitamin B12 absorption", "ans": "D", "e": "The Schilling test assessed vitamin B12 absorption; oral radiolabelled B12 measured in 24-hour urine after intramuscular B12 saturated stores.<br><br>Stage 1: oral radiolabelled B12 alone. Stage 2: with intrinsic factor identifies pernicious anaemia. Stage 3: with antibiotics identifies bacterial overgrowth. Stage 4: with pancreatic enzymes identifies pancreatic insufficiency. Now rarely performed. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Haemolysis (option A) requires different tests; iron absorption (option B) requires different tests; folate absorption (option C) requires different tests, none being assessed by the Schilling test like B12 absorption.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In folate deficiency, neurological symptoms are absent because:", "a": "Folate stored in liver", "b": "Myelin unaffected by folate metabolism", "c": "Folate synthesized in marrow", "d": "Folate replaced by B12", "ans": "B", "e": "Myelin unaffected by folate metabolism explains absent neurological signs in folate deficiency; B12 is required for myelin synthesis through methylmalonyl-CoA mutase but folate alone is not.<br><br>Folate deficiency produces megaloblastic anaemia and glossitis without neurological involvement. Combined with elevated homocysteine and normal methylmalonic acid.<br><br>Folate stored in liver (option A) does not explain absent neurology; folate synthesised in marrow (option C) is incorrect; folate replaced by B12 (option D) is incorrect, none being the principal mechanism of absent neurological involvement in folate deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which population has highest risk of folate deficiency?", "a": "Alcoholics with malnutrition", "b": "Elderly with gastritis", "c": "Patients with CKD", "d": "Athletes", "ans": "A", "e": "Alcoholics with malnutrition have highest risk of folate deficiency; alcohol impairs folate metabolism, absorption, and intake.<br><br>Other high-risk groups include pregnancy (increased demand), patients on antifolate drugs (methotrexate, trimethoprim, phenytoin), and haemolytic anaemias (increased turnover). Treatment with oral folic acid 5 mg daily for 4 months. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Elderly with gastritis (option B) is mainly B12 risk; CKD patients (option C) is mainly EPO deficiency; athletes (option D) is uncommon, none being highest folate-deficiency risk like alcoholics with malnutrition.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Elevated LDH in megaloblastic anemia occurs due to:", "a": "Hemorrhage", "b": "Iron overload", "c": "Intramedullary RBC destruction", "d": "Infection", "ans": "C", "e": "Intramedullary RBC destruction elevates LDH in megaloblastic anaemia; ineffective haematopoiesis releases LDH from dying erythroblasts within bone marrow.<br><br>Combined with elevated indirect bilirubin and reticulocyte count not raised (distinguishing from true haemolysis). Distinguishing megaloblastic pseudohaemolysis from true haemolysis through bone marrow examination. Treatment with B12 or folate replacement. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Haemorrhage (option A) is unrelated to LDH; iron overload (option B) is in haemochromatosis; infection (option D) is non-specific, none being the megaloblastic-specific LDH elevation mechanism like intramedullary destruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The daily requirement of folic acid increases markedly in:", "a": "Pregnancy", "b": "Asthma", "c": "Hypertension", "d": "Diabetes", "ans": "A", "e": "Pregnancy markedly increases daily folic acid requirement; fetal growth and increased erythropoiesis demand higher folate intake.<br><br>Standard supplementation 400 mcg daily pre-conception and through first trimester prevents neural tube defects. Higher doses (5 mg daily) for women with previous affected pregnancy, diabetes, epilepsy on antiepileptics, sickle cell disease, or thalassaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician.<br><br>Asthma (option B) does not affect folate; hypertension (option C) does not affect folate; diabetes (option D) increases need only modestly, none increasing folate requirement as markedly as pregnancy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A macrocytic anemia patient has paresthesia and ataxia. Most appropriate initial test:", "a": "Serum iron", "b": "Serum vitamin B12", "c": "Reticulocyte count", "d": "Coombs test", "ans": "B", "e": "Serum vitamin B12 is most appropriate initial test; macrocytic anaemia with paraesthesia and ataxia suggests B12 deficiency requiring B12 measurement first.<br><br>Combined with serum folate, methylmalonic acid (elevated in B12 deficiency), and homocysteine. Treatment with intramuscular hydroxocobalamin for confirmed deficiency. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including neurologist. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Serum iron (option A) is for microcytic anaemia; reticulocyte count (option C) is for haemolysis assessment; Coombs test (option D) is for autoimmune haemolysis, none being the appropriate first test for macrocytic anaemia with neurology.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which feature favors B12 deficiency over folate deficiency?", "a": "Hypersegmented neutrophils", "b": "Glossitis", "c": "Macrocytosis", "d": "Neurological signs", "ans": "D", "e": "Neurological signs favour B12 deficiency over folate deficiency; folate deficiency lacks neurological complications.<br><br>Other features favouring B12 include hypersegmented neutrophils (occurring in both though), glossitis (both), and macrocytosis (both). Diagnosis by methylmalonic acid (elevated in B12 deficiency, normal in folate). Treatment with B12 first if both deficient. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Hypersegmented neutrophils (option A) occur in both; glossitis (option B) occurs in both; macrocytosis (option C) occurs in both, none being as distinguishing as neurological signs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Homocysteine elevation causes increased risk of:", "a": "Bleeding", "b": "Infection", "c": "Thrombosis", "d": "Hypoglycemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Homocysteine elevation increases thrombosis risk; hyperhomocysteinaemia damages endothelium promoting venous and arterial thrombosis.<br><br>Mechanism includes endothelial dysfunction, platelet activation, and coagulation pathway alteration. Treatment includes B12 and folate replacement reducing homocysteine. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Bleeding (option A) is opposite of thrombosis; infection (option B) is unrelated; hypoglycaemia (option D) is unrelated, none being the principal homocysteine-elevation risk like thrombosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with megaloblastic anemia shows pancytopenia. Mechanism:", "a": "Bone marrow failure", "b": "Ineffective hematopoiesis due to impaired DNA synthesis", "c": "Peripheral destruction", "d": "Splenic sequestration", "ans": "B", "e": "Ineffective haematopoiesis from impaired DNA synthesis causes pancytopenia in megaloblastic anaemia; affects all three lineages with intramedullary cell death.<br><br>Diagnosis by megaloblastic bone marrow with megaloblasts, giant metamyelocytes, and hypersegmented neutrophils. Treatment with B12 or folate replacement produces rapid haematological response. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Bone marrow failure (option A) is aplastic anaemia hypocellular; peripheral destruction (option C) is haemolysis or hypersplenism; splenic sequestration (option D) is hypersplenism, none being the megaloblastic-specific ineffective haematopoiesis mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which vitamin regenerates tetrahydrofolate from methyl-THF?", "a": "Vitamin B6", "b": "Vitamin D", "c": "Vitamin C", "d": "Vitamin B12", "ans": "D", "e": "Vitamin B12 regenerates tetrahydrofolate from methyl-THF; methionine synthase reaction uses methyl-B12 to transfer methyl group releasing THF for DNA synthesis.<br><br>B12 deficiency traps folate as methyl-THF (folate trap hypothesis) explaining megaloblastic anaemia in B12 deficiency. Treatment with B12 replacement restores reaction. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Vitamin B6 (option A) is for sideroblastic anaemia and homocysteine metabolism; vitamin D (option B) is for calcium; vitamin C (option C) is antioxidant, none regenerating THF from methyl-THF like B12.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The main storage site of vitamin B12 is:", "a": "Liver", "b": "Bone marrow", "c": "Spleen", "d": "Kidney", "ans": "A", "e": "Liver is the principal storage site of vitamin B12; total body B12 stores (2-5 mg) primarily hepatic.<br><br>Stores last 3-5 years explaining delayed presentation of B12 deficiency. Treatment with intramuscular hydroxocobalamin for deficiency. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing storage from circulating B12 explains gradual depletion.<br><br>Bone marrow (option B) is consumption site not storage; spleen (option C) is RBC destruction site; kidney (option D) is excretion, none being the principal B12 storage site like liver.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Megaloblastic anemia due to folate deficiency most commonly develops within:", "a": "Years", "b": "Weeks", "c": "Months", "d": "Days", "ans": "C", "e": "Folate deficiency anaemia develops within months; folate stores (5-10 mg total) deplete in 4-5 months with inadequate intake.<br><br>Distinguishing from B12 deficiency (years) which has 3-5 year stores. Treatment with oral folic acid 5 mg daily for 4 months. Combined with addressing underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Years (option A) is for B12 deficiency; weeks (option B) is too rapid; days (option D) is too rapid, none being the typical folate deficiency timeframe like months.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which hematologic change occurs after effective B12 therapy?", "a": "Immediate platelet normalization", "b": "Reticulocytosis followed by Hb rise", "c": "Immediate WBC normalization", "d": "Immediate MCV normalization", "ans": "B", "e": "Reticulocytosis followed by Hb rise is the expected response to effective B12 therapy; bone marrow responds within 5-7 days before haemoglobin normalisation.<br><br>Reticulocyte peak at 5-10 days. Haemoglobin rises by 1 g/dL per week. MCV normalises over weeks. Hypersegmented neutrophils persist for 2 weeks. Hypokalaemia may complicate rapid haematopoiesis. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Immediate platelet normalisation (option A) is later; immediate WBC normalisation (option C) is later; immediate MCV normalisation (option D) is later, none being the early B12 therapy response like reticulocytosis followed by Hb rise.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which condition causes functional folate deficiency despite normal folate levels?", "a": "Hemolytic anemia", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Vitamin B12 deficiency", "d": "Thalassemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Vitamin B12 deficiency causes functional folate deficiency despite normal folate levels; folate trap hypothesis explains this phenomenon.<br><br>Mechanism includes B12-dependent methionine synthase converting methyl-THF and homocysteine to THF and methionine. B12 deficiency traps folate as methyl-THF reducing THF available for DNA synthesis. Treatment with B12 replacement releases trapped folate. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemolytic anaemia (option A) increases folate consumption causing actual deficiency; iron deficiency (option B) is unrelated to folate; thalassaemia (option D) is unrelated to folate, none causing functional folate deficiency with normal levels like B12 deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 19-year-old male presents with sudden onset pallor, jaundice and dark urine after taking antimalarial medication. Hb dropped rapidly within 24 hours, LDH markedly elevated, indirect bilirubin high and haptoglobin undetectable. Which mechanism best explains this acute hemolysis?", "a": "Immune mediated RBC destruction", "b": "Membrane cytoskeleton defect", "c": "Ineffective erythropoiesis", "d": "Oxidative damage to erythrocytes", "ans": "D", "e": "Oxidative damage to erythrocytes causes acute haemolysis after antimalarial; G6PD deficiency reduces NADPH and glutathione regeneration making red cells vulnerable to oxidative drugs like primaquine.<br><br>Diagnosis by enzyme assay (may be falsely normal during acute haemolysis as deficient older cells lysed first). Heinz bodies and bite cells on smear. Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care.<br><br>Immune-mediated destruction (option A) features positive Coombs; membrane cytoskeleton defect (option B) is hereditary spherocytosis with spherocytes; ineffective erythropoiesis (option C) is megaloblastic, none fitting drug-triggered acute oxidative haemolysis like G6PD deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with chronic anemia has persistent splenomegaly, mild jaundice and pigment gallstones since childhood. Peripheral smear shows numerous spherocytes and MCHC increased. The primary structural defect involves:", "a": "Ankyrin–spectrin cytoskeleton interaction", "b": "Ferrochelatase activity", "c": "Complement inhibition", "d": "Hemoglobin globin chain synthesis", "ans": "A", "e": "Ankyrin-spectrin cytoskeleton interaction defect causes hereditary spherocytosis; impaired vertical membrane support produces spherocytes with elevated MCHC, chronic haemolysis, splenomegaly, and pigment stones.<br><br>Diagnosis by family history, peripheral smear, increased osmotic fragility, and EMA binding test. Genetic testing for ankyrin, spectrin, band 3, or protein 4.2 mutations. Treatment includes folate supplementation, splenectomy for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Ferrochelatase activity (option B) defect is sideroblastic anaemia; complement inhibition (option C) defect is PNH; haemoglobin globin synthesis (option D) defect is thalassaemia, none being the membrane skeleton defect of hereditary spherocytosis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which laboratory profile is most consistent with ongoing hemolysis in a stable outpatient with compensated anemia?", "a": "Increased ferritin only", "b": "High haptoglobin and low LDH", "c": "Elevated LDH with reticulocytosis and low haptoglobin", "d": "Low reticulocyte count", "ans": "C", "e": "Elevated LDH with reticulocytosis and low haptoglobin confirms ongoing haemolysis; this classical laboratory triad reflects red cell breakdown with marrow compensation.<br><br>Combined with elevated indirect bilirubin. Distinguishing intravascular (markedly elevated LDH, undetectable haptoglobin, haemoglobinuria) from extravascular (mild LDH elevation, mild haptoglobin reduction). Treatment depends on cause. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Increased ferritin only (option A) is iron overload or ACD; high haptoglobin with low LDH (option B) is opposite; low reticulocyte count (option D) is bone marrow failure not haemolysis, none confirming active haemolysis like this triad.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient develops anemia one week after starting penicillin therapy. Direct Coombs test is positive. The mechanism of drug-induced hemolysis is most consistent with:", "a": "Hapten mediated antibody formation", "b": "RBC enzyme deficiency", "c": "Oxidative injury", "d": "Complement deficiency", "ans": "A", "e": "Hapten-mediated antibody formation causes penicillin-induced immune haemolysis; high-dose penicillin binds covalently to red cell membrane proteins acting as a hapten triggering antibody production.<br><br>Direct Coombs test positive for IgG. Treatment includes drug discontinuation and supportive care. Most cases resolve within weeks. Combined with avoidance of related beta-lactams. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>RBC enzyme deficiency (option B) is G6PD or pyruvate kinase; oxidative injury (option C) is G6PD; complement deficiency (option D) is opposite (PNH features complement sensitivity), none being the penicillin-specific hapten mechanism.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In chronic extravascular hemolysis, bilirubin elevation occurs primarily because of:", "a": "Reduced hepatic uptake", "b": "Decreased albumin binding", "c": "Increased conjugation", "d": "Increased heme breakdown in macrophages", "ans": "D", "e": "Increased haem breakdown in macrophages elevates bilirubin in extravascular haemolysis; splenic and hepatic macrophages phagocytose abnormal red cells producing unconjugated bilirubin from haem.<br><br>Combined with elevated indirect bilirubin (unconjugated), mildly elevated LDH, mildly reduced haptoglobin, and reticulocytosis. Treatment depends on cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Reduced hepatic uptake (option A) is Gilbert syndrome; decreased albumin binding (option B) is uncommon; increased conjugation (option C) is opposite mechanism, none being the principal extravascular haemolysis bilirubin mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A young woman presents in winter with acrocyanosis, fatigue and anemia. RBC agglutination occurs at 4°C and Coombs test positive for complement only. The most likely diagnosis is:", "a": "Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria", "b": "Cold agglutinin disease", "c": "Warm autoimmune hemolytic anemia", "d": "Hereditary elliptocytosis", "ans": "B", "e": "Cold agglutinin disease fits acrocyanosis and anaemia in winter with cold-temperature agglutination and complement-only Coombs; IgM antibodies bind red cells at low temperatures activating complement.<br><br>Causes include idiopathic, lymphoproliferative disorders, Mycoplasma pneumoniae, and EBV. Treatment includes cold avoidance, treating underlying cause, and rituximab for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Paroxysmal nocturnal haemoglobinuria (option A) features morning haemoglobinuria and CD55/CD59 deficiency; warm AIHA (option C) features IgG at 37°C; hereditary elliptocytosis (option D) features elliptocytes, none fitting this cold-temperature complement-only pattern.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The most useful confirmatory test for autoimmune hemolytic anemia is:", "a": "Bone marrow biopsy", "b": "Osmotic fragility test", "c": "Hemoglobin electrophoresis", "d": "Direct antiglobulin (Coombs) test", "ans": "D", "e": "Direct antiglobulin (Coombs) test is most useful for confirming autoimmune haemolytic anaemia; this detects antibodies or complement on red cell surface.<br><br>IgG positive in warm AIHA. C3 positive in cold AIHA. Both positive in mixed AIHA. Combined with reticulocyte count, LDH, indirect bilirubin, and haptoglobin to confirm haemolysis. Treatment depends on type and underlying cause.<br><br>Bone marrow biopsy (option A) is unnecessary for AIHA; osmotic fragility (option B) is for hereditary spherocytosis; haemoglobin electrophoresis (option C) is for haemoglobinopathies, none being as specific for AIHA confirmation as direct Coombs.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In hereditary spherocytosis, increased osmotic fragility occurs because RBCs have:", "a": "Increased hemoglobin concentration", "b": "Increased ATP production", "c": "Reduced surface area to volume ratio", "d": "Excess membrane surface area", "ans": "C", "e": "Reduced surface area to volume ratio causes increased osmotic fragility in hereditary spherocytosis; spherical shape (instead of biconcave disc) reduces capacity to swell before lysis in hypotonic solution.<br><br>Mechanism includes membrane skeleton defect causing membrane loss with maintained volume producing spherical morphology. Diagnosis by EMA binding test or osmotic fragility.<br><br>Increased haemoglobin concentration (option A) is consequence not cause; increased ATP production (option B) is unrelated; excess membrane surface (option D) is opposite, none being the mechanism of fragility like reduced surface to volume ratio.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which feature favors chronic hemolysis over acute blood loss?", "a": "Reticulocytopenia", "b": "Elevated indirect bilirubin", "c": "Normal urobilinogen", "d": "Low LDH", "ans": "B", "e": "Elevated indirect bilirubin favours chronic haemolysis over acute blood loss; red cell breakdown releases haem producing unconjugated bilirubin while acute blood loss lacks bilirubin elevation.<br><br>Combined with elevated LDH, reduced haptoglobin, reticulocytosis, and clinical features. Treatment depends on cause. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing chronic haemolysis from acute blood loss guides investigation.<br><br>Reticulocytopenia (option A) is bone marrow failure not haemolysis; normal urobilinogen (option C) is opposite (elevated in haemolysis); low LDH (option D) is opposite (elevated in haemolysis), none favouring haemolysis like elevated indirect bilirubin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with warm autoimmune hemolytic anemia is treated initially with:", "a": "Corticosteroids", "b": "Splenectomy", "c": "Iron therapy", "d": "Erythropoietin", "ans": "A", "e": "Corticosteroids are first-line for warm autoimmune haemolytic anaemia; prednisolone 1 mg/kg daily reduces antibody production and macrophage Fc receptor function.<br><br>Standard taper over 3-6 months as Hb stabilises. Refractory or steroid-dependent disease may require rituximab, splenectomy, or other immunosuppression (azathioprine, cyclophosphamide). Folate supplementation supports erythropoiesis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Splenectomy (option B) is second-line; iron therapy (option C) is for iron deficiency; erythropoietin (option D) is for CKD anaemia, none being first-line for warm AIHA like corticosteroids.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hereditary spherocytosis most commonly presents with which triad?", "a": "Cyanosis, clubbing, edema", "b": "Anemia, jaundice, splenomegaly", "c": "Fever, rash, arthralgia", "d": "Pallor, neuropathy, glossitis", "ans": "B", "e": "Anaemia, jaundice, and splenomegaly form the classical hereditary spherocytosis triad; chronic extravascular haemolysis produces all three features.<br><br>Autosomal dominant defect in red cell membrane proteins (ankyrin, spectrin, band 3, protein 4.2). Diagnosis by family history, peripheral smear showing spherocytes, increased osmotic fragility, and EMA binding test. Treatment includes folate supplementation, splenectomy for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Cyanosis-clubbing-oedema (option A) is cardiopulmonary; fever-rash-arthralgia (option C) is infectious or autoimmune; pallor-neuropathy-glossitis (option D) is B12 deficiency, none being the classical hereditary spherocytosis triad.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In intravascular hemolysis, hemoglobinuria occurs because:", "a": "Hemoglobin released directly into plasma exceeding haptoglobin binding", "b": "Decreased erythropoietin", "c": "RBCs destroyed in spleen", "d": "Increased bilirubin conjugation", "ans": "A", "e": "Haemoglobin released directly into plasma exceeding haptoglobin binding capacity causes haemoglobinuria in intravascular haemolysis; free haemoglobin filtered by glomerulus when haptoglobin saturated.<br><br>Causes include G6PD deficiency, PNH, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, transfusion reactions, and severe trauma. Diagnosis by elevated LDH, low haptoglobin, haemoglobinuria, and haemoglobinaemia. Treatment depends on cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Decreased erythropoietin (option B) is renal disease; RBCs destroyed in spleen (option C) is extravascular; increased bilirubin conjugation (option D) is liver function, none being the intravascular haemoglobinuria mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which complication commonly develops in chronic hemolytic anemia due to increased bilirubin turnover?", "a": "Uric acid nephropathy", "b": "Calcium oxalate stones", "c": "Pigment gallstones", "d": "Renal stones", "ans": "C", "e": "Pigment gallstones develop in chronic haemolytic anaemia; increased bilirubin turnover supersaturates bile producing black pigment stones (calcium bilirubinate).<br><br>Treatment includes laparoscopic cholecystectomy for symptomatic disease. Combined with addressing underlying haemolysis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Uric acid nephropathy (option A) is tumour lysis; calcium oxalate stones (option B) are dietary or metabolic; renal stones (option D) are non-specific, none being the chronic-haemolysis bilirubin-turnover specific complication like pigment gallstones.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Cold agglutinin disease is most commonly associated with infection by:", "a": "Streptococcus pyogenes", "b": "Staphylococcus aureus", "c": "Salmonella typhi", "d": "Mycoplasma pneumoniae", "ans": "D", "e": "Mycoplasma pneumoniae is most commonly associated with cold agglutinin disease; this atypical pneumonia produces transient anti-I cold agglutinins.<br><br>Other associations include EBV (anti-i specificity), idiopathic, and lymphoproliferative disorders. Diagnosis by direct Coombs test positive for C3, elevated cold agglutinin titre, and Mycoplasma serology. Treatment of underlying infection. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Streptococcus pyogenes (option A) causes pharyngitis and rheumatic fever; Staphylococcus aureus (option B) is unrelated; Salmonella typhi (option C) causes typhoid, none being the principal cold agglutinin disease association.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In hereditary spherocytosis, definitive treatment for severe disease is:", "a": "Iron supplementation", "b": "Chemotherapy", "c": "Splenectomy", "d": "Plasma exchange", "ans": "C", "e": "Splenectomy is definitive treatment for severe hereditary spherocytosis; removes site of red cell destruction.<br><br>Indications include severe haemolysis, transfusion dependence, and growth retardation in children. Pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib vaccinations before splenectomy. Long-term penicillin prophylaxis. Combined with folate supplementation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Iron supplementation (option A) is for iron deficiency and contraindicated risking overload; chemotherapy (option B) is for malignancy; plasma exchange (option D) is for TTP or hyperviscosity, none being the hereditary spherocytosis definitive treatment.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient presents with anemia, high reticulocyte count and negative Coombs test but increased osmotic fragility. Diagnosis:", "a": "Hereditary spherocytosis", "b": "Autoimmune hemolysis", "c": "Thalassemia", "d": "Iron deficiency", "ans": "A", "e": "Hereditary spherocytosis fits high reticulocytes, negative Coombs, and increased osmotic fragility; membrane defect produces non-immune extravascular haemolysis.<br><br>Autosomal dominant defect in red cell membrane proteins (ankyrin, spectrin, band 3, protein 4.2). Diagnosis by family history, peripheral smear showing spherocytes, increased osmotic fragility, and EMA binding test. Treatment includes folate supplementation, splenectomy for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Autoimmune haemolysis (option B) features positive Coombs; thalassaemia (option C) features microcytosis and elevated HbA2; iron deficiency (option D) features low ferritin, none fitting the Coombs-negative high-osmotic-fragility pattern of hereditary spherocytosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which laboratory marker decreases significantly in intravascular hemolysis due to binding free hemoglobin?", "a": "Transferrin", "b": "Ferritin", "c": "Albumin", "d": "Haptoglobin", "ans": "D", "e": "Haptoglobin decreases significantly in intravascular haemolysis; this plasma protein binds free haemoglobin and the complex is rapidly cleared producing low or undetectable levels.<br><br>Causes include G6PD deficiency, PNH, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, transfusion reactions, and severe trauma. Diagnosis by elevated LDH, low haptoglobin, haemoglobinuria, and haemoglobinaemia. Treatment depends on cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Transferrin (option A) transports iron; ferritin (option B) stores iron; albumin (option C) is general transport, none being the free-haemoglobin-binding marker that decreases in intravascular haemolysis like haptoglobin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In warm autoimmune hemolysis, antibodies are typically:", "a": "IgE mediated", "b": "IgG active at body temperature", "c": "IgM active at cold temperature", "d": "IgA secretory", "ans": "B", "e": "IgG active at body temperature characterises warm autoimmune haemolytic anaemia; these antibodies bind red cells optimally at 37°C producing extravascular haemolysis in spleen.<br><br>Diagnosis by direct Coombs test positive for IgG with or without C3. Causes include idiopathic, lymphoproliferative disorders (CLL, lymphoma), autoimmune disease (SLE), and drugs. Treatment with corticosteroids first-line. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>IgE-mediated (option A) is allergic reactions; IgM active at cold (option C) is cold agglutinin disease; IgA secretory (option D) is mucosal immunity, none being warm AIHA antibody characteristics.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child with hereditary spherocytosis requires folate supplementation because of:", "a": "Increased erythropoiesis", "b": "Drug interaction", "c": "Renal loss", "d": "Malabsorption", "ans": "A", "e": "Increased erythropoiesis demands folate supplementation in hereditary spherocytosis; accelerated red cell turnover requires increased folate for compensatory erythropoiesis.<br><br>Standard dose folic acid 5 mg daily. Combined with treatment of underlying haemolysis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing increased demand from absolute deficiency.<br><br>Drug interaction (option B) is not the principal cause; renal loss (option C) is uncommon; malabsorption (option D) is not principal in hereditary spherocytosis, none explaining folate need like increased erythropoiesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which finding strongly suggests intravascular rather than extravascular hemolysis?", "a": "Spherocytes", "b": "Splenomegaly", "c": "Gallstones", "d": "Hemoglobinuria", "ans": "D", "e": "Haemoglobinuria strongly suggests intravascular rather than extravascular haemolysis; free haemoglobin filtered by glomerulus when haptoglobin saturated.<br><br>Causes include G6PD deficiency, PNH, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, transfusion reactions, and severe trauma. Diagnosis by elevated LDH, low haptoglobin, haemoglobinuria, and haemoglobinaemia. Treatment depends on cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Spherocytes (option A) suggest hereditary spherocytosis or warm AIHA (extravascular); splenomegaly (option B) suggests extravascular; gallstones (option C) suggest chronic haemolysis but not intravascular specifically, none being as specific for intravascular as haemoglobinuria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Drug-induced immune hemolysis due to methyldopa resembles:", "a": "G6PD deficiency", "b": "Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria", "c": "Warm autoimmune hemolytic anemia", "d": "Cold agglutinin disease", "ans": "C", "e": "Methyldopa-induced haemolysis resembles warm autoimmune haemolytic anaemia; this drug produces IgG antibodies binding red cells at body temperature with extravascular haemolysis.<br><br>Diagnosis by direct Coombs test positive for IgG. Treatment includes drug discontinuation and supportive care. Most cases resolve within weeks. Combined with avoidance of related drugs. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>G6PD deficiency (option A) features oxidative haemolysis; PNH (option B) features intravascular complement-mediated; cold agglutinin disease (option D) features IgM at low temperature, none being the methyldopa-warm-AIHA-resembling mechanism.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Reticulocyte count in chronic hemolytic anemia is typically:", "a": "Decreased", "b": "Increased", "c": "Normal", "d": "Absent", "ans": "B", "e": "Reticulocyte count is increased in chronic haemolytic anaemia; bone marrow responds to red cell loss with compensatory erythropoiesis.<br><br>Combined with elevated LDH, low haptoglobin, elevated indirect bilirubin, and clinical features. Reticulocyte index over 2 percent supports haemolysis. Reduced reticulocyte count suggests bone marrow failure or aplastic crisis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Decreased (option A) is bone marrow failure not haemolysis; normal (option C) excludes active haemolysis; absent (option D) is severe failure, none being characteristic of haemolysis like increased reticulocytes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which protein provides vertical support to RBC membrane and is deficient in hereditary spherocytosis?", "a": "Complement C3", "b": "Transferrin", "c": "Globin", "d": "Spectrin", "ans": "D", "e": "Spectrin deficiency provides vertical support and is deficient in hereditary spherocytosis; this principal cytoskeletal protein anchors membrane via ankyrin.<br><br>Other affected proteins include ankyrin (most common), band 3, and protein 4.2. Diagnosis by family history, peripheral smear showing spherocytes, increased osmotic fragility, and EMA binding test. Treatment includes folate supplementation, splenectomy for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Complement C3 (option A) is for opsonisation; transferrin (option B) transports iron; globin (option C) makes haemoglobin (thalassaemia), none being the membrane skeleton protein deficient in hereditary spherocytosis like spectrin.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Extravascular hemolysis primarily occurs in:", "a": "Kidneys", "b": "Liver and spleen macrophages", "c": "Plasma circulation", "d": "Bone marrow", "ans": "B", "e": "Liver and spleen macrophages phagocytose abnormal red cells in extravascular haemolysis; reticuloendothelial system removes opsonised or membrane-defective cells.<br><br>Splenic macrophages target antibody-coated red cells (warm AIHA) and spherocytes (hereditary spherocytosis). Liver macrophages target complement-coated red cells (cold agglutinin disease). Diagnosis depends on underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Kidneys (option A) filter free haemoglobin from intravascular haemolysis; plasma circulation (option C) is intravascular haemolysis site; bone marrow (option D) is for ineffective haematopoiesis, none being principal extravascular haemolysis site like liver-spleen macrophages.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The direct Coombs test detects:", "a": "Hemoglobin variants", "b": "Complement levels in plasma", "c": "Antibodies bound to RBC surface", "d": "Free antibodies in serum", "ans": "C", "e": "Direct Coombs test detects antibodies bound to RBC surface; anti-human globulin reagent agglutinates red cells coated with IgG or C3.<br><br>Positive in warm AIHA (IgG), cold agglutinin disease (C3), drug-induced haemolysis, haemolytic disease of newborn, and transfusion reactions. Indirect Coombs test detects free antibodies in serum. Combined for full antibody assessment.<br><br>Haemoglobin variants (option A) require electrophoresis; complement levels in plasma (option B) require complement assay; free antibodies in serum (option D) is indirect Coombs, none being detected by direct Coombs like RBC-bound antibodies.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In cold agglutinin disease, hemolysis worsens in cold because antibodies:", "a": "Activate complement at low temperature", "b": "Increase RBC production", "c": "Reduce bilirubin", "d": "Destroy RBC enzymes", "ans": "A", "e": "IgM antibodies activate complement at low temperatures in cold agglutinin disease; cold exposure allows IgM binding red cell antigens triggering complement-mediated haemolysis.<br><br>Mechanism includes IgM binding red cell antigens at 4°C, complement activation, and red cell destruction. Treatment includes cold avoidance, treating underlying cause (Mycoplasma, lymphoma), and rituximab for severe disease.<br><br>Increase RBC production (option B) is opposite of disease; reduce bilirubin (option C) is opposite; destroy RBC enzymes (option D) is G6PD mechanism, none being the cold agglutinin specific mechanism like cold-temperature complement activation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with hereditary spherocytosis develops aplastic crisis after parvovirus infection because:", "a": "Iron deficiency", "b": "Increased hemolysis", "c": "Splenic rupture", "d": "Temporary suppression of erythropoiesis", "ans": "D", "e": "Temporary suppression of erythropoiesis causes aplastic crisis in hereditary spherocytosis after parvovirus infection; parvovirus B19 infects erythroid precursors halting red cell production while haemolysis continues.<br><br>Diagnosis by parvovirus B19 PCR in blood, anti-parvovirus B19 IgM serology. Treatment with IVIG and supportive care. Bone marrow recovery follows clearance. Combined with addressing underlying haemolytic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) is unrelated; increased haemolysis (option B) is opposite mechanism; splenic rupture (option C) is unrelated, none being the parvovirus-aplastic-crisis mechanism like erythropoiesis suppression.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which investigation differentiates hereditary spherocytosis from autoimmune hemolysis?", "a": "Coombs test", "b": "Bilirubin level", "c": "Osmotic fragility test", "d": "Peripheral smear", "ans": "A", "e": "Coombs test differentiates hereditary spherocytosis from autoimmune haemolysis; negative in hereditary spherocytosis (membrane defect) and positive in autoimmune haemolysis (antibody-mediated).<br><br>Combined with peripheral smear showing spherocytes in both, osmotic fragility test, and EMA binding test for hereditary spherocytosis. Treatment differs significantly. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Bilirubin level (option B) elevated in both; osmotic fragility (option C) may be elevated in both (warm AIHA from spherocytes); peripheral smear (option D) shows spherocytes in both, none being as differentiating as Coombs test.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Warm autoimmune hemolysis usually causes:", "a": "Intravascular hemolysis only", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Extravascular splenic hemolysis", "d": "Bone marrow failure", "ans": "C", "e": "Extravascular splenic haemolysis usually occurs in warm autoimmune haemolysis; IgG-coated red cells removed by splenic macrophages.<br><br>Diagnosis by direct Coombs test positive for IgG. Causes include idiopathic, lymphoproliferative disorders (CLL, lymphoma), autoimmune disease (SLE), and drugs. Treatment with corticosteroids first-line, rituximab or splenectomy second-line. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Intravascular haemolysis only (option A) is uncommon for warm AIHA; iron deficiency (option B) is unrelated; bone marrow failure (option D) is aplastic anaemia, none being the warm AIHA principal mechanism like extravascular splenic.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In hemolytic anemia, elevated urobilinogen in urine occurs due to:", "a": "Reduced bilirubin formation", "b": "Increased bilirubin production", "c": "Renal failure", "d": "Hepatic obstruction", "ans": "B", "e": "Increased bilirubin production elevates urinary urobilinogen in haemolysis; excess bilirubin reaches gut, converted to urobilinogen, reabsorbed and excreted via kidney.<br><br>Combined with elevated indirect bilirubin in serum, elevated LDH, reduced haptoglobin, and reticulocytosis. Treatment depends on underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Reduced bilirubin formation (option A) is opposite; renal failure (option C) reduces urobilinogen excretion; hepatic obstruction (option D) reduces gut bilirubin, none being the haemolysis-specific urinary urobilinogen mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with severe hemolysis shows back pain, hemoglobinuria and renal impairment. This pattern suggests:", "a": "Megaloblastic anemia", "b": "Extravascular hemolysis", "c": "Aplastic anemia", "d": "Intravascular hemolysis", "ans": "D", "e": "Intravascular haemolysis features back pain, haemoglobinuria, and renal impairment; free haemoglobin in plasma exceeds haptoglobin binding causing renal toxicity.<br><br>Causes include severe ABO incompatibility, severe G6PD deficiency, PNH, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, and severe trauma. Diagnosis by elevated LDH, undetectable haptoglobin, haemoglobinuria, and haemoglobinaemia. Treatment includes IV fluids, supportive care, and addressing cause. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Megaloblastic anaemia (option A) is ineffective haematopoiesis; extravascular haemolysis (option B) lacks haemoglobinuria; aplastic anaemia (option C) is bone marrow failure, none fitting this severe-intravascular-haemolysis-with-renal pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which complication follows long-standing hemolytic anemia due to marrow expansion?", "a": "Bone deformities", "b": "Osteoporosis", "c": "Rickets", "d": "Hypercalcemia", "ans": "A", "e": "Bone deformities follow long-standing haemolytic anaemia from marrow expansion; compensatory erythropoiesis expands medullary cavities producing skull and facial bone changes.<br><br>Features include frontal bossing, malar prominence, maxillary overgrowth (chipmunk facies), and hair-on-end skull X-ray appearance. Most prominent in beta thalassaemia major. Treatment with regular transfusion suppresses expansion. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Osteoporosis (option B) is bone density loss not deformity; rickets (option C) is vitamin D deficiency; hypercalcaemia (option D) is bone resorption disorder, none being the marrow-expansion deformity mechanism of chronic haemolytic anaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Cold agglutinin antibodies are typically of which class?", "a": "IgE", "b": "IgM", "c": "IgA", "d": "IgG", "ans": "B", "e": "IgM is the antibody class of cold agglutinins; this pentameric immunoglobulin binds red cells optimally at cold temperatures activating complement.<br><br>Causes include idiopathic, lymphoproliferative disorders, Mycoplasma pneumoniae, and EBV. Diagnosis by direct Coombs test positive for C3 (not IgM directly as IgM dissociates), elevated cold agglutinin titre. Treatment includes cold avoidance, treating underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>IgE (option A) is allergic reactions; IgA (option C) is mucosal immunity; IgG (option D) is warm AIHA, none being the cold agglutinin specific antibody class.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Best supportive measure in cold agglutinin disease:", "a": "Splenectomy", "b": "Cold exposure", "c": "Warm clothing and avoidance of cold", "d": "Iron therapy", "ans": "C", "e": "Warm clothing and avoidance of cold is best supportive measure for cold agglutinin disease; cold exposure precipitates haemolysis.<br><br>Combined with treating underlying cause (Mycoplasma, lymphoma) and rituximab for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing supportive from disease-modifying therapy.<br><br>Splenectomy (option A) is ineffective in cold AIHA (liver Kupffer cells phagocytose C3-coated cells); cold exposure (option B) is opposite; iron therapy (option D) is for iron deficiency, none being the cold AIHA supportive measure like warmth.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hereditary spherocytosis cells are trapped in spleen because:", "a": "Increased size", "b": "Reduced deformability", "c": "Decreased hemoglobin", "d": "Increased flexibility", "ans": "B", "e": "Reduced deformability traps hereditary spherocytosis cells in spleen; spherical shape lacks the flexibility needed to traverse splenic cords and sinusoids.<br><br>Splenic macrophages phagocytose trapped cells producing extravascular haemolysis. Treatment includes folate supplementation, splenectomy for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Increased size (option A) is uncommon (cells are smaller); decreased haemoglobin (option C) is opposite (MCHC elevated); increased flexibility (option D) is opposite, none being the splenic-trapping mechanism like reduced deformability.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Indirect bilirubin increases in hemolysis because it is:", "a": "Filtered in urine", "b": "Produced in kidney", "c": "Conjugated in spleen", "d": "Released from heme breakdown faster than liver conjugation", "ans": "D", "e": "Indirect bilirubin rises in haemolysis because it is released from haem breakdown faster than liver conjugation; rapid red cell breakdown overwhelms hepatic conjugation capacity.<br><br>Combined with elevated LDH, reduced haptoglobin, and reticulocytosis. Distinguishing from Gilbert syndrome (reduced UGT1A1 activity) and Crigler-Najjar through clinical context and reticulocyte count. Treatment depends on underlying cause.<br><br>Filtered in urine (option A) is direct bilirubin; produced in kidney (option B) is incorrect; conjugated in spleen (option C) is incorrect, none being the haemolysis indirect bilirubin mechanism like haem breakdown overwhelming conjugation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which anemia improves dramatically after splenectomy?", "a": "Iron deficiency anemia", "b": "Cold agglutinin disease", "c": "Hereditary spherocytosis", "d": "Warm autoimmune hemolysis", "ans": "C", "e": "Hereditary spherocytosis improves dramatically after splenectomy; removing site of red cell destruction reverses haemolysis without correcting membrane defect.<br><br>Indications include severe haemolysis, transfusion dependence, and growth retardation in children. Pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib vaccinations before splenectomy. Long-term penicillin prophylaxis. Combined with folate supplementation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Iron deficiency anaemia (option A) requires iron not splenectomy; cold agglutinin disease (option B) responds poorly to splenectomy (liver Kupffer cells); warm AIHA (option D) has variable response, none responding as dramatically as hereditary spherocytosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In autoimmune hemolysis, spherocytes form because macrophages remove:", "a": "Membrane fragments", "b": "Hemoglobin", "c": "Nucleus", "d": "Whole RBC", "ans": "A", "e": "Membrane fragments are removed by macrophages forming spherocytes in autoimmune haemolysis; antibody-coated cell membrane partially phagocytosed leaves spherical residue.<br><br>Mechanism includes IgG-coated red cells with Fc receptor binding on splenic macrophages. Treatment with corticosteroids first-line, rituximab or splenectomy second-line. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Haemoglobin (option B) is not removed by macrophages individually; nucleus (option C) is removed during normal RBC maturation; whole RBC (option D) is complete phagocytosis not spherocyte formation, none being the spherocyte-formation mechanism like membrane fragment removal.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Positive Coombs test with complement only suggests:", "a": "Thalassemia", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Cold agglutinin disease", "d": "Warm antibody hemolysis", "ans": "C", "e": "Cold agglutinin disease produces positive Coombs test with complement only; IgM dissociates leaving C3 on red cell surface.<br><br>Diagnosis by direct Coombs test positive for C3, elevated cold agglutinin titre. Causes include idiopathic, lymphoproliferative disorders, Mycoplasma pneumoniae, and EBV. Treatment includes cold avoidance, treating underlying cause, and rituximab for severe disease.<br><br>Thalassaemia (option A) is Coombs negative; iron deficiency (option B) is Coombs negative; warm antibody haemolysis (option D) is IgG positive (with or without C3), none producing complement-only Coombs like cold agglutinin disease.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Chronic hemolysis leads to increased requirement of:", "a": "Folate", "b": "Vitamin C", "c": "Iron", "d": "Calcium", "ans": "A", "e": "Folate requirement increases in chronic haemolysis; accelerated erythropoiesis demands increased folate for compensatory red cell production.<br><br>Standard supplementation folic acid 5 mg daily in chronic haemolytic anaemias. Combined with treatment of underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing increased demand from absolute deficiency.<br><br>Vitamin C (option B) is not principally increased; iron (option C) is contraindicated in haemolytic anaemias risking overload; calcium (option D) is not principally increased, none being the haemolysis-related supplementation need like folate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which condition presents with episodic dark urine in morning due to complement mediated lysis?", "a": "Autoimmune hemolysis", "b": "Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria", "c": "G6PD deficiency", "d": "Hereditary spherocytosis", "ans": "B", "e": "Paroxysmal nocturnal haemoglobinuria presents with episodic morning dark urine from complement-mediated lysis; PIG-A mutation reduces GPI-anchor proteins (CD55, CD59) making red cells complement-sensitive.<br><br>Diagnosis by flow cytometry showing reduced CD55 and CD59 on red cells. Treatment with eculizumab (anti-C5 monoclonal antibody) blocks complement. Bone marrow transplantation curative. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Autoimmune haemolysis (option A) is Coombs positive without nocturnal pattern; G6PD deficiency (option C) is drug-triggered; hereditary spherocytosis (option D) features chronic disease, none fitting the PNH episodic morning haemoglobinuria pattern.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In hereditary spherocytosis, MCHC is typically:", "a": "Normal", "b": "Absent", "c": "Decreased", "d": "Increased", "ans": "D", "e": "MCHC is increased in hereditary spherocytosis; spherical shape concentrates haemoglobin in reduced cell volume producing characteristically elevated MCHC.<br><br>Mechanism includes membrane skeleton defect causing membrane loss with maintained haemoglobin. Diagnosis by family history, peripheral smear showing spherocytes, increased osmotic fragility, EMA binding test, and elevated MCHC. Treatment includes folate supplementation, splenectomy for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Normal (option A) excludes hereditary spherocytosis; absent (option B) is incorrect; decreased (option C) is opposite (iron deficiency), none being characteristic of hereditary spherocytosis like increased MCHC.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with hemolytic anemia develops leg ulcers due to:", "a": "Infection", "b": "Chronic hypoxia", "c": "Hypercalcemia", "d": "Iron overload", "ans": "B", "e": "Chronic hypoxia produces leg ulcers in haemolytic anaemia; impaired oxygen delivery to skin causes ischaemic ulceration particularly in lower extremities.<br><br>Common in sickle cell disease, thalassaemia, and severe chronic haemolytic anaemias. Treatment includes addressing underlying anaemia, wound care, and compression therapy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Infection (option A) is secondary not principal cause; hypercalcaemia (option C) is unrelated; iron overload (option D) is rare cause, none being the chronic haemolysis principal leg ulcer mechanism like chronic hypoxia.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which lab feature suggests extravascular hemolysis?", "a": "Hemoglobinuria", "b": "Low bilirubin", "c": "Splenomegaly with spherocytes", "d": "Hemoglobinemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Splenomegaly with spherocytes suggests extravascular haemolysis; splenic enlargement from increased phagocytic activity with spherocyte formation from membrane fragment removal.<br><br>Causes include hereditary spherocytosis and warm autoimmune haemolytic anaemia. Diagnosis by Coombs test (negative in hereditary, positive in autoimmune), peripheral smear, and clinical features. Treatment depends on cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemoglobinuria (option A) is intravascular; low bilirubin (option B) excludes haemolysis; haemoglobinaemia (option D) is intravascular, none suggesting extravascular like splenomegaly with spherocytes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The primary management of severe warm autoimmune hemolytic anemia refractory to steroids is:", "a": "Splenectomy or rituximab", "b": "Iron therapy", "c": "Plasma infusion", "d": "Vitamin B12", "ans": "A", "e": "Splenectomy or rituximab is primary management of steroid-refractory warm autoimmune haemolytic anaemia; both target antibody-mediated haemolysis through different mechanisms.<br><br>Rituximab targets CD20 on B cells reducing antibody production. Splenectomy removes site of extravascular haemolysis. Choice depends on patient factors including age and comorbidities. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Iron therapy (option B) is for iron deficiency; plasma infusion (option C) is for TTP; vitamin B12 (option D) is for B12 deficiency, none being steroid-refractory warm AIHA standard like splenectomy or rituximab.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In hemolytic anemia, LDH rises due to:", "a": "Liver disease", "b": "Infection", "c": "Kidney failure", "d": "RBC destruction releasing intracellular enzymes", "ans": "D", "e": "RBC destruction releases intracellular LDH in haemolytic anaemia; this cytosolic enzyme leaks into plasma when red cells lyse.<br><br>Combined with elevated indirect bilirubin, low haptoglobin, and reticulocytosis confirms haemolysis. Distinguishing intravascular (markedly elevated) from extravascular (mild elevation). Treatment depends on cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Liver disease (option A) elevates LDH from hepatocyte injury; infection (option B) is non-specific; kidney failure (option C) is non-specific, none being the haemolysis LDH mechanism like RBC destruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which anemia presents with reticulocytosis but normal iron stores and jaundice?", "a": "Aplastic anemia", "b": "Hemolytic anemia", "c": "Iron deficiency anemia", "d": "Megaloblastic anemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Haemolytic anaemia presents with reticulocytosis, normal iron stores, and jaundice; bone marrow compensates for red cell destruction with increased reticulocytes while iron metabolism remains normal and haem breakdown elevates indirect bilirubin.<br><br>Diagnosis by elevated LDH, low haptoglobin, elevated indirect bilirubin, and reticulocytosis. Treatment depends on cause (immune, hereditary, drug-induced, mechanical). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Aplastic anaemia (option A) features reticulocytopenia; iron deficiency anaemia (option C) features low ferritin; megaloblastic anaemia (option D) features macrocytosis without true haemolysis, none matching the reticulocytosis-normal-iron-jaundice haemolytic pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with hereditary spherocytosis should be vaccinated before splenectomy against:", "a": "Viruses", "b": "Fungi", "c": "Encapsulated bacteria", "d": "Parasites", "ans": "C", "e": "Encapsulated bacteria vaccination is essential before splenectomy in hereditary spherocytosis; absent spleen increases risk of overwhelming infection by capsulated organisms.<br><br>Vaccinations include pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib (all encapsulated). Long-term penicillin prophylaxis (penicillin V 250 mg twice daily) reduces post-splenectomy infection. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Viruses (option A) are not principally splenic clearance; fungi (option B) are not principally splenic clearance; parasites (option D) are not principally splenic clearance, none being the post-splenectomy specific vaccination target like encapsulated bacteria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Chronic hemolysis increases risk of folate deficiency because:", "a": "Increased marrow utilization", "b": "Reduced absorption", "c": "Liver failure", "d": "Increased urinary loss", "ans": "A", "e": "Increased marrow utilisation of folate in chronic haemolysis causes deficiency; accelerated erythropoiesis demands more folate than dietary intake provides.<br><br>Standard supplementation folic acid 5 mg daily. Combined with treatment of underlying haemolysis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing increased demand from absolute deficiency.<br><br>Reduced absorption (option B) is not principal cause; liver failure (option C) is not principal; increased urinary loss (option D) is not principal, none being the chronic haemolysis folate-deficiency mechanism like increased marrow utilisation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which laboratory combination best confirms active hemolysis?", "a": "Low bilirubin, normal reticulocyte", "b": "Low LDH, high haptoglobin", "c": "High ferritin only", "d": "High LDH, low haptoglobin, reticulocytosis", "ans": "D", "e": "High LDH, low haptoglobin, and reticulocytosis combination best confirms active haemolysis; this triad reflects red cell breakdown with marrow compensation.<br><br>Combined with elevated indirect bilirubin. Distinguishing intravascular (markedly elevated LDH, undetectable haptoglobin, haemoglobinuria) from extravascular (mild LDH elevation, mild haptoglobin reduction). Treatment depends on cause. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Low bilirubin with normal reticulocytes (option A) excludes haemolysis; low LDH with high haptoglobin (option B) excludes haemolysis; high ferritin only (option C) suggests iron overload not haemolysis, none confirming active haemolysis like this triad.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 21-year-old male develops sudden jaundice, back pain and cola-colored urine one day after taking primaquine for malaria prophylaxis. Hb falls rapidly, LDH high and haptoglobin undetectable. Peripheral smear later shows bite cells. The most likely diagnosis is:", "a": "Warm autoimmune hemolysis", "b": "Aplastic crisis", "c": "G6PD deficiency hemolysis", "d": "Hereditary spherocytosis", "ans": "C", "e": "G6PD deficiency haemolysis is the diagnosis; sudden jaundice, back pain, cola-coloured urine after primaquine with high LDH, undetectable haptoglobin, and bite cells fits classical X-linked intravascular haemolysis.<br><br>Diagnosis by enzyme assay (may be falsely normal during acute haemolysis as older deficient cells lysed first). Heinz bodies and bite cells on smear.<br><br>Warm autoimmune haemolysis (option A) features positive Coombs; aplastic crisis (option B) features reticulocytopenia; hereditary spherocytosis (option D) features spherocytes not bite cells, none fitting drug-triggered intravascular haemolysis like G6PD deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The primary biochemical defect in G6PD deficiency results in reduced ability of RBCs to generate:", "a": "NADPH", "b": "ATP", "c": "cAMP", "d": "Lactate", "ans": "A", "e": "NADPH generation is reduced in G6PD deficiency; this enzyme catalyses the first step of the pentose phosphate pathway producing NADPH essential for glutathione regeneration.<br><br>Mechanism includes reduced glutathione protecting red cells from oxidative damage. Deficiency makes red cells vulnerable to oxidative stress producing Heinz bodies, bite cells, and intravascular haemolysis. Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care.<br><br>ATP (option B) is reduced in pyruvate kinase deficiency; cAMP (option C) is unrelated to G6PD; lactate (option D) is anaerobic metabolism product, none being the G6PD-specific cofactor like NADPH.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which drug most commonly precipitates hemolysis in G6PD deficient individuals?", "a": "Metformin", "b": "Isoniazid", "c": "Propranolol", "d": "Sulfonamides", "ans": "D", "e": "Sulfonamides most commonly precipitate G6PD haemolysis; sulfa drugs produce oxidative stress overwhelming reduced glutathione regeneration.<br><br>Other triggers include primaquine, dapsone, nitrofurantoin, methylene blue, fava beans, and infections. Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Metformin (option A) is biguanide; isoniazid (option B) causes sideroblastic anaemia through pyridoxine antagonism; propranolol (option C) is beta-blocker, none being principal G6PD haemolysis triggers like sulfonamides.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Heinz bodies seen in G6PD deficiency represent:", "a": "Membrane lipid deposits", "b": "Denatured hemoglobin precipitates", "c": "Nuclear remnants", "d": "Iron granules", "ans": "B", "e": "Heinz bodies represent denatured haemoglobin precipitates in G6PD deficiency; oxidative damage produces haemoglobin denaturation within red cells.<br><br>Visible on supravital staining (methylene blue or crystal violet) but not on routine Wright stain. Splenic macrophages remove Heinz bodies producing characteristic bite cells. Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Membrane lipid deposits (option A) are not Heinz bodies; nuclear remnants (option C) are Howell-Jolly bodies; iron granules (option D) are Pappenheimer bodies, none being the G6PD-specific denatured haemoglobin inclusions like Heinz bodies.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Bite cells form because splenic macrophages remove:", "a": "Heinz body inclusions", "b": "Cytoplasm", "c": "Entire RBC", "d": "Nucleus", "ans": "A", "e": "Heinz body inclusions are removed by splenic macrophages forming bite cells; partial phagocytosis of these denatured haemoglobin precipitates produces characteristic bite-shaped defects.<br><br>Combined with Heinz bodies on supravital staining. Common triggers include primaquine, dapsone, sulfa drugs, fava beans, and infections. Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Cytoplasm (option B) is not principally removed; entire RBC (option C) is complete phagocytosis (extravascular haemolysis); nucleus (option D) is removed during normal maturation, none being the bite-cell-formation mechanism like Heinz body removal.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "During acute hemolytic episode in G6PD deficiency, the diagnostic enzyme assay may be falsely normal because:", "a": "Antibodies interfere with test", "b": "Reticulocytes contain higher G6PD levels", "c": "RBC destruction increases enzyme activity", "d": "Iron deficiency alters results", "ans": "B", "e": "Reticulocytes contain higher G6PD levels making assay falsely normal during acute haemolysis; older deficient cells lysed first leaving younger cells with residual enzyme activity.<br><br>Repeat assay 2-3 months after acute haemolysis when steady-state achieved. Particularly relevant in African (A-) variant where younger cells retain activity. Mediterranean variant has all-age affected cells.<br><br>Antibodies interfere (option A) is autoimmune haemolysis problem; RBC destruction increases enzyme activity (option C) is incorrect; iron deficiency alters results (option D) is unrelated, none being the G6PD assay false-normal mechanism like reticulocyte high enzyme content.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Best management of acute hemolysis in G6PD deficiency is:", "a": "Iron therapy", "b": "Immediate splenectomy", "c": "Remove offending agent and supportive care", "d": "Corticosteroids", "ans": "C", "e": "Remove offending agent and supportive care is best management of acute G6PD haemolysis; trigger removal allows haemolysis to subside as deficient cells lyse and reticulocyte response replaces them.<br><br>Combined with IV fluids maintaining renal perfusion, transfusion for severe anaemia, and avoiding further triggers. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing trigger avoidance from active treatment.<br><br>Iron therapy (option A) is contraindicated; immediate splenectomy (option B) is for hereditary spherocytosis; corticosteroids (option D) are for autoimmune haemolysis, none being appropriate for G6PD haemolysis like trigger removal.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Favism refers to hemolysis precipitated by ingestion of:", "a": "Raw milk", "b": "Eggs", "c": "Fish", "d": "Fava beans", "ans": "D", "e": "Fava beans precipitate haemolysis in favism; divicine and isouramil from fava beans cause oxidative stress overwhelming G6PD-deficient red cells.<br><br>Particularly severe in Mediterranean variant of G6PD deficiency. Other triggers include primaquine, dapsone, sulfa drugs, nitrofurantoin, methylene blue, and infections. Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Raw milk (option A) is for unpasteurised infection; eggs (option B) are unrelated; fish (option C) is unrelated, none being the favism-specific dietary trigger like fava beans.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which infection commonly precipitates hemolysis in G6PD deficiency?", "a": "Tuberculosis", "b": "Bacterial infection causing oxidative stress", "c": "HIV", "d": "Viral hepatitis", "ans": "B", "e": "Bacterial infection causing oxidative stress commonly precipitates G6PD haemolysis; reactive oxygen species from neutrophil respiratory burst during infection overwhelm reduced glutathione regeneration.<br><br>Treatment includes addressing infection alongside supportive care. Combined with trigger avoidance. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing infection-triggered from drug-triggered haemolysis.<br><br>Tuberculosis (option A) is not typical G6PD trigger; HIV (option C) is not typical trigger though drugs used may be; viral hepatitis (option D) is not typical trigger, none being principal G6PD precipitant like bacterial infection.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Peripheral smear in G6PD deficiency typically shows:", "a": "Bite cells and blister cells", "b": "Schistocytes", "c": "Spherocytes", "d": "Target cells", "ans": "A", "e": "Bite cells and blister cells characterise G6PD deficiency peripheral smear; splenic macrophages remove Heinz body inclusions producing characteristic morphology.<br><br>Combined with Heinz bodies on supravital staining (not visible on routine Wright stain). Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Schistocytes (option B) suggest microangiopathic haemolysis; spherocytes (option C) suggest hereditary spherocytosis or warm AIHA; target cells (option D) suggest thalassaemia or liver disease, none being the G6PD-specific morphology like bite-blister cells.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "G6PD deficiency is inherited as:", "a": "Autosomal dominant", "b": "Mitochondrial", "c": "Autosomal recessive", "d": "X-linked recessive", "ans": "D", "e": "X-linked recessive inheritance characterises G6PD deficiency; G6PD gene located on X chromosome with affected males and variable expression in heterozygous females.<br><br>Common in Mediterranean, African, and Asian populations. Heterozygous females have variable expression depending on lyonisation (X-inactivation). Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Autosomal dominant (option A) is hereditary spherocytosis; mitochondrial (option B) is rare; autosomal recessive (option C) is sickle cell disease, none being G6PD inheritance pattern like X-linked recessive.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The protective advantage of G6PD deficiency relates to reduced severity of:", "a": "Tuberculosis", "b": "Dengue", "c": "Malaria infection", "d": "Typhoid fever", "ans": "C", "e": "Malaria infection severity is reduced by G6PD deficiency; oxidative environment within deficient red cells impairs Plasmodium falciparum growth.<br><br>Geographic distribution of G6PD deficiency overlaps with malaria-endemic regions reflecting selective advantage. Combined with sickle cell trait and thalassaemia trait similarly protective. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Tuberculosis (option A) is not protected by G6PD; dengue (option B) is not protected; typhoid fever (option D) is not protected, none being the protective association of G6PD like malaria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In severe hemolysis due to G6PD deficiency, transfusion is indicated when:", "a": "Hb dangerously low with symptoms", "b": "Bilirubin increases only", "c": "Mild jaundice present", "d": "Reticulocyte count rises", "ans": "A", "e": "Hb dangerously low with symptoms is the transfusion indication in severe G6PD haemolysis; severe anaemia with cardiovascular compromise requires transfusion support.<br><br>Combined with IV fluids maintaining renal perfusion, trigger removal, and supportive care. Most cases self-limiting with trigger removal. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Bilirubin increases only (option B) is mild haemolysis; mild jaundice present (option C) is mild haemolysis; reticulocyte count rises (option D) is bone marrow response not transfusion indication, none triggering transfusion like dangerously low Hb with symptoms.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A neonate with G6PD deficiency is particularly at risk of:", "a": "Megaloblastic anemia", "b": "Leukopenia", "c": "Thrombocytopenia", "d": "Severe neonatal jaundice and kernicterus", "ans": "D", "e": "Severe neonatal jaundice and kernicterus is principal G6PD neonatal risk; immature hepatic conjugation overwhelmed by haemolysis-related bilirubin production causes bilirubin encephalopathy.<br><br>Treatment includes phototherapy and exchange transfusion for severe disease. Avoiding triggers (naphthalene moth balls, certain herbal remedies) prevents haemolysis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including paediatrician. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Megaloblastic anaemia (option A) is unrelated; leukopenia (option B) is unrelated; thrombocytopenia (option C) is unrelated, none being the G6PD-neonatal-specific complication like severe jaundice with kernicterus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Sickle cell disease results from mutation causing substitution of:", "a": "Alanine for glycine", "b": "Valine for glutamate in beta globin", "c": "Aspartate for valine", "d": "Lysine for glutamate", "ans": "B", "e": "Valine for glutamate substitution at position 6 of beta-globin chain causes sickle cell disease; point mutation in beta-globin gene produces HbS that polymerises when deoxygenated.<br><br>Mechanism includes deoxygenated HbS polymerises producing sickle cell shape, vascular occlusion, and haemolysis. Diagnosis by Hb electrophoresis showing HbSS in homozygotes.<br><br>Alanine for glycine (option A) is not the sickle mutation; aspartate for valine (option C) is not the sickle mutation; lysine for glutamate (option D) is HbC mutation, none being the sickle cell-specific mutation like valine for glutamate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Sickling of RBCs is promoted most strongly by:", "a": "Hyperglycemia", "b": "High oxygen tension", "c": "Acidosis and hypoxia", "d": "Alkalosis", "ans": "C", "e": "Acidosis and hypoxia most strongly promote sickling; deoxygenated HbS at low pH aggregates producing sickle cell shape.<br><br>Other promoters include dehydration, cold exposure, infection, and stress. Treatment includes IV fluids, analgesia, oxygen, and addressing precipitants. Hydroxyurea reduces frequency of crises through HbF induction. Bone marrow transplantation curative in selected cases. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Hyperglycaemia (option A) is not principal sickling promoter; high oxygen tension (option B) is opposite (reduces sickling); alkalosis (option D) is opposite (reduces sickling), none promoting sickling like acidosis-hypoxia combination.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Repeated vaso-occlusion in sickle cell disease leads to functional absence of spleen known as:", "a": "Autosplenectomy", "b": "Splenic infarction crisis", "c": "Splenomegaly", "d": "Hypersplenism", "ans": "A", "e": "Autosplenectomy describes functional splenic absence in sickle cell disease; repeated vaso-occlusion and infarction produces splenic atrophy with functional asplenia.<br><br>Increased risk of infection by encapsulated organisms (Streptococcus pneumoniae, H. influenzae, N. meningitidis, Salmonella). Prophylactic penicillin (penicillin V 125 mg twice daily until age 5). Pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib vaccinations essential. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Splenic infarction crisis (option B) is acute event not chronic state; splenomegaly (option C) is opposite (early disease); hypersplenism (option D) is opposite, none describing this functional asplenia state like autosplenectomy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child with sickle cell disease presents with sudden pallor and low reticulocyte count after viral infection. The most likely organism is:", "a": "Cytomegalovirus", "b": "Epstein–Barr virus", "c": "Parvovirus B19", "d": "Influenza", "ans": "C", "e": "Parvovirus B19 is the most likely organism in sickle cell child with sudden pallor and low reticulocytes after viral infection; this virus infects erythroid precursors halting red cell production while haemolysis continues.<br><br>Diagnosis by parvovirus B19 PCR in blood, anti-parvovirus B19 IgM serology. Treatment with IVIG and supportive care. Bone marrow recovery follows clearance.<br><br>Cytomegalovirus (option A) is uncommon cause; Epstein-Barr virus (option B) is uncommon cause; influenza (option D) is uncommon cause, none being principal sickle cell aplastic crisis cause like parvovirus B19.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The mechanism of aplastic crisis in sickle cell disease is:", "a": "Iron deficiency", "b": "Increased hemolysis", "c": "Splenic sequestration", "d": "Temporary suppression of erythropoiesis", "ans": "D", "e": "Temporary suppression of erythropoiesis is the mechanism of aplastic crisis in sickle cell disease; parvovirus B19 infects erythroid precursors halting red cell production.<br><br>Diagnosis by parvovirus B19 PCR in blood, anti-parvovirus B19 IgM serology, reticulocytopenia, and falling Hb. Treatment with IVIG and supportive care. Bone marrow recovery follows clearance. Combined with addressing underlying sickle cell disease.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) is unrelated; increased haemolysis (option B) is opposite mechanism; splenic sequestration (option C) is different crisis type, none being the parvovirus-aplastic crisis specific mechanism like erythropoiesis suppression.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Painful vaso-occlusive crisis in sickle cell disease primarily results from:", "a": "RBC membrane fragility", "b": "Microvascular obstruction by sickled cells", "c": "Autoimmune destruction", "d": "Platelet deficiency", "ans": "B", "e": "Microvascular obstruction by sickled cells causes painful vaso-occlusive crisis; sickle-shaped red cells occlude small vessels producing tissue ischaemia and pain.<br><br>Triggers include hypoxia, dehydration, infection, cold exposure, and stress. Treatment includes IV fluids, analgesia (often opioids), oxygen, and addressing precipitants. Hydroxyurea reduces frequency of crises. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>RBC membrane fragility (option A) is hereditary spherocytosis; autoimmune destruction (option C) is AIHA; platelet deficiency (option D) is thrombocytopenia, none being the vaso-occlusive crisis mechanism like sickled cell microvascular obstruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hydroxyurea improves sickle cell disease by:", "a": "Stimulating erythropoietin", "b": "Increasing iron absorption", "c": "Increasing HbF production", "d": "Preventing hemolysis antibodies", "ans": "C", "e": "Increasing HbF production is hydroxyurea's mechanism in sickle cell disease; gamma chain induction produces HbF which interferes with HbS polymerisation.<br><br>Indications include frequent painful crises, acute chest syndrome, and severe anaemia. Side effects include myelosuppression and rarely teratogenicity. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Stimulating erythropoietin (option A) is not principal mechanism; increasing iron absorption (option B) is contraindicated risking overload; preventing haemolysis antibodies (option D) is for autoimmune disease, none being hydroxyurea's mechanism like HbF induction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which complication is common in sickle cell disease due to repeated infarction of bones?", "a": "Osteomyelitis by Salmonella", "b": "Bone tumors", "c": "Osteoarthritis", "d": "Osteoporosis", "ans": "A", "e": "Osteomyelitis by Salmonella is common sickle cell complication; bone infarction predisposes to Salmonella infection (uniquely associated due to functional asplenia and infarcted bone).<br><br>Treatment includes prolonged antibiotic therapy (ceftriaxone, ciprofloxacin), surgical debridement for established infection, and addressing underlying sickle cell disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Bone tumours (option B) are not specifically increased; osteoarthritis (option C) is degenerative not infarction-related; osteoporosis (option D) is density not infarction-related, none being the sickle cell-specific bone infarction complication like Salmonella osteomyelitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Acute chest syndrome in sickle cell disease presents with:", "a": "Severe hypertension", "b": "Chest pain, fever and pulmonary infiltrates", "c": "Hematuria only", "d": "Seizures", "ans": "B", "e": "Chest pain, fever, and pulmonary infiltrates characterise acute chest syndrome in sickle cell disease; this severe complication features pulmonary microvascular sickling, fat embolism, and infection.<br><br>Treatment includes oxygen, antibiotics (covering atypicals including Mycoplasma), IV fluids, analgesia, and exchange transfusion for severe disease. Mortality remains substantial despite treatment. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Severe hypertension (option A) is not the principal acute chest pattern; haematuria only (option C) is renal not chest; seizures (option D) are CNS not chest, none being acute chest syndrome features like chest pain-fever-infiltrates.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Definitive curative therapy for sickle cell disease is:", "a": "Chronic transfusion only", "b": "Folic acid", "c": "Hydroxyurea", "d": "Bone marrow transplantation", "ans": "D", "e": "Bone marrow transplantation is definitive curative therapy for sickle cell disease; HLA-matched sibling donor replaces sickle haematopoiesis with normal donor stem cells.<br><br>Indications include severe disease in young patients with HLA-matched sibling. Mortality 5-10 percent in experienced centres. Combined with reduced-intensity conditioning regimens. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Gene therapy emerging as alternative.<br><br>Chronic transfusion only (option A) is disease-modifying not curative; folic acid (option B) is supportive; hydroxyurea (option C) is disease-modifying not curative, none being curative sickle cell therapy like marrow transplantation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Splenic sequestration crisis is characterized by:", "a": "Reticulocytopenia", "b": "Leukocytosis", "c": "Sudden splenic enlargement with hypovolemia", "d": "Increased hemoglobin", "ans": "C", "e": "Sudden splenic enlargement with hypovolaemia characterises splenic sequestration crisis; rapid splenic pooling of red cells produces falling haemoglobin and hypovolaemic shock.<br><br>Common in young children with sickle cell disease (before autosplenectomy). Treatment includes immediate transfusion and supportive care. Splenectomy for recurrent episodes. Adults usually have functional asplenia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Reticulocytopenia (option A) is aplastic crisis; leukocytosis (option B) is infection; increased haemoglobin (option D) is opposite of crisis, none being splenic sequestration features like splenic enlargement with hypovolaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Peripheral smear in sickle cell anemia shows:", "a": "Sickle shaped RBCs and target cells", "b": "Tear drop cells", "c": "Macro-ovalocytes", "d": "Spherocytes", "ans": "A", "e": "Sickle-shaped RBCs and target cells characterise sickle cell anaemia peripheral smear; HbS polymerisation produces sickle morphology while functional asplenia produces target cells.<br><br>Other findings include Howell-Jolly bodies (functional asplenia), nucleated red cells, and basophilic stippling. Diagnosis by Hb electrophoresis showing HbSS. Treatment includes hydroxyurea, folate, prophylactic penicillin, vaccinations, exchange transfusion. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Tear drop cells (option B) are myelofibrosis; macro-ovalocytes (option C) are megaloblastic; spherocytes (option D) are hereditary spherocytosis or AIHA, none being sickle cell smear findings like sickle cells with target cells.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which factor decreases sickling of RBCs?", "a": "Acidosis", "b": "Dehydration", "c": "Hypoxia", "d": "Increased HbF", "ans": "D", "e": "Increased HbF decreases sickling; fetal haemoglobin interferes with HbS polymerisation reducing sickle cell formation.<br><br>Hydroxyurea induces HbF reducing sickling. Indications include frequent painful crises, acute chest syndrome, and severe anaemia. Side effects include myelosuppression and rarely teratogenicity. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Standard supportive care guides management. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Acidosis (option A) promotes sickling; dehydration (option B) promotes sickling; hypoxia (option C) promotes sickling, none reducing sickling like increased HbF.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Stroke in children with sickle cell disease is prevented by:", "a": "Iron therapy", "b": "Chronic transfusion program", "c": "Splenectomy", "d": "Antibiotics", "ans": "B", "e": "Chronic transfusion programme prevents stroke in sickle cell disease children; maintaining HbS under 30 percent reduces cerebrovascular complications.<br><br>Transcranial Doppler screening identifies high-risk children for primary prevention. Secondary prevention after first stroke also requires chronic transfusion. Hydroxyurea may reduce risk. Combined with iron chelation managing transfusion-related iron overload. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Iron therapy (option A) is contraindicated risking overload; splenectomy (option C) is for hypersplenism; antibiotics (option D) are for infection prevention not stroke, none being sickle cell stroke prevention like chronic transfusion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Dactylitis in infants with sickle cell disease is due to:", "a": "Iron overload", "b": "Joint infection", "c": "Vitamin deficiency", "d": "Bone infarction", "ans": "D", "e": "Bone infarction causes dactylitis in infants with sickle cell disease; vaso-occlusion in small bones of hands and feet produces painful swelling (hand-foot syndrome).<br><br>Often first manifestation of sickle cell disease. Treatment includes IV fluids, analgesia, and addressing precipitants. Combined with addressing underlying sickle cell disease (hydroxyurea, folate, prophylactic penicillin, vaccinations). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Iron overload (option A) is transfusion-related complication; joint infection (option B) is septic arthritis; vitamin deficiency (option C) is nutritional, none being the dactylitis mechanism like bone infarction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "The major cause of mortality in sickle cell disease during childhood is:", "a": "Diabetes", "b": "Hypertension", "c": "Infection with encapsulated bacteria", "d": "Renal failure", "ans": "C", "e": "Infection with encapsulated bacteria is the major mortality cause in sickle cell disease childhood; functional asplenia from autosplenectomy increases infection risk by encapsulated organisms.<br><br>Increased risk of Streptococcus pneumoniae, H. influenzae, N. meningitidis, and Salmonella. Prophylactic penicillin (penicillin V 125 mg twice daily until age 5). Pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib vaccinations essential.<br><br>Diabetes (option A) is not principal sickle cell mortality; hypertension (option B) is not principal; renal failure (option D) is later complication, none being principal childhood mortality cause like encapsulated bacterial infection.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Aplastic anemia is characterized by:", "a": "Leukocytosis", "b": "Pancytopenia with hypocellular marrow", "c": "Thrombocytosis", "d": "Hypercellular marrow", "ans": "B", "e": "Pancytopenia with hypocellular marrow characterises aplastic anaemia; bone marrow failure produces this combination distinguishing from other causes of pancytopenia.<br><br>Causes include idiopathic, drug-induced (chloramphenicol, NSAIDs), toxin exposure (benzene), viral infection (parvovirus B19, hepatitis), and autoimmune. Diagnosis by bone marrow biopsy showing hypocellular marrow with under 25 percent cellularity. Treatment includes immunosuppression, bone marrow transplantation, and supportive care.<br><br>Leukocytosis (option A) is infection or leukaemia; thrombocytosis (option C) is reactive or essential thrombocythaemia; hypercellular marrow (option D) is opposite, none being aplastic anaemia features like pancytopenia with hypocellularity.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common cause of acquired aplastic anemia worldwide:", "a": "Viral hepatitis related immune destruction", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Malaria", "d": "Hemolysis", "ans": "A", "e": "Viral hepatitis-related immune destruction is the most common cause of acquired aplastic anaemia worldwide; non-A non-B non-C hepatitis causes severe immune-mediated bone marrow failure.<br><br>Mechanism unclear but may be immune-mediated. Treatment includes immunosuppression (ATG, ciclosporin), bone marrow transplantation, and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option B) is microcytic anaemia not aplastic; malaria (option C) causes haemolysis; haemolysis (option D) is RBC destruction, none being principal acquired aplastic anaemia cause like viral hepatitis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Bone marrow biopsy in aplastic anemia shows:", "a": "Hyperplasia", "b": "Fatty replacement of marrow", "c": "Tumor infiltration", "d": "Fibrosis", "ans": "B", "e": "Fatty replacement of marrow characterises aplastic anaemia bone marrow biopsy; hypocellular marrow with under 25 percent cellularity replaced by adipocytes.<br><br>Combined with peripheral blood findings (Camitta criteria: neutrophils under 0.5 x 10^9/L, platelets under 20 x 10^9/L, reticulocytes under 1 percent). Distinguishes from myelodysplastic syndrome, hypoplastic leukaemia, and other causes. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Hyperplasia (option A) is opposite (megaloblastic); tumour infiltration (option C) is metastatic disease or leukaemia; fibrosis (option D) is myelofibrosis, none being aplastic anaemia marrow finding like fatty replacement.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which drug commonly causes aplastic anemia?", "a": "Metformin", "b": "Penicillin", "c": "Chloramphenicol", "d": "Paracetamol", "ans": "C", "e": "Chloramphenicol commonly causes aplastic anaemia; this antibiotic produces idiosyncratic bone marrow suppression unrelated to dose.<br><br>Other drugs include NSAIDs (phenylbutazone), antimalarials, anticonvulsants (carbamazepine, phenytoin), and gold. Treatment includes drug discontinuation and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Metformin (option A) causes B12 deficiency; penicillin (option B) causes immune haemolysis rarely aplastic; paracetamol (option D) causes liver toxicity not aplastic anaemia, none being principal aplastic anaemia drug cause like chloramphenicol.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Severe neutropenia in aplastic anemia predisposes to:", "a": "Hemolysis", "b": "Bleeding", "c": "Jaundice", "d": "Recurrent infections", "ans": "D", "e": "Recurrent infections result from severe neutropenia in aplastic anaemia; reduced neutrophil count impairs defence against bacterial and fungal infections.<br><br>Treatment includes broad-spectrum antibiotics for febrile neutropenia, prophylactic antibiotics in some protocols, and growth factors (G-CSF) selectively. Combined with addressing underlying aplastic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemolysis (option A) is RBC destruction; bleeding (option B) is thrombocytopenia consequence; jaundice (option C) is haemolysis or liver disease, none being the principal neutropenia consequence like recurrent infections.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Petechiae and mucosal bleeding in aplastic anemia occur due to:", "a": "Thrombocytopenia", "b": "Hemolysis", "c": "Iron deficiency", "d": "Hyperviscosity", "ans": "A", "e": "Thrombocytopenia produces petechiae and mucosal bleeding in aplastic anaemia; reduced platelet production from bone marrow failure causes bleeding manifestations.<br><br>Treatment includes platelet transfusion for severe thrombocytopenia (under 10 x 10^9/L) or active bleeding. Combined with addressing underlying aplastic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Haemolysis (option B) features jaundice; iron deficiency (option C) is microcytic anaemia; hyperviscosity (option D) is plasma cell disorder or myeloproliferative, none being the petechiae-mucosal bleeding mechanism like thrombocytopenia.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Curative treatment for severe aplastic anemia in young patient:", "a": "Steroids alone", "b": "Iron therapy", "c": "Bone marrow transplant", "d": "Splenectomy", "ans": "C", "e": "Bone marrow transplant is curative for severe aplastic anaemia in young patients; HLA-matched sibling donor replaces defective haematopoiesis.<br><br>Indications include severe disease in young patients with HLA-matched sibling. Mortality 5-15 percent in experienced centres. Combined with conditioning regimens. Survival rates 80-90 percent at 5 years. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Steroids alone (option A) are inadequate; iron therapy (option B) is for iron deficiency; splenectomy (option D) is for hypersplenism not aplastic anaemia, none being curative for severe aplastic anaemia in young patients like marrow transplant.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Immunosuppressive therapy used in non-transplant candidates includes:", "a": "Methotrexate", "b": "Hydroxyurea", "c": "Warfarin", "d": "Cyclosporine with antithymocyte globulin", "ans": "D", "e": "Cyclosporine with antithymocyte globulin (ATG) is immunosuppression for non-transplant aplastic anaemia patients; T-cell-mediated mechanism in many cases responds to this combination.<br><br>Indications include severe aplastic anaemia without HLA-matched donor or in older patients. Combined with G-CSF in some protocols. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Response rates 60-80 percent.<br><br>Methotrexate (option A) is for autoimmune disease or chemotherapy; hydroxyurea (option B) is for sickle cell or CML; warfarin (option C) is anticoagulant, none being aplastic anaemia immunosuppression like ciclosporin-ATG.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which virus is classically associated with aplastic anemia?", "a": "Hepatitis viruses", "b": "Rabies", "c": "Influenza", "d": "Measles", "ans": "A", "e": "Hepatitis viruses are classically associated with aplastic anaemia; non-A non-B non-C hepatitis particularly produces severe immune-mediated bone marrow failure.<br><br>Mechanism unclear but may be immune-mediated. Treatment includes immunosuppression (ATG, ciclosporin), bone marrow transplantation, and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Rabies (option B) is unrelated; influenza (option C) is uncommon cause; measles (option D) is uncommon cause, none being principal aplastic anaemia viral association like hepatitis viruses.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Reticulocyte count in aplastic anemia is typically:", "a": "Normal", "b": "Very low", "c": "Variable", "d": "Increased", "ans": "B", "e": "Reticulocyte count is very low in aplastic anaemia; bone marrow failure prevents production of new red cells reflected in reticulocytopenia.<br><br>Camitta criteria for severe disease require reticulocytes under 1 percent (corrected). Combined with neutrophils under 0.5 x 10^9/L and platelets under 20 x 10^9/L. Treatment includes immunosuppression, bone marrow transplantation, and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Normal (option A) excludes aplastic anaemia; variable (option C) is non-specific; increased (option D) is opposite (haemolysis or blood loss), none being aplastic anaemia reticulocyte feature like very low.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In aplastic anemia, splenomegaly is usually:", "a": "Painful", "b": "Massive", "c": "Mild", "d": "Absent", "ans": "D", "e": "Splenomegaly is usually absent in aplastic anaemia; this distinguishes from other causes of pancytopenia like myelodysplastic syndrome, lymphoma, leukaemia, infection, or infiltration.<br><br>Splenomegaly suggests alternative diagnosis. Combined with bone marrow biopsy showing hypocellular marrow excludes other causes. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Painful (option A) is uncommon; massive (option B) is myeloproliferative; mild (option C) is variable conditions, none being aplastic anaemia spleen finding like absent splenomegaly.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Fanconi anemia differs from acquired aplastic anemia by presence of:", "a": "Hemolysis", "b": "Autoantibodies", "c": "Congenital anomalies", "d": "Infection", "ans": "C", "e": "Congenital anomalies distinguish Fanconi anaemia from acquired aplastic anaemia; this inherited bone marrow failure syndrome features developmental abnormalities.<br><br>Features include short stature, café-au-lait spots, skeletal abnormalities (radial ray, thumb), bone marrow failure, and increased malignancy risk (acute leukaemia, squamous cell carcinoma). Diagnosis by chromosomal breakage with diepoxybutane. Treatment includes bone marrow transplantation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Haemolysis (option A) is unrelated; autoantibodies (option B) are not characteristic; infection (option D) is non-specific, none distinguishing Fanconi from acquired aplastic anaemia like congenital anomalies.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which laboratory finding helps differentiate aplastic anemia from leukemia?", "a": "Pancytopenia", "b": "Hypocellular marrow without blasts", "c": "Anemia", "d": "Fever", "ans": "B", "e": "Hypocellular marrow without blasts differentiates aplastic anaemia from leukaemia; both feature pancytopenia but leukaemia shows hypercellular marrow with over 20 percent blasts.<br><br>Combined with peripheral blood findings (Camitta criteria) and immunophenotyping. Distinguishes from myelodysplastic syndrome (dysplasia, variable blasts), hypoplastic leukaemia, and other causes. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Pancytopenia (option A) occurs in both; anaemia (option C) occurs in many conditions; fever (option D) is non-specific, none differentiating aplastic from leukaemia like hypocellular marrow without blasts.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Main cause of death in untreated aplastic anemia:", "a": "Infection and hemorrhage", "b": "Renal failure", "c": "Thrombosis", "d": "Hypertension", "ans": "A", "e": "Infection and haemorrhage are main causes of death in untreated aplastic anaemia; neutropenia produces infection and thrombocytopenia produces bleeding.<br><br>Treatment includes broad-spectrum antibiotics for febrile neutropenia, platelet transfusion for severe thrombocytopenia or bleeding, red cell transfusion for symptomatic anaemia, and addressing underlying aplastic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Renal failure (option B) is uncommon; thrombosis (option C) is in PNH; hypertension (option D) is unrelated, none being principal untreated aplastic anaemia mortality like infection-haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria may evolve from aplastic anemia due to:", "a": "Iron deficiency", "b": "Clonal stem cell mutation", "c": "Vitamin deficiency", "d": "Splenic damage", "ans": "B", "e": "Clonal stem cell mutation underlies PNH evolution from aplastic anaemia; PIG-A mutation in haematopoietic stem cell produces GPI-anchor deficiency on red cells.<br><br>Diagnosis by flow cytometry showing reduced CD55 and CD59 on red cells and granulocytes. Treatment includes eculizumab for symptomatic PNH and bone marrow transplantation for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) is unrelated; vitamin deficiency (option C) is unrelated; splenic damage (option D) is unrelated, none being the PNH-from-aplastic mechanism like clonal stem cell mutation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which finding is typical in severe aplastic anemia criteria?", "a": "Neutrophils >2,000", "b": "Platelets >150,000", "c": "Absolute neutrophil count <500", "d": "Reticulocyte >5%", "ans": "C", "e": "Absolute neutrophil count under 500 (0.5 x 10^9/L) is typical severe aplastic anaemia Camitta criterion; reflects severe bone marrow failure.<br><br>Combined with platelets under 20 x 10^9/L and reticulocytes under 1 percent (corrected) for diagnosis of severe disease. Treatment includes immunosuppression (ATG, ciclosporin), bone marrow transplantation, and supportive care. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Neutrophils over 2000 (option A) is normal; platelets over 150000 (option B) is normal; reticulocytes over 5 percent (option D) is haemolysis, none being severe aplastic anaemia criterion like neutrophils under 500.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Management of mild aplastic anemia includes:", "a": "Chemotherapy", "b": "Immediate transplant", "c": "Splenectomy", "d": "Observation and supportive care", "ans": "D", "e": "Observation and supportive care manages mild aplastic anaemia; non-severe disease may not require immediate intensive treatment.<br><br>Indications for immediate immunosuppression include severe disease (Camitta criteria), transfusion dependence, or progressive disease. Combined with monitoring for progression. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Chemotherapy (option A) is for malignancy; immediate transplant (option B) is for severe disease; splenectomy (option C) is for hypersplenism, none being mild aplastic anaemia management like observation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In sickle cell crisis, initial management includes:", "a": "Hydration and analgesia", "b": "Steroids only", "c": "Iron therapy", "d": "Diuretics", "ans": "A", "e": "Hydration and analgesia is initial management of sickle cell crisis; addressing dehydration and providing pain relief are foundational.<br><br>Treatment includes IV fluids, analgesia (often opioids), oxygen, and addressing precipitants (infection, hypoxia, cold exposure). Hydroxyurea reduces frequency of future crises through HbF induction. Combined with treating any precipitating infection. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Steroids only (option B) are not standard; iron therapy (option C) is contraindicated; diuretics (option D) worsen dehydration, none being sickle cell crisis initial management like hydration-analgesia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Repeated transfusions in sickle cell disease require monitoring for:", "a": "Hypercalcemia", "b": "Hypoglycemia", "c": "Iron overload", "d": "Polycythemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Iron overload requires monitoring with repeated transfusions in sickle cell disease; each unit adds 200-250 mg iron with no excretion pathway.<br><br>Monitoring with serum ferritin, liver MRI, and cardiac MRI for iron quantification. Iron chelation (deferoxamine, deferasirox, deferiprone) for established overload. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Hypercalcaemia (option A) is not transfusion-related; hypoglycaemia (option B) is not transfusion-related; polycythaemia (option D) is opposite, none being principal sickle cell transfusion complication like iron overload.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which hematological feature is shared by both aplastic anemia and parvovirus B19 aplastic crisis?", "a": "Reticulocytopenia", "b": "Leukocytosis", "c": "Reticulocytosis", "d": "Thrombocytosis", "ans": "A", "e": "Reticulocytopenia is shared between aplastic anaemia and parvovirus B19 aplastic crisis; both feature impaired red cell production.<br><br>Aplastic anaemia features generalised marrow failure (pancytopenia). Parvovirus aplastic crisis features selective erythroid suppression in patients with chronic haemolytic anaemia (sickle cell, hereditary spherocytosis). Treatment differs: immunosuppression for aplastic anaemia, IVIG and supportive care for parvovirus. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Leukocytosis (option B) is infection or leukaemia; reticulocytosis (option C) is opposite (haemolysis); thrombocytosis (option D) is reactive, none being shared feature like reticulocytopenia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 7-year-old child presents with fever, pallor, petechiae and bone pain for 2 weeks. CBC shows pancytopenia and peripheral smear reveals numerous blasts with high nuclear-cytoplasmic ratio and prominent nucleoli. The most likely diagnosis is:", "a": "Myelodysplastic syndrome", "b": "Aplastic anemia", "c": "Chronic leukemia", "d": "Acute leukemia", "ans": "D", "e": "Acute leukaemia is most likely; child with fever, pallor, petechiae, bone pain, pancytopenia, and blasts with high nuclear-cytoplasmic ratio and prominent nucleoli on smear fits this aggressive marrow malignancy.<br><br>Diagnosis by bone marrow showing over 20 percent blasts, immunophenotyping distinguishing ALL from AML, and cytogenetics. Treatment includes induction, consolidation, CNS prophylaxis, maintenance.<br><br>Myelodysplastic syndrome (option A) features dysplasia with under 20 percent blasts; aplastic anaemia (option B) features hypocellular marrow without blasts; chronic leukaemia (option C) features mature cells, none fitting paediatric pancytopenia with prominent blasts like acute leukaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In acute lymphoblastic leukemia, bone marrow examination typically demonstrates:", "a": "Plasma cell sheets", "b": "Replacement by lymphoblasts", "c": "Megakaryocyte hyperplasia", "d": "Granuloma formation", "ans": "B", "e": "Replacement by lymphoblasts characterises ALL bone marrow; over 20 percent lymphoblasts replace normal haematopoiesis producing pancytopenia.<br><br>Diagnosis by bone marrow showing over 20 percent lymphoblasts, immunophenotyping (CD19, CD10, TdT positive in B-ALL; CD3, CD7 in T-ALL), and cytogenetics. Treatment includes induction, consolidation, CNS prophylaxis, and maintenance for 2-3 years. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Plasma cell sheets (option A) characterise multiple myeloma; megakaryocyte hyperplasia (option C) is essential thrombocythaemia; granuloma formation (option D) is sarcoidosis or TB, none being ALL marrow finding like lymphoblast replacement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Presence of Auer rods on peripheral smear indicates:", "a": "Chronic lymphocytic leukemia", "b": "Hairy cell leukemia", "c": "Acute myelogenous leukemia", "d": "Multiple myeloma", "ans": "C", "e": "Acute myelogenous leukaemia is indicated by Auer rods; these crystallised lysosomal granules in myeloblasts are pathognomonic of AML.<br><br>Most prominent in acute promyelocytic leukaemia (APL, AML M3). Combined with bone marrow showing over 20 percent blasts, immunophenotyping (CD13, CD33, CD117, MPO positive), and cytogenetics. Treatment includes induction with cytarabine and anthracycline. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia (option A) features smudge cells; hairy cell leukaemia (option B) features hairy projections on lymphocytes; multiple myeloma (option D) features plasma cells, none being Auer-rod-associated like AML.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Definitive classification of leukemia subtype requires:", "a": "Reticulocyte count", "b": "Peripheral smear only", "c": "ESR", "d": "Bone marrow immunophenotyping", "ans": "D", "e": "Bone marrow immunophenotyping is required for definitive leukaemia subtype classification; flow cytometry identifies surface markers distinguishing AML (CD13, CD33, CD117, MPO), B-ALL (CD19, CD10, TdT), and T-ALL (CD3, CD7).<br><br>Combined with cytogenetics (Philadelphia chromosome, t(15;17), t(8;21), inv(16), MLL rearrangement) and molecular markers (FLT3, NPM1, CEBPA in AML) for full classification. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Reticulocyte count (option A) is for haemolysis; peripheral smear only (option B) is screening; ESR (option C) is non-specific, none being definitive classification tool like bone marrow immunophenotyping.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Tumor lysis syndrome after chemotherapy most characteristically causes:", "a": "Hyperkalemia with hyperuricemia", "b": "Hypophosphatemia", "c": "Hypernatremia", "d": "Hypokalemia", "ans": "A", "e": "Hyperkalaemia with hyperuricaemia characterises tumour lysis syndrome; rapid tumour cell breakdown after chemotherapy releases intracellular potassium and purines metabolised to uric acid.<br><br>Combined with hyperphosphataemia, hypocalcaemia (phosphate binds calcium), and acute kidney injury. Common in haematological malignancies (Burkitt lymphoma, ALL, AML). Treatment includes IV fluids, allopurinol or rasburicase, and addressing electrolyte abnormalities. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Hypophosphataemia (option B) is opposite (hyperphosphataemia occurs); hypernatraemia (option C) is unrelated; hypokalaemia (option D) is opposite, none being TLS specific pattern like hyperkalaemia with hyperuricaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Leukocyte alkaline phosphatase score is typically low in:", "a": "Leukemoid reaction", "b": "Chronic myelogenous leukemia", "c": "Lymphoma", "d": "Acute leukemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Chronic myelogenous leukaemia features low LAP score; abnormal granulocyte maturation reduces leukocyte alkaline phosphatase activity.<br><br>Distinguishes CML from leukaemoid reaction (LAP elevated in reactive). Combined with Philadelphia chromosome on cytogenetics and BCR-ABL on FISH or PCR. Treatment with tyrosine kinase inhibitors (imatinib, dasatinib, nilotinib). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Leukaemoid reaction (option A) features high LAP; lymphoma (option C) features variable LAP; acute leukaemia (option D) features variable LAP, none being characterised by low LAP like CML.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Philadelphia chromosome is formed by translocation between:", "a": "9 and 22", "b": "8 and 14", "c": "11 and 14", "d": "15 and 17", "ans": "A", "e": "Philadelphia chromosome is formed by translocation between chromosomes 9 and 22; t(9;22) produces BCR-ABL fusion gene.<br><br>BCR on chromosome 22 fuses with ABL on chromosome 9 producing constitutively active tyrosine kinase. Characterises CML and 20-30 percent of adult ALL. Treatment with tyrosine kinase inhibitors targeting BCR-ABL. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Chromosomes 8 and 14 (option B) is Burkitt lymphoma t(8;14); chromosomes 11 and 14 (option C) is mantle cell lymphoma t(11;14); chromosomes 15 and 17 (option D) is APL t(15;17), none being Philadelphia chromosome like t(9;22).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "BCR-ABL fusion gene produces:", "a": "Growth factor receptor", "b": "DNA polymerase", "c": "Tyrosine kinase", "d": "Tumor suppressor protein", "ans": "C", "e": "BCR-ABL fusion gene produces constitutively active tyrosine kinase; this aberrant enzyme drives uncontrolled myeloid proliferation in CML.<br><br>Tyrosine kinase inhibitors (imatinib, dasatinib, nilotinib) target this fusion protein producing remarkable clinical responses. Monitoring by quantitative BCR-ABL PCR. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Growth factor receptor (option A) is not BCR-ABL function; DNA polymerase (option B) is replication enzyme; tumour suppressor protein (option D) is opposite (BCR-ABL is oncoprotein), none being BCR-ABL product like tyrosine kinase.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "First-line therapy for chronic myelogenous leukemia:", "a": "Methotrexate", "b": "Imatinib", "c": "Prednisone", "d": "Cyclophosphamide", "ans": "B", "e": "Imatinib is first-line therapy for chronic myelogenous leukaemia; this tyrosine kinase inhibitor targets BCR-ABL fusion protein.<br><br>Standard dose 400 mg daily for chronic phase CML. Side effects include cytopenias, oedema, muscle cramps, and rashes. Resistance from BCR-ABL mutations may require dasatinib or nilotinib. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Methotrexate (option A) is for ALL maintenance or autoimmune disease; prednisone (option C) is for ALL induction; cyclophosphamide (option D) is for various malignancies, none being CML first-line like imatinib.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "An elderly patient with lymphocytosis and smudge cells most likely has:", "a": "AML", "b": "CML", "c": "ALL", "d": "CLL", "ans": "D", "e": "CLL fits elderly patient with lymphocytosis and smudge cells; mature B-lymphocyte accumulation produces this pattern with fragile cells rupturing on smear preparation.<br><br>Diagnosis by lymphocytosis over 5 x 10^9/L, immunophenotyping (CD5, CD19, CD23 positive), and bone marrow showing lymphocytic infiltration. Rai or Binet staging guides treatment.<br><br>AML (option A) features myeloblasts not smudge cells; CML (option B) features Philadelphia chromosome with myeloid hyperplasia; ALL (option C) features lymphoblasts in younger patients, none fitting elderly lymphocytosis with smudge cells like CLL.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most frequent autoimmune complication of CLL:", "a": "Neutrophilia", "b": "Thrombocytosis", "c": "Autoimmune hemolytic anemia", "d": "Polycythemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Autoimmune haemolytic anaemia is the most frequent autoimmune complication of CLL; warm AIHA most common with IgG antibodies producing extravascular haemolysis.<br><br>Other autoimmune complications include immune thrombocytopenia (ITP), pure red cell aplasia, and autoimmune neutropenia. Treatment includes corticosteroids first-line, rituximab or splenectomy second-line. Combined with treating CLL. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Neutrophilia (option A) is reactive not autoimmune; thrombocytosis (option B) is reactive or essential; polycythaemia (option D) is myeloproliferative, none being CLL autoimmune complication like AIHA.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Richter transformation refers to progression of CLL into:", "a": "Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma", "b": "AML", "c": "Hodgkin lymphoma", "d": "Myeloma", "ans": "A", "e": "Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma is the typical Richter transformation of CLL; aggressive transformation occurs in 5-10 percent of CLL patients.<br><br>Diagnosis by lymph node biopsy showing diffuse large B-cell infiltrate with CD20 positive immunophenotype, often clonally related to underlying CLL. Treatment with R-CHOP chemotherapy. Poor prognosis with median survival under 12 months.<br><br>AML (option B) is not typical Richter; Hodgkin lymphoma (option C) is rare Richter variant (over DLBCL); myeloma (option D) is plasma cell not Richter, none being typical Richter transformation like DLBCL.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Rouleaux formation and bone pain suggest:", "a": "CML", "b": "Multiple myeloma", "c": "Hodgkin lymphoma", "d": "AML", "ans": "B", "e": "Multiple myeloma fits rouleaux formation and bone pain; elevated monoclonal protein increases RBC stacking producing rouleaux while plasma cell proliferation causes lytic bone disease.<br><br>Diagnosis by serum protein electrophoresis showing M-protein, urine Bence Jones protein, bone marrow showing over 10 percent plasma cells, and CRAB criteria. Treatment includes proteasome inhibitors, immunomodulatory drugs, corticosteroids, and autologous stem cell transplantation.<br><br>CML (option A) features Philadelphia chromosome; Hodgkin lymphoma (option C) features Reed-Sternberg cells; AML (option D) features myeloblasts, none fitting rouleaux with bone pain like multiple myeloma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Bence Jones proteins are:", "a": "Fibrin fragments", "b": "Albumin fragments", "c": "Heavy chains", "d": "Light chains", "ans": "D", "e": "Bence Jones proteins are urinary light chains in multiple myeloma; kappa or lambda free immunoglobulin light chains filter through glomeruli appearing in urine.<br><br>Detected by urine protein electrophoresis or serum free light chain assay (more sensitive). Combined with serum protein electrophoresis showing M-protein. Treatment includes proteasome inhibitors (bortezomib), immunomodulatory drugs (lenalidomide), corticosteroids, and autologous stem cell transplantation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Fibrin fragments (option A) are D-dimer; albumin fragments (option B) are degradation products; heavy chains (option C) are different immunoglobulin component, none being Bence Jones like light chains.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "CRAB criteria in multiple myeloma includes:", "a": "Leukocytosis", "b": "Hypercalcemia", "c": "Polycythemia", "d": "Hypocalcemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Hypercalcaemia is one component of CRAB criteria in multiple myeloma; osteoclast activation from plasma cell cytokines produces bone resorption and calcium release.<br><br>Full CRAB criteria: C: hypercalcaemia (over 11 mg/dL). R: renal impairment (creatinine over 2 mg/dL). A: anaemia (Hb under 10 g/dL). B: bone lesions (lytic on imaging). Treatment includes proteasome inhibitors, immunomodulatory drugs, corticosteroids, and autologous stem cell transplantation.<br><br>Leukocytosis (option A) is not CRAB criterion; polycythaemia (option C) is not CRAB; hypocalcaemia (option D) is opposite (hypercalcaemia occurs), none being CRAB criterion like hypercalcaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most specific diagnostic test for multiple myeloma:", "a": "Peripheral smear", "b": "Reticulocyte count", "c": "ESR", "d": "Serum protein electrophoresis", "ans": "D", "e": "Serum protein electrophoresis is most specific diagnostic test for multiple myeloma; identifies monoclonal protein (M-protein) spike.<br><br>Combined with urine protein electrophoresis (Bence Jones), serum free light chain assay, bone marrow biopsy showing over 10 percent plasma cells, and CRAB criteria for full diagnosis. Treatment includes proteasome inhibitors, immunomodulatory drugs, corticosteroids, and autologous stem cell transplantation.<br><br>Peripheral smear (option A) shows rouleaux but non-specific; reticulocyte count (option B) is non-specific; ESR (option C) is elevated but non-specific, none being as specific as serum protein electrophoresis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Lytic bone lesions in myeloma are due to:", "a": "Osteoclast activation", "b": "Vitamin deficiency", "c": "Osteoblast inhibition", "d": "Infection", "ans": "A", "e": "Osteoclast activation causes lytic bone lesions in multiple myeloma; plasma cell cytokines (RANKL, MIP-1 alpha) stimulate osteoclast resorption.<br><br>Mechanism includes increased bone resorption and reduced bone formation producing lytic lesions on imaging. Bisphosphonates (zoledronate) reduce skeletal events. Combined with radiation therapy for symptomatic lesions and addressing underlying myeloma. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Vitamin deficiency (option B) is unrelated; osteoblast inhibition (option C) is contributory not principal; infection (option D) is osteomyelitis not myeloma, none being myeloma lytic lesion mechanism like osteoclast activation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Backbone therapy for multiple myeloma commonly includes:", "a": "Iron therapy", "b": "Antihistamines", "c": "Proteasome inhibitor chemotherapy", "d": "Antibiotics", "ans": "C", "e": "Proteasome inhibitor chemotherapy is backbone of multiple myeloma therapy; bortezomib and carfilzomib block protein degradation in plasma cells.<br><br>Combined with immunomodulatory drugs (lenalidomide, thalidomide), corticosteroids (dexamethasone), and autologous stem cell transplantation in transplant-eligible patients. Side effects of bortezomib include peripheral neuropathy and thrombocytopenia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Iron therapy (option A) is for iron deficiency; antihistamines (option B) are for allergy; antibiotics (option D) are for infection, none being myeloma backbone therapy like proteasome inhibitors.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Reed–Sternberg cells are diagnostic of:", "a": "Hodgkin lymphoma", "b": "CLL", "c": "AML", "d": "Non-Hodgkin lymphoma", "ans": "A", "e": "Reed-Sternberg cells are diagnostic of Hodgkin lymphoma; these binucleate or multinucleate giant cells with prominent nucleoli are pathognomonic.<br><br>Subtypes include classical (nodular sclerosis most common, mixed cellularity, lymphocyte-rich, lymphocyte-depleted) and nodular lymphocyte predominant. Diagnosis by lymph node biopsy showing Reed-Sternberg cells in inflammatory background. Treatment includes ABVD chemotherapy and radiotherapy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>CLL (option B) features smudge cells; AML (option C) features Auer rods; non-Hodgkin lymphoma (option D) lacks Reed-Sternberg cells, none being Reed-Sternberg-diagnostic like Hodgkin lymphoma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Classical B symptoms include:", "a": "Headache and seizures", "b": "Fever, night sweats and weight loss", "c": "Rash and itching", "d": "Edema and dyspnea", "ans": "B", "e": "Fever, night sweats, and weight loss define classical B symptoms in lymphoma; these constitutional symptoms have adverse prognostic significance.<br><br>Fever over 38°C, drenching night sweats, weight loss over 10 percent in 6 months. Combined with Ann Arbor staging guides treatment. B symptoms more common in advanced disease. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Headache and seizures (option A) are CNS not B symptoms; rash and itching (option C) are non-specific; oedema and dyspnoea (option D) are cardiac or pulmonary, none being classical B symptoms like fever-night sweats-weight loss.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hodgkin lymphoma spreads primarily:", "a": "Random hematogenous", "b": "Only extranodal", "c": "Via nerves", "d": "Contiguously between nodes", "ans": "D", "e": "Hodgkin lymphoma spreads contiguously between nodes; orderly lymphatic spread from one nodal group to adjacent group characterises this disease.<br><br>Distinguishing from non-Hodgkin lymphoma (haematogenous non-contiguous spread). Ann Arbor staging classifies extent based on this contiguous pattern. Treatment includes ABVD (doxorubicin, bleomycin, vinblastine, dacarbazine) chemotherapy and radiotherapy for early disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Random haematogenous (option A) is non-Hodgkin pattern; only extranodal (option B) is uncommon; via nerves (option C) is perineural spread (head/neck cancers), none being Hodgkin spread pattern like contiguous nodal.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Ann Arbor stage III indicates:", "a": "Single node region", "b": "Only bone marrow disease", "c": "Both sides of diaphragm involvement", "d": "Extranodal organ only", "ans": "C", "e": "Both sides of diaphragm involvement defines Ann Arbor stage III; lymph nodes affected above and below diaphragm.<br><br>Stage I: single nodal site. Stage II: two or more nodal sites on same side of diaphragm. Stage III: nodal sites on both sides of diaphragm. Stage IV: extranodal involvement (liver, bone marrow). A/B suffix for absent/present B symptoms.<br><br>Single node region (option A) is stage I; only bone marrow disease (option B) is stage IV; extranodal organ only (option D) is stage IV, none being stage III defining like bilateral diaphragm involvement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Standard first-line Hodgkin therapy:", "a": "Steroids alone", "b": "Antibiotics", "c": "Radiation only", "d": "ABVD chemotherapy", "ans": "D", "e": "ABVD chemotherapy is standard first-line Hodgkin lymphoma therapy; doxorubicin, bleomycin, vinblastine, and dacarbazine combination.<br><br>Standard 6 cycles for advanced disease, 2-4 cycles for early disease combined with radiation. Side effects include myelosuppression, alopecia, pulmonary toxicity (bleomycin), cardiotoxicity (doxorubicin), and infertility. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Steroids alone (option A) are inadequate; antibiotics (option B) are for infection; radiation only (option C) is for early-stage selected cases, none being standard Hodgkin first-line like ABVD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Non-Hodgkin lymphoma differs from Hodgkin lymphoma by:", "a": "Non-contiguous spread", "b": "Presence of Reed–Sternberg cells", "c": "Absence of lymphadenopathy", "d": "Only cervical nodes involved", "ans": "A", "e": "Non-contiguous spread distinguishes non-Hodgkin lymphoma from Hodgkin lymphoma; haematogenous dissemination rather than orderly nodal spread.<br><br>Diagnosis by lymph node biopsy showing diffuse or follicular pattern with B-cell or T-cell immunophenotype. Treatment depends on subtype: R-CHOP for DLBCL, watchful waiting or rituximab for follicular lymphoma, intensive chemotherapy for Burkitt. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Presence of Reed-Sternberg cells (option B) is opposite (Hodgkin feature); absence of lymphadenopathy (option C) is incorrect; only cervical nodes (option D) is incorrect (NHL is widespread), none distinguishing NHL like non-contiguous spread.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common origin cell in NHL:", "a": "Plasma cell", "b": "Neutrophil", "c": "B cell", "d": "T cell", "ans": "C", "e": "B cell is the most common origin of non-Hodgkin lymphoma; 85-90 percent of NHL is B-cell origin with diffuse large B-cell lymphoma and follicular lymphoma most common subtypes.<br><br>Diagnosis by lymph node biopsy showing diffuse or follicular pattern with CD20 positive immunophenotype. Treatment depends on subtype: R-CHOP for DLBCL, rituximab for follicular, intensive chemotherapy for Burkitt.<br><br>Plasma cell (option A) is multiple myeloma; neutrophil (option B) is not lymphoma origin; T cell (option D) is 10-15 percent of NHL, none being most common NHL origin like B cell.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Diagnosis of lymphoma requires:", "a": "CBC only", "b": "Excisional biopsy", "c": "CT scan only", "d": "FNAC", "ans": "B", "e": "Excisional biopsy is required for lymphoma diagnosis; whole node architecture preservation allows histology and immunophenotyping.<br><br>Fine needle aspiration is inadequate as it does not preserve architecture. Cytogenetics and molecular studies for prognostication. Combined with PET-CT for staging. Treatment depends on subtype. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>CBC only (option A) is screening; CT scan only (option C) is staging; FNAC (option D) is inadequate for lymphoma, none being adequate diagnostic technique like excisional biopsy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Tumor lysis syndrome prevention includes:", "a": "Iron therapy", "b": "Splenectomy", "c": "Blood transfusion", "d": "Allopurinol and hydration", "ans": "D", "e": "Allopurinol and hydration prevent tumour lysis syndrome; xanthine oxidase inhibitor reduces uric acid production while aggressive hydration enhances urinary excretion.<br><br>Standard allopurinol 300-600 mg daily before chemotherapy initiation. Standard 2.5-3 L/m^2 daily of normal saline or 5 percent dextrose. Rasburicase (urate oxidase) for established hyperuricaemia or very high-risk disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Iron therapy (option A) is for iron deficiency; splenectomy (option B) is for hereditary spherocytosis; blood transfusion (option C) is for anaemia, none being TLS prevention like allopurinol-hydration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hyperuricemia in tumor lysis primarily causes:", "a": "Renal failure", "b": "Seizures", "c": "Anemia", "d": "Pulmonary edema", "ans": "A", "e": "Renal failure is primary consequence of hyperuricaemia in tumour lysis syndrome; uric acid precipitates in renal tubules producing acute kidney injury.<br><br>Combined with hyperphosphataemia depositing calcium phosphate in tubules. Treatment includes IV fluids, allopurinol or rasburicase, and addressing electrolyte abnormalities. Dialysis for severe renal failure. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Seizures (option B) are from hypocalcaemia or hyponatraemia not hyperuricaemia; anaemia (option C) is non-specific; pulmonary oedema (option D) is from fluid overload, none being principal hyperuricaemia consequence like renal failure.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common childhood leukemia:", "a": "CML", "b": "CLL", "c": "ALL", "d": "AML", "ans": "C", "e": "ALL is the most common childhood leukaemia; B-cell ALL accounts for most childhood leukaemia with peak incidence 2-5 years.<br><br>Diagnosis by bone marrow showing over 20 percent lymphoblasts, immunophenotyping (CD19, CD10, TdT positive in B-ALL; CD3, CD7 in T-ALL), and cytogenetics. Treatment includes induction, consolidation, CNS prophylaxis, maintenance for 2-3 years. Cure rates 80-90 percent in standard-risk paediatric B-ALL.<br><br>CML (option A) is uncommon in children; CLL (option B) is in elderly; AML (option D) is less common than ALL in children, none being most common childhood leukaemia like ALL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "CNS prophylaxis in ALL involves:", "a": "Oral antibiotics", "b": "Intrathecal methotrexate", "c": "Steroids only", "d": "Iron", "ans": "B", "e": "Intrathecal methotrexate provides CNS prophylaxis in ALL; lymphoblasts may infiltrate CSF requiring direct intrathecal treatment as systemic chemotherapy poorly penetrates CNS.<br><br>Combined with cranial irradiation in selected high-risk patients. Standard schedule of intrathecal methotrexate during induction, consolidation, and maintenance. CNS relapse rate reduced from 50 percent to under 5 percent with prophylaxis.<br><br>Oral antibiotics (option A) are for infection prophylaxis; steroids only (option C) are part of induction but not CNS prophylaxis; iron (option D) is for iron deficiency, none being ALL CNS prophylaxis like intrathecal methotrexate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Myeloperoxidase positivity indicates lineage:", "a": "Myeloid", "b": "Lymphoid", "c": "Megakaryocytic", "d": "Plasma", "ans": "A", "e": "Myeloperoxidase positivity indicates myeloid lineage; this cytochemical stain differentiates AML (positive) from ALL (negative).<br><br>Combined with immunophenotyping (CD13, CD33, CD117 positive in AML; CD19, CD10 positive in B-ALL; CD3, CD7 positive in T-ALL). Distinguishing AML from ALL guides treatment selection (7+3 for AML versus multi-drug induction for ALL). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Lymphoid lineage (option B) is CD19/CD3 positive; megakaryocytic lineage (option C) is CD41/CD61; plasma (option D) is CD138 positive, none being MPO-positive lineage like myeloid.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hyperleukocytosis complication causes:", "a": "Bradycardia", "b": "Leukostasis", "c": "Edema", "d": "Hypoglycemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Leukostasis complicates hyperleukocytosis; markedly elevated WBC (over 100 x 10^9/L) produces microvascular obstruction by leukaemic blasts.<br><br>Features include dyspnoea, hypoxia, neurological symptoms, and retinal haemorrhages. Treatment includes leukapheresis for emergency cytoreduction, hydroxyurea, and prompt chemotherapy initiation. Combined with treating tumour lysis syndrome risk. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Bradycardia (option A) is unrelated; oedema (option C) is fluid overload not WBC; hypoglycaemia (option D) is unrelated, none being hyperleukocytosis complication like leukostasis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "APL treatment drug:", "a": "Insulin", "b": "Warfarin", "c": "Penicillin", "d": "ATRA", "ans": "D", "e": "ATRA (all-trans retinoic acid) is the treatment drug for acute promyelocytic leukaemia; this differentiating agent targets the PML-RARA fusion protein.<br><br>Combined with arsenic trioxide produces high cure rates without traditional chemotherapy. Side effects include differentiation syndrome (fever, dyspnoea, pulmonary infiltrates) requiring corticosteroids. DIC common at presentation requiring supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Insulin (option A) is for diabetes; warfarin (option B) is anticoagulant; penicillin (option C) is antibiotic, none being APL specific treatment like ATRA.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "APL associated translocation:", "a": "t(11;14)", "b": "t(8;14)", "c": "t(15;17)", "d": "t(9;22)", "ans": "C", "e": "t(15;17) is the APL-associated translocation; this produces PML-RARA fusion protein that ATRA and arsenic trioxide target.<br><br>Diagnosis by characteristic morphology (faggot cells with multiple Auer rods), cytogenetics, and molecular confirmation of PML-RARA fusion. Treatment with all-trans retinoic acid (ATRA) and arsenic trioxide produces high cure rates. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>t(11;14) (option A) is mantle cell lymphoma; t(8;14) (option B) is Burkitt lymphoma; t(9;22) (option D) is Philadelphia chromosome (CML, Ph+ ALL), none being APL translocation like t(15;17).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Smudge cells indicate fragile:", "a": "Neutrophils", "b": "Lymphocytes", "c": "RBCs", "d": "Platelets", "ans": "B", "e": "Smudge cells indicate fragile lymphocytes in CLL; mature B-lymphocyte cytoskeletal abnormalities make cells rupture during smear preparation.<br><br>Combined with absolute lymphocytosis over 5 x 10^9/L and CLL immunophenotype (CD5, CD19, CD23 positive). Treatment includes watchful waiting for early disease, chemoimmunotherapy, BTK inhibitors, and BCL2 inhibitors for advanced disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Neutrophils (option A) are not smudge cells; RBCs (option C) produce different fragments; platelets (option D) are not smudge cells, none being smudge cell origin like fragile lymphocytes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hyperviscosity syndrome manifests as:", "a": "Hematuria", "b": "Hypotension", "c": "Diarrhea", "d": "Headache and blurred vision", "ans": "D", "e": "Headache and blurred vision manifest hyperviscosity syndrome; elevated serum viscosity from monoclonal protein impairs cerebral microcirculation.<br><br>Other features include mucosal bleeding, cardiac failure, and confusion. Common in Waldenström macroglobulinaemia (IgM elevation), multiple myeloma, and polycythaemia vera. Treatment with plasma exchange (plasmapheresis) for emergency. Combined with addressing underlying disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Haematuria (option A) is renal or urological; hypotension (option B) is opposite (hyperviscosity may cause hypertension); diarrhoea (option C) is unrelated, none being hyperviscosity feature like headache-blurred vision.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "High LAP score suggests:", "a": "Leukemoid reaction", "b": "CML", "c": "Myeloma", "d": "AML", "ans": "A", "e": "Leukaemoid reaction features high LAP score; reactive granulocyte response retains normal alkaline phosphatase activity.<br><br>Distinguishes leukaemoid reaction (LAP elevated) from CML (LAP low). Causes of leukaemoid reaction include severe infection, malignancy, and corticosteroid use. Combined with Philadelphia chromosome (absent in leukaemoid) for distinction. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>CML (option B) features low LAP; myeloma (option C) features plasma cells not granulocytes; AML (option D) features myeloblasts, none being high-LAP-suggesting like leukaemoid reaction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common extranodal NHL site:", "a": "Brain", "b": "Skin", "c": "Stomach", "d": "Kidney", "ans": "C", "e": "Stomach is the most common extranodal site of non-Hodgkin lymphoma; gastric MALT lymphoma associated with H. pylori infection.<br><br>Treatment of H. pylori eradication may produce regression in early MALT lymphoma. Diagnosis by endoscopic biopsy with immunophenotyping. Combined with imaging for staging. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Brain (option A) is uncommon extranodal site (primary CNS lymphoma); skin (option B) is for cutaneous T-cell lymphoma but less common than gastric; kidney (option D) is uncommon, none being most common extranodal NHL site like stomach.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Marrow infiltration by leukemia causes:", "a": "Pancytopenia", "b": "Polycythemia", "c": "Neutrophilia", "d": "Thrombocytosis", "ans": "A", "e": "Pancytopenia results from leukaemic marrow infiltration; blasts replace normal haematopoiesis producing reduced production of all three lineages.<br><br>Features include anaemia (fatigue, dyspnoea), neutropenia (infection), and thrombocytopenia (petechiae, bleeding). Treatment of underlying leukaemia restores haematopoiesis. Combined with supportive care including transfusions and antibiotics. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Polycythaemia (option B) is opposite; neutrophilia (option C) is opposite or peripheral blasts not pancytopenia; thrombocytosis (option D) is opposite, none being leukaemic marrow infiltration consequence like pancytopenia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Monoclonal spike called:", "a": "T protein", "b": "S protein", "c": "D protein", "d": "M protein", "ans": "D", "e": "M protein describes monoclonal spike on serum protein electrophoresis; identical immunoglobulin from clonal plasma cell or lymphoid proliferation produces characteristic narrow peak.<br><br>Diagnostic of multiple myeloma, MGUS, Waldenström macroglobulinaemia, and amyloidosis. Combined with urine immunoglobulin (Bence Jones), serum free light chain assay, and bone marrow biopsy. Treatment depends on underlying disease.<br><br>T protein (option A) is not a defined entity; S protein (option B) is not a defined entity; D protein (option C) is not a defined entity, none being monoclonal spike term like M protein.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Waldenström macroglobulinemia secretes:", "a": "IgA", "b": "IgG", "c": "IgM", "d": "IgE", "ans": "C", "e": "IgM is secreted in Waldenström macroglobulinaemia; this lymphoplasmacytic lymphoma variant produces monoclonal IgM paraprotein.<br><br>Diagnosis by serum protein electrophoresis showing IgM M-protein, bone marrow showing lymphoplasmacytic infiltrate, and MYD88 L265P mutation. Treatment with rituximab, BTK inhibitors (ibrutinib), and chemoimmunotherapy. Hyperviscosity syndrome may require plasma exchange. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>IgA (option A) is multiple myeloma subtype; IgG (option B) is multiple myeloma subtype; IgE (option D) is rare myeloma subtype, none being Waldenström specific paraprotein like IgM.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Pruritus in Hodgkin lymphoma due to:", "a": "Hemolysis", "b": "Cytokines", "c": "Iron deficiency", "d": "Infection", "ans": "B", "e": "Cytokines cause pruritus in Hodgkin lymphoma; tumour-released cytokines (eosinophil-derived, IL-5, others) produce generalised itching.<br><br>Often improves with treatment of underlying lymphoma. Symptomatic management with antihistamines for severe pruritus. Combined with ABVD chemotherapy and radiotherapy as appropriate. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemolysis (option A) features anaemia and jaundice; iron deficiency (option C) features brittle nails and pica; infection (option D) is non-specific, none being Hodgkin pruritus mechanism like cytokines.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "CML blast crisis resembles:", "a": "Acute leukemia", "b": "Hemophilia", "c": "Thalassemia", "d": "Aplastic anemia", "ans": "A", "e": "CML blast crisis resembles acute leukaemia; transformation to over 20 percent blasts produces clinical and morphological picture of acute leukaemia (myeloid in 70 percent, lymphoid in 30 percent).<br><br>Diagnosis by over 20 percent blasts in bone marrow or peripheral blood, extramedullary disease (chloroma), or progressive splenomegaly with cytogenetic abnormalities. Treatment with intensive chemotherapy, third-generation TKI, and bone marrow transplantation. Poor prognosis.<br><br>Haemophilia (option B) is bleeding disorder; thalassaemia (option C) is microcytic anaemia; aplastic anaemia (option D) is hypocellular marrow, none resembling CML blast crisis like acute leukaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Marrow hypercellularity with blasts suggests:", "a": "Iron deficiency", "b": "Acute leukemia", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Aplastic anemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Acute leukaemia is suggested by marrow hypercellularity with blasts; over 20 percent blasts replacing normal haematopoiesis defines this aggressive malignancy.<br><br>Diagnosis by bone marrow showing over 20 percent blasts, immunophenotyping distinguishing ALL from AML, and cytogenetics. Treatment includes induction, consolidation, CNS prophylaxis, and maintenance for ALL. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) is microcytic anaemia with normal marrow; haemolysis (option C) features erythroid hyperplasia not blasts; aplastic anaemia (option D) is hypocellular marrow, none being hypercellular-with-blasts like acute leukaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hypercalcemia in myeloma due to:", "a": "Vitamin deficiency", "b": "Kidney failure", "c": "Infection", "d": "Increased bone resorption", "ans": "D", "e": "Increased bone resorption causes hypercalcaemia in multiple myeloma; osteoclast activation from plasma cell cytokines (RANKL, MIP-1 alpha) releases calcium from bone.<br><br>Treatment includes IV fluids, calcitonin, bisphosphonates (zoledronate, pamidronate), and addressing underlying myeloma. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing acute from chronic hypercalcaemia guides therapy intensity.<br><br>Vitamin deficiency (option A) does not cause hypercalcaemia; kidney failure (option B) typically causes hypocalcaemia; infection (option C) is non-specific, none being myeloma hypercalcaemia mechanism like bone resorption.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Emergency management of tumor lysis hyperkalemia:", "a": "Folic acid", "b": "Iron infusion", "c": "Calcium gluconate", "d": "Vitamin C", "ans": "C", "e": "Calcium gluconate is emergency management of tumour lysis hyperkalaemia with ECG changes; cardioprotective action stabilises cardiac membrane.<br><br>Combined with insulin-dextrose, salbutamol, and sodium bicarbonate to shift potassium intracellularly. Resin (calcium polystyrene sulfonate) or dialysis to remove potassium. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Folic acid (option A) is for folate deficiency; iron infusion (option B) is for iron deficiency; vitamin C (option D) is non-specific, none being hyperkalaemia emergency cardioprotection like calcium gluconate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Night sweats are classified as:", "a": "A symptoms", "b": "B symptoms", "c": "Systemic signs", "d": "Local symptoms", "ans": "B", "e": "Night sweats are classified as B symptoms in lymphoma; B symptoms include fever over 38°C, drenching night sweats, and weight loss over 10 percent in 6 months.<br><br>B symptoms carry adverse prognostic significance. Combined with Ann Arbor staging guides treatment. A/B suffix added to stage (e.g., IIIA versus IIIB). Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>A symptoms (option A) describes absence of B symptoms; systemic signs (option C) is non-specific term; local symptoms (option D) are nodal not constitutional, none being night sweats classification like B symptoms.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Minimal residual leukemia detection best by:", "a": "Platelet count", "b": "ESR", "c": "Flow cytometry/PCR", "d": "Hb level", "ans": "C", "e": "Flow cytometry and PCR are best for minimal residual disease detection in leukaemia; sensitive detection of leukaemic cells at 10^-4 to 10^-6 frequency.<br><br>Combined with conventional cytology and immunophenotyping. MRD positivity after induction predicts relapse and guides treatment intensification (transplantation, CAR-T, novel agents). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Platelet count (option A) is non-specific; ESR (option B) is non-specific; Hb level (option D) is non-specific, none being MRD detection technique like flow cytometry-PCR.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Recurrent infections in myeloma due to:", "a": "Hypogammaglobulinemia", "b": "Neutrophilia", "c": "Polycythemia", "d": "Iron deficiency", "ans": "A", "e": "Hypogammaglobulinaemia causes recurrent infections in myeloma; clonal plasma cells suppress production of normal polyclonal immunoglobulins.<br><br>Treatment includes IVIG replacement for severe infections, prophylactic antibiotics, and vaccinations. Combined with addressing underlying myeloma. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Encapsulated bacteria particular risk. Standard supportive care guides management. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Neutrophilia (option B) is opposite; polycythaemia (option C) is unrelated; iron deficiency (option D) is unrelated, none being myeloma infection mechanism like hypogammaglobulinaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Gum hypertrophy most associated with:", "a": "CLL", "b": "CML", "c": "ALL", "d": "AML", "ans": "D", "e": "AML is most associated with gum hypertrophy; monocytic subtypes (AML M4, M5) infiltrate gingiva producing characteristic gum swelling.<br><br>Diagnosis by bone marrow showing over 20 percent blasts with monocytic features, immunophenotyping (CD13, CD33, CD117, MPO positive), and cytogenetics. Treatment includes induction with cytarabine and anthracycline (7+3 regimen). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>CLL (option A) lacks gum hypertrophy; CML (option B) lacks gum hypertrophy; ALL (option C) lacks gum hypertrophy, none being gum-hypertrophy-associated like AML monocytic subtypes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Adolescent presenting with mediastinal mass and lymphoblasts in blood most likely has:", "a": "T-ALL", "b": "CML", "c": "CLL", "d": "AML", "ans": "A", "e": "T-ALL fits adolescent with mediastinal mass and lymphoblasts; T-cell ALL classically presents with thymic mediastinal mass in adolescent males alongside marrow involvement.<br><br>Diagnosis by bone marrow showing over 20 percent lymphoblasts with T-cell immunophenotype (CD3, CD7, CD2 positive, TdT positive). Mediastinal mass may cause superior vena cava obstruction requiring emergency management.<br><br>CML (option B) features Philadelphia chromosome with myeloid hyperplasia not mediastinal mass; CLL (option C) is in elderly with smudge cells; AML (option D) features myeloblasts with Auer rods, none fitting adolescent mediastinal mass like T-ALL.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Bone pain in leukemia mainly occurs due to:", "a": "Hypercalcemia", "b": "Trauma", "c": "Marrow expansion stretching periosteum", "d": "Infection", "ans": "C", "e": "Marrow expansion stretching periosteum causes leukaemia bone pain; blast proliferation expands medullary cavity producing periosteal stretch and pain.<br><br>Common in acute leukaemia and CML. Combined with cortical thinning visible on imaging. Treatment of underlying leukaemia relieves pain. Analgesia for symptomatic management. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Hypercalcaemia (option A) causes bone pain in myeloma not leukaemia; trauma (option B) is unrelated; infection (option D) is osteomyelitis not leukaemic infiltration, none being leukaemia bone pain mechanism like marrow expansion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common immediate cause of death in untreated acute leukemia:", "a": "Hyperglycemia", "b": "Infection or hemorrhage", "c": "Hypertension", "d": "Renal failure", "ans": "B", "e": "Infection or haemorrhage is the most common immediate cause of death in untreated acute leukaemia; neutropenia produces life-threatening infection while thrombocytopenia produces fatal bleeding.<br><br>Treatment includes broad-spectrum antibiotics for febrile neutropenia, platelet transfusion for severe thrombocytopenia or bleeding, red cell transfusion for symptomatic anaemia. Combined with definitive leukaemia treatment. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Hyperglycaemia (option A) is uncommon cause; hypertension (option C) is unrelated; renal failure (option D) is later complication, none being principal immediate mortality cause like infection-haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Aggressive but potentially curable non-Hodgkin lymphoma:", "a": "Follicular lymphoma", "b": "MALT lymphoma", "c": "Small lymphocytic lymphoma", "d": "Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma", "ans": "D", "e": "Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma is aggressive but potentially curable; intensive R-CHOP chemoimmunotherapy achieves cure in 60-70 percent of patients.<br><br>Diagnosis by excisional biopsy showing diffuse large B-cell infiltrate with CD20 positive immunophenotype. Treatment with R-CHOP (rituximab, cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, vincristine, prednisone) for 6 cycles. CAR-T cell therapy for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Follicular lymphoma (option A) is indolent not aggressive; MALT lymphoma (option B) is indolent; small lymphocytic lymphoma (option C) is indolent CLL-equivalent, none being aggressive-curable like DLBCL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Pain in lymph nodes after alcohol intake suggests:", "a": "Myeloma", "b": "AML", "c": "Hodgkin lymphoma", "d": "CLL", "ans": "C", "e": "Hodgkin lymphoma classically features pain in lymph nodes after alcohol intake; this rare but characteristic symptom occurs in 2-3 percent of patients.<br><br>Mechanism unclear but may relate to vasodilatation and cytokine release. Combined with painless lymphadenopathy, B symptoms (fever, night sweats, weight loss), and Reed-Sternberg cells on biopsy. Treatment includes ABVD chemotherapy and radiotherapy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Myeloma (option A) lacks alcohol-related nodal pain; AML (option B) lacks lymphadenopathy; CLL (option D) lacks alcohol-related pain, none featuring alcohol-related nodal pain like Hodgkin lymphoma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Chronic phase CML blood film shows:", "a": "Myeloid precursors at various stages", "b": "Only blasts", "c": "Pancytopenia", "d": "Plasma cells", "ans": "A", "e": "Myeloid precursors at various stages characterise chronic phase CML blood film; myeloid hyperplasia produces all stages of granulocyte maturation including myelocytes, metamyelocytes, neutrophils, basophils, and eosinophils.<br><br>Combined with Philadelphia chromosome on cytogenetics and BCR-ABL on FISH or PCR. Treatment with tyrosine kinase inhibitors (imatinib, dasatinib, nilotinib) first-line. Monitoring by quantitative BCR-ABL PCR for treatment response.<br><br>Only blasts (option B) is acute leukaemia; pancytopenia (option C) is aplastic anaemia; plasma cells (option D) are multiple myeloma, none being chronic phase CML blood findings like myeloid precursors at all stages.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Tumor lysis syndrome hyperphosphatemia commonly leads to:", "a": "Hypernatremia", "b": "Hypocalcemia", "c": "Hypokalemia", "d": "Hypercalcemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Hypocalcaemia results from hyperphosphataemia in tumour lysis syndrome; elevated phosphate binds calcium producing calcium phosphate deposition and lowered ionised calcium.<br><br>Combined with hyperkalaemia, hyperuricaemia, and acute kidney injury. Treatment includes IV fluids, allopurinol or rasburicase, calcium replacement for symptomatic hypocalcaemia, and phosphate binders. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Hypernatraemia (option A) is unrelated; hypokalaemia (option C) is opposite (hyperkalaemia occurs); hypercalcaemia (option D) is opposite, none being TLS hyperphosphataemia consequence like hypocalcaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Best laboratory parameter distinguishing leukemoid reaction from CML:", "a": "ESR", "b": "Hemoglobin level", "c": "Platelet count", "d": "LAP score", "ans": "D", "e": "LAP score is the best laboratory parameter distinguishing leukaemoid reaction from CML; LAP elevated in reactive granulocytes (leukaemoid) but reduced in CML granulocytes.<br><br>Combined with Philadelphia chromosome on cytogenetics (positive in CML, negative in leukaemoid). Causes of leukaemoid reaction include severe infection, malignancy, and corticosteroid use. Treatment of underlying cause resolves leukaemoid. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>ESR (option A) is non-specific; haemoglobin level (option B) is non-specific; platelet count (option C) is variable in both, none being as specific as LAP score for CML-leukaemoid distinction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Typical immunophenotype of CLL cells:", "a": "CD19 CD5 CD23 positive", "b": "CD3 positive", "c": "CD34 positive", "d": "MPO positive", "ans": "A", "e": "CD19, CD5, and CD23 positive immunophenotype defines CLL cells; this combination distinguishes CLL from other B-cell lymphoproliferative disorders.<br><br>CD5 is a T-cell marker but expressed aberrantly in CLL B-cells. Combined with absolute lymphocytosis over 5 x 10^9/L and bone marrow showing lymphocytic infiltration. Treatment includes watchful waiting for early disease, chemoimmunotherapy, BTK inhibitors (ibrutinib), and BCL2 inhibitors (venetoclax).<br><br>CD3 positive (option B) is T-cell lineage; CD34 positive (option C) is haematopoietic precursors; MPO positive (option D) is myeloid, none being CLL immunophenotype like CD19-CD5-CD23.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Renal damage in multiple myeloma occurs mainly due to:", "a": "Infection", "b": "Hypertension", "c": "Light chain deposition in tubules", "d": "Stones", "ans": "C", "e": "Light chain deposition in tubules causes renal damage in multiple myeloma; Bence Jones proteins (free immunoglobulin light chains) form casts in distal tubules producing tubular obstruction.<br><br>Combined with hypercalcaemia, dehydration, hyperuricaemia, and amyloidosis (AL type) contributing to renal failure. Treatment includes addressing underlying myeloma, plasma exchange for severe cases, and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Infection (option A) is uncommon principal cause; hypertension (option B) is not principal; stones (option D) are uncommon, none being principal myeloma renal damage mechanism like light chain tubular deposition.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Allopurinol in tumor lysis syndrome acts by:", "a": "Breaking uric acid", "b": "Inhibiting xanthine oxidase", "c": "Increasing renal excretion of potassium", "d": "Increasing calcium levels", "ans": "B", "e": "Inhibiting xanthine oxidase is allopurinol's mechanism in tumour lysis syndrome; blocks conversion of hypoxanthine and xanthine to uric acid reducing uric acid production.<br><br>Standard dose 300-600 mg daily before chemotherapy initiation. Combined with aggressive hydration. Rasburicase (urate oxidase) converts existing uric acid to allantoin for established hyperuricaemia or very high-risk disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Breaking uric acid (option A) is rasburicase mechanism; increasing renal potassium excretion (option C) is loop diuretic; increasing calcium (option D) is unrelated, none being allopurinol mechanism like xanthine oxidase inhibition.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Anemia in leukemia primarily results from:", "a": "Hemolysis", "b": "Blood loss", "c": "Iron deficiency", "d": "Marrow infiltration by blasts", "ans": "D", "e": "Marrow infiltration by blasts causes anaemia in leukaemia; leukaemic blasts replace normal erythroid precursors producing reduced red cell production.<br><br>Combined with neutropenia and thrombocytopenia (pancytopenia). Treatment of underlying leukaemia restores haematopoiesis. Supportive care with transfusions and antibiotics. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Haemolysis (option A) is not principal leukaemia anaemia mechanism; blood loss (option B) is not principal; iron deficiency (option C) is unrelated, none being leukaemia principal anaemia mechanism like marrow blast infiltration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common subtype of Hodgkin lymphoma:", "a": "Lymphocyte depleted", "b": "Nodular sclerosis", "c": "Lymphocyte rich", "d": "Mixed cellularity", "ans": "B", "e": "Nodular sclerosis is the most common Hodgkin lymphoma subtype; accounts for 60-80 percent of classical Hodgkin lymphoma cases.<br><br>Histology shows lacunar Reed-Sternberg cells in fibrous bands. Common in young adults with mediastinal involvement. Treatment includes ABVD chemotherapy and radiotherapy for early disease. Excellent prognosis with cure rates over 80 percent. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Lymphocyte depleted (option A) is rare aggressive subtype; lymphocyte rich (option C) is uncommon; mixed cellularity (option D) is second most common, none being most common Hodgkin subtype like nodular sclerosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Burkitt lymphoma is strongly associated with infection by:", "a": "EBV", "b": "HIV", "c": "CMV", "d": "HBV", "ans": "A", "e": "EBV is strongly associated with Burkitt lymphoma; particularly endemic (African) Burkitt lymphoma with 95 percent EBV-positive while sporadic Burkitt is 30 percent EBV-positive.<br><br>Diagnosis by characteristic starry sky appearance on histology, MYC translocation (t(8;14) most common), and high proliferation index (Ki-67 over 95 percent). Treatment with intensive chemotherapy regimens producing high cure rates.<br><br>HIV (option B) is associated with various lymphomas but not specifically Burkitt; CMV (option C) is unrelated to Burkitt; HBV (option D) is unrelated to Burkitt, none being principal Burkitt association like EBV.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Starry-sky appearance on histology is characteristic of:", "a": "Myeloma", "b": "CLL", "c": "Burkitt lymphoma", "d": "AML", "ans": "C", "e": "Starry sky appearance characterises Burkitt lymphoma histology; tingible body macrophages (containing apoptotic debris) appear as 'stars' in 'sky' of densely packed neoplastic B-cells.<br><br>Combined with MYC translocation (t(8;14) most common), high proliferation index (Ki-67 over 95 percent), and EBV association in endemic form. Treatment with intensive chemotherapy regimens. Tumour lysis syndrome major risk requiring aggressive prophylaxis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Myeloma (option A) features plasma cells; CLL (option B) features mature lymphocytes; AML (option D) features myeloblasts, none featuring starry sky like Burkitt lymphoma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Accelerated phase of CML is marked by:", "a": "Normal CBC", "b": "Severe anemia only", "c": "Thrombocytopenia only", "d": "Increasing blasts and basophils", "ans": "D", "e": "Increasing blasts and basophils mark accelerated phase of CML; 10-19 percent blasts in blood or marrow, over 20 percent basophils, or progressive splenomegaly defines accelerated phase.<br><br>Treatment with intensive chemotherapy, third-generation tyrosine kinase inhibitors (ponatinib for T315I mutation), and bone marrow transplantation. Poor prognosis compared to chronic phase. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Normal CBC (option A) is chronic phase; severe anaemia only (option B) is not defining; thrombocytopenia only (option C) is not defining, none being accelerated phase features like blasts-basophils increase.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common initial site involved in Hodgkin lymphoma:", "a": "Axillary nodes", "b": "Abdominal nodes", "c": "Cervical lymph nodes", "d": "Inguinal nodes", "ans": "C", "e": "Cervical lymph nodes are most commonly initially involved in Hodgkin lymphoma; 60-80 percent of patients present with painless cervical lymphadenopathy.<br><br>Combined with mediastinal involvement (common in nodular sclerosis), B symptoms (fever, night sweats, weight loss), and Reed-Sternberg cells on biopsy. Treatment includes ABVD chemotherapy and radiotherapy. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Axillary nodes (option A) are less common initial site; abdominal nodes (option B) suggest non-Hodgkin lymphoma; inguinal nodes (option D) are uncommon initial site, none being most common Hodgkin initial site like cervical nodes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Definitive curative therapy for refractory leukemia:", "a": "Bone marrow transplantation", "b": "Antibiotics", "c": "Iron therapy", "d": "Splenectomy", "ans": "A", "e": "Bone marrow transplantation is definitive curative therapy for refractory leukaemia; HLA-matched donor stem cells replace defective haematopoiesis with graft-versus-leukaemia effect.<br><br>Indications include refractory or relapsed acute leukaemia, CML accelerated or blast phase, and high-risk myelodysplastic syndrome. Mortality 10-30 percent depending on regimen. Combined with conditioning. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Antibiotics (option B) are for infection; iron therapy (option C) is for iron deficiency; splenectomy (option D) is for hypersplenism, none being curative for refractory leukaemia like marrow transplantation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most sensitive imaging modality for detecting myeloma bone lesions:", "a": "X-ray chest", "b": "MRI", "c": "Ultrasound", "d": "CT brain", "ans": "B", "e": "MRI is most sensitive imaging for detecting myeloma bone lesions; detects marrow infiltration before lytic lesions visible on X-ray.<br><br>Whole-body MRI or low-dose whole-body CT replacing traditional skeletal survey. Combined with serum protein electrophoresis, urine Bence Jones, serum free light chain assay, bone marrow biopsy, and CRAB criteria. Treatment includes proteasome inhibitors, immunomodulatory drugs, corticosteroids, and autologous stem cell transplantation.<br><br>X-ray chest (option A) limited sensitivity; ultrasound (option C) does not show bone; CT brain (option D) is unrelated, none being most sensitive for myeloma bone lesions like MRI.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Symptoms of hypercalcemia include:", "a": "Bradycardia", "b": "Sweating", "c": "Hypotension", "d": "Polyuria and confusion", "ans": "D", "e": "Polyuria and confusion are symptoms of hypercalcaemia; impaired ADH response causes polyuria while elevated calcium produces neurological symptoms.<br><br>Other features include bone pain, kidney stones, abdominal pain, constipation, and altered mental status (stones, bones, abdominal groans, psychiatric overtones). Treatment includes IV fluids, calcitonin, bisphosphonates, and addressing underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Bradycardia (option A) is hypothermia or vagal; sweating (option B) is hypoglycaemia; hypotension (option C) is hypovolaemia, none being hypercalcaemia features like polyuria-confusion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child with Down syndrome develops acute leukemia characterized by megakaryoblast proliferation. The leukemia type is:", "a": "CML", "b": "CLL", "c": "AML M7", "d": "ALL", "ans": "C", "e": "AML M7 (acute megakaryoblastic leukaemia) is the leukaemia type in Down syndrome child with megakaryoblast proliferation; trisomy 21 specifically predisposes to this rare subtype.<br><br>Diagnosis by megakaryocytic immunophenotype (CD41, CD61 positive) and characteristic megakaryoblasts. Transient abnormal myelopoiesis (TAM) in neonates may precede development. Treatment with intensive chemotherapy with good outcomes in Down syndrome children.<br><br>CML (option A) is not Down syndrome-associated; CLL (option B) is in elderly not children; ALL (option D) is more common but does not fit megakaryoblast specifically, none being Down syndrome megakaryoblastic specific like AML M7.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Bone marrow blasts exceeding 20% define:", "a": "Acute leukemia", "b": "Myelodysplasia", "c": "Chronic leukemia", "d": "Lymphoma", "ans": "A", "e": "Acute leukaemia is defined by bone marrow blasts exceeding 20 percent; this WHO criterion distinguishes acute from chronic leukaemia.<br><br>Combined with immunophenotyping distinguishing AML (CD13, CD33, CD117, MPO positive) from ALL (lymphoid markers). Treatment includes induction (7+3 for AML, multi-drug for ALL), consolidation, CNS prophylaxis for ALL, and maintenance for ALL.<br><br>Myelodysplasia (option B) features under 20 percent blasts with dysplasia; chronic leukaemia (option C) features mature cells; lymphoma (option D) is solid lymphoid tissue, none defined by over 20 percent blasts like acute leukaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A myeloma patient develops headache, visual blurring and mucosal bleeding due to increased serum viscosity. Immediate treatment is:", "a": "Splenectomy", "b": "Iron infusion", "c": "Steroids", "d": "Plasmapheresis", "ans": "D", "e": "Plasmapheresis is immediate treatment for myeloma hyperviscosity syndrome; removes excess paraprotein reducing serum viscosity.<br><br>Indications include headache, visual blurring, mucosal bleeding, and neurological symptoms. Multiple sessions may be required. Combined with addressing underlying myeloma. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Splenectomy (option A) is for hereditary spherocytosis; iron infusion (option B) is for iron deficiency; steroids (option C) are part of myeloma treatment not emergency hyperviscosity, none being hyperviscosity emergency like plasmapheresis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "An elderly asymptomatic patient is found to have persistent lymphocytosis on routine CBC and smudge cells on smear. Most likely diagnosis:", "a": "AML", "b": "CLL", "c": "CML", "d": "ALL", "ans": "B", "e": "CLL fits elderly asymptomatic patient with persistent lymphocytosis and smudge cells; mature B-cell accumulation produces this characteristic pattern.<br><br>Diagnosis by lymphocytosis over 5 x 10^9/L, immunophenotyping (CD5, CD19, CD23 positive), and bone marrow showing lymphocytic infiltration. Rai or Binet staging guides treatment. Treatment includes watchful waiting for early disease, chemoimmunotherapy, BTK inhibitors, and BCL2 inhibitors.<br><br>AML (option A) features myeloblasts; CML (option C) features myeloid hyperplasia; ALL (option D) features lymphoblasts in younger patients, none fitting elderly asymptomatic lymphocytosis with smudge cells like CLL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "During tumor lysis syndrome, which electrolyte abnormality most commonly triggers fatal arrhythmia?", "a": "Hypernatremia", "b": "Hypophosphatemia", "c": "Hyperkalemia", "d": "Hypocalcemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Hyperkalaemia most commonly triggers fatal arrhythmia in tumour lysis syndrome; elevated potassium produces ventricular fibrillation or asystole.<br><br>ECG features include peaked T waves, prolonged PR interval, widened QRS, and eventually sine wave pattern. Treatment includes calcium gluconate (cardioprotection), insulin-dextrose, salbutamol, sodium bicarbonate, and dialysis for severe cases. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Hypernatraemia (option A) is unrelated; hypophosphataemia (option B) is opposite (hyperphosphataemia occurs); hypocalcaemia (option D) causes tetany not principally arrhythmia, none being principal TLS arrhythmia like hyperkalaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A leukemia patient develops spontaneous gum bleeding due to decreased platelets from marrow replacement. The mechanism is:", "a": "Thrombocytopenia", "b": "Leukocytosis", "c": "Hyperviscosity", "d": "Hemolysis", "ans": "A", "e": "Thrombocytopenia causes spontaneous gum bleeding in leukaemia; marrow replacement by leukaemic blasts reduces platelet production.<br><br>Treatment includes platelet transfusion for severe thrombocytopenia (under 10 x 10^9/L) or active bleeding. Combined with addressing underlying leukaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Leukocytosis (option B) is opposite (high WBC not bleeding mechanism); hyperviscosity (option C) is plasma cell disorders; haemolysis (option D) is RBC destruction not platelet issue, none being leukaemia mucosal bleeding mechanism like thrombocytopenia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Presence of fever, weight loss and drenching night sweats in lymphoma indicates:", "a": "Remission", "b": "Early stage disease", "c": "Infection only", "d": "B symptoms", "ans": "D", "e": "B symptoms describe fever, weight loss, and drenching night sweats in lymphoma; these constitutional symptoms have adverse prognostic significance.<br><br>Fever over 38°C, drenching night sweats, weight loss over 10 percent in 6 months. Combined with Ann Arbor staging guides treatment. A/B suffix added to stage (e.g., IIIA versus IIIB). Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Remission (option A) is treatment response not symptoms; early stage disease (option B) is staging not constitutional symptoms; infection only (option C) is non-lymphoma cause, none being lymphoma constitutional symptom designation like B symptoms.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hairy cell leukemia is identified by which cytochemical marker?", "a": "MPO negative", "b": "TRAP positive", "c": "CD3 positive", "d": "PAS positive", "ans": "B", "e": "TRAP positive (tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase) identifies hairy cell leukaemia; this cytochemical marker is characteristic of hairy cell leukaemia.<br><br>Combined with characteristic hairy projections on lymphocytes, immunophenotype (CD11c, CD25, CD103, CD123 positive), and bone marrow showing 'fried-egg' appearance with reticulin fibrosis. Treatment with cladribine or pentostatin produces durable remission. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>MPO negative (option A) is non-specific; CD3 positive (option C) is T-cell lineage; PAS positive (option D) is non-specific, none being hairy cell specific marker like TRAP.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with chronic gastritis develops gastric lymphoma associated with Helicobacter pylori infection. The lymphoma type is:", "a": "MALT lymphoma", "b": "Mantle cell lymphoma", "c": "Burkitt lymphoma", "d": "Hodgkin lymphoma", "ans": "A", "e": "MALT lymphoma fits gastric lymphoma with H. pylori chronic gastritis; mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue lymphoma develops from H. pylori-driven chronic inflammation.<br><br>Diagnosis by endoscopic biopsy with immunophenotyping. H. pylori eradication may produce regression in early-stage disease (Lugano stage I-II without t(11;18)). Combined with imaging for staging. Treatment of refractory or advanced disease includes rituximab and chemotherapy.<br><br>Mantle cell lymphoma (option B) features t(11;14) and cyclin D1 overexpression; Burkitt lymphoma (option C) features t(8;14); Hodgkin lymphoma (option D) features Reed-Sternberg cells, none being H. pylori-associated gastric lymphoma like MALT.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Acute kidney injury in tumor lysis syndrome occurs due to:", "a": "Calcium deposition", "b": "Dehydration", "c": "Uric acid crystal deposition", "d": "Hemoglobinuria", "ans": "C", "e": "Uric acid crystal deposition causes acute kidney injury in tumour lysis syndrome; uric acid precipitates in renal tubules producing obstruction.<br><br>Combined with calcium phosphate deposition from hyperphosphataemia and dehydration. Treatment includes IV fluids, allopurinol or rasburicase, and dialysis for severe renal failure. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Calcium deposition (option A) is contributory not principal; dehydration (option B) is contributory; haemoglobinuria (option D) is intravascular haemolysis not TLS, none being principal TLS renal injury mechanism like uric acid crystals.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A young adult with painless cervical lymphadenopathy is diagnosed with Hodgkin lymphoma. The tumor is highly sensitive to:", "a": "Diuretics", "b": "Radiotherapy", "c": "Iron therapy", "d": "Anticoagulation", "ans": "B", "e": "Radiotherapy is highly effective in Hodgkin lymphoma; this disease is markedly radiosensitive allowing curative treatment in early-stage disease.<br><br>Combined with ABVD chemotherapy (often 2-4 cycles + involved-field radiotherapy) for early-stage disease. Advanced disease treated with 6 cycles of ABVD. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Diuretics (option A) are for fluid overload; iron therapy (option C) is for iron deficiency; anticoagulation (option D) is for thrombosis, none being Hodgkin first-line modality like radiotherapy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Flow cytometry of lymphocytes reveals CD19, CD5 and CD23 positivity confirming:", "a": "ALL", "b": "AML", "c": "Myeloma", "d": "CLL", "ans": "D", "e": "CLL is confirmed by CD19, CD5, and CD23 positive flow cytometry; this combination distinguishes CLL from other B-cell lymphoproliferative disorders.<br><br>Combined with absolute lymphocytosis over 5 x 10^9/L and bone marrow showing lymphocytic infiltration. Rai or Binet staging guides treatment. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>ALL (option A) features TdT and CD10 positive lymphoblasts; AML (option B) features CD13, CD33, MPO positive myeloblasts; myeloma (option C) features CD138, CD38 positive plasma cells, none being CD19-CD5-CD23 positive like CLL.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Plasma cells in bone marrow primarily function to produce:", "a": "Hemoglobin", "b": "Immunoglobulins", "c": "Complement proteins", "d": "Clotting factors", "ans": "B", "e": "Plasma cells produce immunoglobulins in bone marrow; terminally differentiated B-cells secrete antibodies in response to antigenic stimulation.<br><br>Mature plasma cells reside in bone marrow producing IgG, IgA, IgM, IgE, and IgD. Clonal plasma cell expansion produces multiple myeloma with monoclonal paraprotein. Treatment depends on underlying disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemoglobin (option A) is produced by erythrocytes; complement proteins (option C) are produced by hepatocytes; clotting factors (option D) are mostly hepatic, none being plasma cell function like immunoglobulin production.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 5-year-old child with fever and bone pain is diagnosed with leukemia. The most common leukemia in this age group is:", "a": "CLL", "b": "AML", "c": "ALL", "d": "CML", "ans": "C", "e": "ALL is most common in 5-year-old child with fever and bone pain; B-cell ALL is the most common childhood leukaemia with peak incidence 2-5 years.<br><br>Diagnosis by bone marrow showing over 20 percent lymphoblasts, immunophenotyping (CD19, CD10, TdT positive in B-ALL; CD3, CD7 in T-ALL), and cytogenetics. Treatment includes induction, consolidation, CNS prophylaxis, maintenance for 2-3 years.<br><br>CLL (option A) is in elderly; AML (option B) is less common in children than ALL; CML (option D) is uncommon in children, none being most common 5-year-old leukaemia like ALL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Anemia in multiple myeloma occurs mainly because of:", "a": "Blood loss", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Marrow replacement by plasma cells", "ans": "D", "e": "Marrow replacement by plasma cells causes anaemia in multiple myeloma; clonal plasma cell expansion displaces normal erythroid precursors.<br><br>Combined with renal impairment reducing erythropoietin, chronic disease inflammatory effects, and treatment-related myelosuppression. Treatment includes proteasome inhibitors, immunomodulatory drugs, corticosteroids, and autologous stem cell transplantation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Blood loss (option A) is not principal myeloma anaemia mechanism; iron deficiency (option B) is unrelated; haemolysis (option C) is uncommon, none being principal myeloma anaemia mechanism like plasma cell marrow replacement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Extremely high leukocyte counts often exceeding 100,000/mm³ are most characteristic of:", "a": "CML", "b": "CLL", "c": "ALL", "d": "AML", "ans": "A", "e": "CML produces extremely high leukocyte counts often exceeding 100,000/mm^3; myeloid hyperplasia drives marked leukocytosis with all stages of granulocyte maturation.<br><br>Combined with Philadelphia chromosome on cytogenetics, BCR-ABL on FISH or PCR, and low LAP score. Treatment with tyrosine kinase inhibitors (imatinib, dasatinib, nilotinib) first-line. Monitoring by quantitative BCR-ABL PCR. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>CLL (option B) features lymphocytosis usually under 100,000; ALL (option C) features lymphoblasts variable count; AML (option D) features myeloblasts variable count, none routinely exceeding 100,000 like CML.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Stage IV Hodgkin lymphoma indicates:", "a": "Single lymph node region", "b": "Extranodal organ involvement", "c": "Only mediastinal nodes", "d": "Only splenic disease", "ans": "B", "e": "Extranodal organ involvement defines Ann Arbor stage IV Hodgkin lymphoma; liver, bone marrow, lung, or other organ involvement.<br><br>Stage I: single nodal site. Stage II: two or more nodal sites on same side of diaphragm. Stage III: nodal sites on both sides of diaphragm. Stage IV: extranodal involvement.<br><br>Single lymph node region (option A) is stage I; only mediastinal nodes (option C) is stage I or II; only splenic disease (option D) is stage III (spleen counts as nodal), none defining stage IV like extranodal organ involvement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Eligible multiple myeloma patients benefit most from:", "a": "Antibiotics only", "b": "Radiation only", "c": "Splenectomy", "d": "Autologous stem cell transplant", "ans": "D", "e": "Autologous stem cell transplant benefits eligible multiple myeloma patients; consolidation after induction chemotherapy significantly improves outcomes.<br><br>Indications include transplant-eligible patients (typically under 70 years with good performance status). Combined with induction (proteasome inhibitor, immunomodulatory drug, dexamethasone), stem cell collection, high-dose melphalan, and stem cell reinfusion. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Antibiotics only (option A) are for infection; radiation only (option B) is palliative for symptomatic lesions; splenectomy (option C) is for hereditary spherocytosis, none being myeloma curative-intent therapy like autologous SCT.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Rapid destruction of malignant cells during chemotherapy causing metabolic derangements is called:", "a": "Polycythemia", "b": "Hemophilia", "c": "Tumor lysis syndrome", "d": "Aplastic crisis", "ans": "C", "e": "Tumour lysis syndrome describes rapid destruction of malignant cells causing metabolic derangements; characterised by hyperkalaemia, hyperphosphataemia, hyperuricaemia, hypocalcaemia, and acute kidney injury.<br><br>Common in haematological malignancies with high tumour burden (Burkitt lymphoma, ALL, AML). Prevention with IV fluids, allopurinol, or rasburicase. Treatment includes addressing electrolyte abnormalities and dialysis for severe cases. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Polycythaemia (option A) is RBC excess; haemophilia (option B) is bleeding disorder; aplastic crisis (option D) is parvovirus B19 complication, none being chemotherapy-induced metabolic derangement like TLS.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Markedly elevated LDH level in lymphoma correlates with:", "a": "High tumor burden", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Hemorrhage", "d": "Dehydration", "ans": "A", "e": "High tumour burden correlates with markedly elevated LDH in lymphoma; tumour cell turnover releases this cytosolic enzyme.<br><br>Combined with B symptoms (fever, night sweats, weight loss), advanced stage, and elevated tumour markers (beta-2 microglobulin) as adverse prognostic factors. Treatment intensity adjusted accordingly. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option B) does not elevate LDH; haemorrhage (option C) does not principally elevate LDH; dehydration (option D) does not elevate LDH, none being lymphoma LDH elevation cause like high tumour burden.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A leukemia patient develops persistent headache and vomiting; CSF examination reveals malignant blasts indicating:", "a": "Splenic rupture", "b": "CNS involvement", "c": "Renal metastasis", "d": "Liver infiltration", "ans": "B", "e": "CNS involvement causes persistent headache and vomiting with malignant blasts in CSF; leukaemic blasts infiltrate meninges producing raised intracranial pressure.<br><br>Diagnosis by CSF examination showing blasts. Treatment with intrathecal methotrexate, cytarabine, and hydrocortisone. Combined with systemic chemotherapy and cranial irradiation for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Splenic rupture (option A) features abdominal pain; renal metastasis (option C) features renal symptoms; liver infiltration (option D) features hepatomegaly, none being persistent headache-vomiting with CSF blasts like CNS involvement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "During chemotherapy, rapid nucleic acid breakdown causes hyperuricemia resistant to prevention; the drug converting uric acid to allantoin is:", "a": "Allopurinol", "b": "Methotrexate", "c": "Prednisone", "d": "Rasburicase", "ans": "D", "e": "Rasburicase converts uric acid to allantoin; this recombinant urate oxidase rapidly degrades existing uric acid producing soluble allantoin.<br><br>Indications include established hyperuricaemia, very high-risk disease (Burkitt lymphoma, ALL with high WBC), or hyperuricaemia resistant to allopurinol prevention. Contraindicated in G6PD deficiency (causes methaemoglobinaemia). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Allopurinol (option A) inhibits xanthine oxidase preventing new uric acid not breaking existing; methotrexate (option B) is chemotherapy; prednisone (option C) is corticosteroid, none being uric acid-to-allantoin converter like rasburicase.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Bone marrow blasts containing needle-like cytoplasmic inclusions composed of fused lysosomes represent:", "a": "Myeloblasts with Auer rods", "b": "Megakaryocytes", "c": "Plasma cells", "d": "Lymphoblasts", "ans": "A", "e": "Myeloblasts with Auer rods are described as needle-like cytoplasmic inclusions composed of fused lysosomes; these crystallised primary granules are pathognomonic of AML.<br><br>Most prominent in acute promyelocytic leukaemia (APL, AML M3) where faggot cells contain multiple Auer rods. Combined with bone marrow showing over 20 percent blasts, immunophenotyping (CD13, CD33, CD117, MPO positive), and cytogenetics. Treatment includes induction with cytarabine and anthracycline.<br><br>Megakaryocytes (option B) are giant multinucleated platelets producers; plasma cells (option C) produce immunoglobulins; lymphoblasts (option D) lack Auer rods, none containing Auer rods like myeloblasts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In diffuse large B-cell lymphoma, prognosis is mainly determined by:", "a": "Serum sodium", "b": "Platelet count", "c": "Stage and histologic grade", "d": "Hemoglobin level", "ans": "C", "e": "Stage and histologic grade primarily determine prognosis in diffuse large B-cell lymphoma; Ann Arbor stage and pathological features predict outcome.<br><br>Combined with IPI (International Prognostic Index) factors: age, performance status, LDH, extranodal sites, and stage. Cell of origin (germinal centre versus activated B-cell) and double-hit lymphoma (MYC and BCL2 rearrangements) further refine prognosis. Treatment with R-CHOP for most patients.<br><br>Serum sodium (option A) is non-specific; platelet count (option B) is non-specific; haemoglobin level (option D) is non-specific, none being principal DLBCL prognostic factor like stage-grade.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with hyperleukocytosis develops dyspnea and neurological deficits due to microvascular obstruction by leukemic cells. This complication is:", "a": "DIC", "b": "Leukostasis", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Hyperviscosity syndrome", "ans": "B", "e": "Leukostasis fits hyperleukocytosis with dyspnoea and neurological deficits from microvascular obstruction; markedly elevated WBC (over 100 x 10^9/L) produces leukaemic blast microvascular obstruction.<br><br>Features include dyspnoea, hypoxia, neurological symptoms, and retinal haemorrhages. Treatment includes leukapheresis for emergency cytoreduction, hydroxyurea, and prompt chemotherapy initiation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>DIC (option A) features coagulopathy with elevated D-dimer; haemolysis (option C) features RBC destruction; hyperviscosity syndrome (option D) is plasma protein excess not leukocyte-driven, none being hyperleukocytosis microvascular obstruction like leukostasis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "After chemotherapy for leukemia, severe hyperuricemia develops; enzyme therapy rapidly lowers uric acid by oxidation to allantoin. The drug used is:", "a": "Colchicine", "b": "Probenecid", "c": "Febuxostat", "d": "Rasburicase", "ans": "D", "e": "Rasburicase rapidly lowers uric acid by oxidation to allantoin; this recombinant urate oxidase enzyme rapidly degrades existing uric acid.<br><br>Indications include established hyperuricaemia, very high-risk disease (Burkitt lymphoma, ALL with high WBC), or hyperuricaemia resistant to allopurinol prevention. Contraindicated in G6PD deficiency (causes methaemoglobinaemia). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Colchicine (option A) is for gout flare; probenecid (option B) is uricosuric for chronic gout; febuxostat (option C) is xanthine oxidase inhibitor like allopurinol, none being uric acid-degrading enzyme like rasburicase.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Gradual painless lymphadenopathy with fragile lymphocytes producing smudge cells indicates proliferation of:", "a": "Mature B lymphocytes", "b": "Monocytes", "c": "Neutrophils", "d": "Plasma cells", "ans": "A", "e": "Mature B lymphocyte proliferation produces gradual painless lymphadenopathy with smudge cells; CLL features clonal accumulation of mature B-cells.<br><br>Diagnosis by lymphocytosis over 5 x 10^9/L, immunophenotyping (CD5, CD19, CD23 positive), and bone marrow showing lymphocytic infiltration. Rai or Binet staging guides treatment. Treatment includes watchful waiting for early disease, chemoimmunotherapy, BTK inhibitors, and BCL2 inhibitors.<br><br>Monocytes (option B) produce different morphology; neutrophils (option C) are not lymphadenopathy-causing; plasma cells (option D) produce myeloma not lymphadenopathy with smudge cells, none being CLL origin like mature B-cells.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Very high ESR in multiple myeloma occurs because elevated immunoglobulins cause RBCs to stack forming:", "a": "Hemolysis", "b": "Poikilocytosis", "c": "Rouleaux formation", "d": "Agglutination", "ans": "C", "e": "Rouleaux formation produces very high ESR in multiple myeloma; elevated monoclonal immunoglobulins coat red cells increasing aggregation tendency causing stacking like coins.<br><br>Combined with serum protein electrophoresis showing M-protein, urine Bence Jones protein, bone marrow showing over 10 percent plasma cells, and CRAB criteria. Treatment includes proteasome inhibitors, immunomodulatory drugs, corticosteroids, and autologous stem cell transplantation.<br><br>Haemolysis (option A) does not cause rouleaux; poikilocytosis (option B) is variable RBC shape not stacking; agglutination (option D) is antibody-mediated cell clumping, none being elevated-immunoglobulin RBC stacking like rouleaux.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Severe mucosal bleeding in acute leukemia occurs due to critically low platelets from marrow replacement; this complication is:", "a": "Hemorrhage due to thrombocytopenia", "b": "Hemolysis", "c": "Hypercalcemia", "d": "Hyperviscosity", "ans": "A", "e": "Haemorrhage due to thrombocytopenia causes severe mucosal bleeding in acute leukaemia; marrow replacement by leukaemic blasts reduces platelet production.<br><br>Treatment includes platelet transfusion for severe thrombocytopenia (under 10 x 10^9/L) or active bleeding. Combined with addressing underlying leukaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Haemolysis (option B) is RBC destruction not bleeding mechanism; hypercalcaemia (option C) is in myeloma not bleeding mechanism; hyperviscosity (option D) is plasma cell disorders, none being acute leukaemia mucosal bleeding mechanism like thrombocytopenia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "During tumor lysis syndrome phosphate release causes calcium precipitation leading to tetany and seizures due to:", "a": "Hypernatremia", "b": "Hypocalcemia", "c": "Hypermagnesemia", "d": "Hyperglycemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Hypocalcaemia from phosphate release causes tetany and seizures in tumour lysis syndrome; elevated phosphate binds calcium producing calcium phosphate deposition and lowered ionised calcium.<br><br>Combined with hyperkalaemia, hyperuricaemia, and acute kidney injury. Treatment includes IV fluids, allopurinol or rasburicase, calcium replacement for symptomatic hypocalcaemia, and phosphate binders. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Hypernatraemia (option A) does not cause tetany; hypermagnesaemia (option C) causes neuromuscular blockade not tetany; hyperglycaemia (option D) is unrelated, none being TLS phosphate-calcium imbalance like hypocalcaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A young woman presents with petechiae, mucosal bleeding and isolated thrombocytopenia with normal PT and aPTT. Peripheral smear shows large platelets. Most likely diagnosis:", "a": "Hemophilia A", "b": "DIC", "c": "Immune thrombocytopenic purpura", "d": "Aplastic anemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Immune thrombocytopenic purpura fits young woman with petechiae, mucosal bleeding, isolated thrombocytopenia, normal coagulation, and large platelets; antibody-mediated peripheral destruction produces this pattern.<br><br>Diagnosis is by exclusion: isolated thrombocytopenia with normal CBC, normal coagulation, and no other identifiable cause. Treatment includes observation for mild disease, corticosteroids for symptomatic disease, IVIG for life-threatening bleeding, and splenectomy or rituximab for refractory disease.<br><br>Haemophilia A (option A) features prolonged aPTT and deep tissue bleeds; aplastic anaemia (option D) features pancytopenia, none fitting isolated thrombocytopenia with large platelets like ITP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Primary mechanism in immune thrombocytopenic purpura is:", "a": "Vitamin K deficiency", "b": "Platelet production failure", "c": "Bone marrow failure", "d": "Autoantibody mediated platelet destruction in spleen", "ans": "D", "e": "Autoantibody-mediated platelet destruction in spleen is the primary ITP mechanism; IgG antibodies against platelet glycoproteins opsonise platelets for splenic phagocytosis.<br><br>Most common antibodies against GPIIb/IIIa or GPIb/IX. Splenic macrophages phagocytose antibody-coated platelets through Fc receptor binding. Treatment includes corticosteroids, IVIG, anti-D, rituximab, thrombopoietin receptor agonists, and splenectomy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Vitamin K deficiency (option A) prolongs PT; platelet production failure (option B) shows decreased megakaryocytes; bone marrow failure (option C) features pancytopenia, none being the ITP-specific peripheral immune destruction mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common antibody in ITP is directed against:", "a": "Factor VIII", "b": "Platelet glycoprotein IIb/IIIa", "c": "Collagen", "d": "Fibrinogen", "ans": "B", "e": "Platelet glycoprotein IIb/IIIa is the most common antibody target in ITP; this fibrinogen receptor on platelet surface is principal target of autoantibodies.<br><br>Other targets include GPIb/IX (vWF receptor). IgG-coated platelets phagocytosed by splenic macrophages through Fc receptor binding. Treatment includes corticosteroids, IVIG, anti-D, rituximab, thrombopoietin receptor agonists, and splenectomy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Factor VIII (option A) is haemophilia A target; collagen (option C) is autoimmune target in SLE; fibrinogen (option D) is not principal ITP target, none being principal ITP antibody target like GPIIb/IIIa.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Bone marrow finding in ITP typically shows:", "a": "Fibrosis", "b": "Hypocellular marrow", "c": "Absence of megakaryocytes", "d": "Increased megakaryocytes", "ans": "D", "e": "Increased megakaryocytes characterise ITP bone marrow; compensatory increase in platelet precursors reflects peripheral destruction not production failure.<br><br>Diagnosis typically clinical without marrow biopsy. Bone marrow indicated for atypical features, older patients, or before splenectomy. Treatment includes corticosteroids, IVIG, anti-D, rituximab, thrombopoietin receptor agonists, and splenectomy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Fibrosis (option A) is myelofibrosis; hypocellular marrow (option B) is aplastic anaemia; absent megakaryocytes (option C) is amegakaryocytic thrombocytopenia, none being ITP marrow finding like increased megakaryocytes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "First-line treatment for symptomatic ITP:", "a": "Platelet transfusion only", "b": "Iron therapy", "c": "Corticosteroids", "d": "Antibiotics", "ans": "C", "e": "Corticosteroids are first-line for symptomatic ITP; prednisolone 1 mg/kg daily reduces antibody production and impairs macrophage Fc receptor function.<br><br>Standard taper over weeks to months as platelets normalise. Refractory or steroid-dependent disease may require IVIG, rituximab, thrombopoietin receptor agonists (eltrombopag, romiplostim), or splenectomy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Platelet transfusion only (option A) is for life-threatening bleeding combined with steroids; iron therapy (option B) is for iron deficiency; antibiotics (option D) are for infection, none being ITP first-line therapy like corticosteroids.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "ITP following viral infection in children is usually:", "a": "Self-limited", "b": "Chronic progressive", "c": "Malignant", "d": "Fatal", "ans": "A", "e": "Self-limited course characterises childhood ITP following viral infection; 70-80 percent of paediatric cases resolve spontaneously within 6 months without treatment.<br><br>Mechanism involves transient autoantibody production triggered by viral infection. Treatment includes observation for mild disease, corticosteroids or IVIG for significant bleeding. Persistent disease over 12 months becomes chronic ITP requiring further investigation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including paediatrician.<br><br>Chronic progressive (option B) is uncommon paediatric pattern; malignant (option C) is not ITP feature; fatal (option D) is uncommon with treatment, none describing typical paediatric viral-triggered ITP course like self-limited.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Splenectomy in ITP works by:", "a": "Decreasing antibodies in plasma directly", "b": "Increasing platelet production", "c": "Removing site of antibody-mediated platelet destruction", "d": "Increasing clotting factors", "ans": "C", "e": "Removing site of antibody-mediated platelet destruction is splenectomy mechanism in ITP; spleen is principal phagocytic site for opsonised platelets.<br><br>Indications include steroid-refractory or steroid-dependent disease. Response rates 60-80 percent with lasting remission. Pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib vaccinations before splenectomy. Long-term penicillin prophylaxis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Decreasing antibodies directly (option A) is rituximab mechanism; increasing platelet production (option B) is thrombopoietin agonist mechanism; increasing clotting factors (option D) is unrelated, none being splenectomy mechanism in ITP like destruction site removal.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which lab finding is characteristic of ITP?", "a": "Isolated thrombocytopenia", "b": "Prolonged PT", "c": "Pancytopenia", "d": "Prolonged aPTT", "ans": "A", "e": "Isolated thrombocytopenia characterises ITP; normal haemoglobin, normal WBC, and normal coagulation distinguish from other causes.<br><br>Diagnosis is by exclusion: isolated thrombocytopenia with otherwise normal CBC, normal coagulation, and no other identifiable cause. Bone marrow shows increased megakaryocytes. Treatment includes observation for mild disease, corticosteroids, IVIG, and splenectomy or rituximab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Prolonged PT (option B) is liver disease, vitamin K deficiency, warfarin; pancytopenia (option C) is aplastic anaemia or leukaemia; prolonged aPTT (option D) is haemophilia or heparin, none being ITP isolated finding like thrombocytopenia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Life-threatening bleeding in ITP is best treated acutely with:", "a": "Vitamin K", "b": "Platelet transfusion alone", "c": "Iron therapy", "d": "IV immunoglobulin", "ans": "D", "e": "IV immunoglobulin treats life-threatening ITP bleeding; saturates splenic macrophage Fc receptors blocking platelet destruction.<br><br>Standard dose 1 g/kg daily for 1-2 days. Combined with corticosteroids and platelet transfusion for major bleeding. Rapid response within 24-48 hours but transient. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Vitamin K (option A) is for warfarin reversal; platelet transfusion alone (option B) is short-lived without addressing destruction; iron therapy (option C) is for iron deficiency, none being ITP life-threatening bleeding management like IVIG.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Anti-D immunoglobulin therapy in ITP is useful because:", "a": "Stimulates platelet production", "b": "Saturates splenic Fc receptors", "c": "Increases clotting factors", "d": "Prevents hemolysis", "ans": "B", "e": "Saturating splenic Fc receptors is anti-D immunoglobulin mechanism in ITP; anti-D coats Rh-positive red cells which competitively bind Fc receptors blocking platelet destruction.<br><br>Limited to Rh-positive non-splenectomised patients. Side effects include mild haemolysis and rarely severe haemolysis. Combined with corticosteroids and IVIG for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Stimulates platelet production (option A) is thrombopoietin agonist mechanism; increases clotting factors (option C) is unrelated; prevents haemolysis (option D) is opposite (causes mild haemolysis), none being anti-D ITP mechanism like Fc receptor saturation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Von Willebrand factor primarily functions to:", "a": "Mediate platelet adhesion to subendothelium", "b": "Produce platelets", "c": "Activate thrombin", "d": "Dissolve fibrin", "ans": "A", "e": "Mediating platelet adhesion to subendothelium is vWF primary function; this large multimeric glycoprotein binds exposed collagen and platelet GPIb receptor.<br><br>Also serves as carrier protein for factor VIII protecting it from degradation. Deficiency or dysfunction causes von Willebrand disease (most common inherited bleeding disorder). Treatment includes desmopressin (releases stored vWF) or factor concentrates. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Produces platelets (option B) is thrombopoietin function; activates thrombin (option C) is factor Xa function; dissolves fibrin (option D) is plasmin function, none being vWF principal function like platelet adhesion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common inherited bleeding disorder worldwide:", "a": "Factor V deficiency", "b": "Von Willebrand disease", "c": "Platelet storage pool disease", "d": "Hemophilia A", "ans": "B", "e": "Von Willebrand disease is the most common inherited bleeding disorder worldwide; affects 0.6-1.3 percent of population with type 1 (partial quantitative deficiency) most common.<br><br>Diagnosis by reduced vWF antigen, reduced vWF activity (ristocetin cofactor), reduced factor VIII, and prolonged bleeding time. Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease.<br><br>Factor V deficiency (option A) is rare; haemophilia A (option D) is less common than vWD (1 in 5000 males vs 1 percent population), none being most common inherited bleeding disorder like vWD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Typical bleeding manifestation in von Willebrand disease:", "a": "Hemarthrosis", "b": "Retroperitoneal bleeding", "c": "Deep muscle hematoma", "d": "Mucocutaneous bleeding", "ans": "D", "e": "Mucocutaneous bleeding characterises von Willebrand disease; impaired platelet adhesion produces typical platelet-type bleeding pattern.<br><br>Features include epistaxis, menorrhagia, gum bleeding, and easy bruising. Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Haemarthrosis (option A) is haemophilia; retroperitoneal bleeding (option B) is haemophilia; deep muscle haematoma (option C) is haemophilia, none being vWD bleeding pattern like mucocutaneous.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Screening test most sensitive for vWD:", "a": "Thrombin time", "b": "D-dimer", "c": "Bleeding time / platelet function assay", "d": "PT", "ans": "C", "e": "Bleeding time and platelet function assay are most sensitive screens for vWD; impaired platelet adhesion prolongs bleeding time.<br><br>Combined with vWF antigen, vWF activity (ristocetin cofactor), and factor VIII levels for diagnosis. PFA-100 (platelet function analyser) more standardised than traditional bleeding time. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Thrombin time (option A) is for fibrinogen abnormalities; D-dimer (option B) is for DIC and thrombosis; PT (option D) is for extrinsic pathway, none being vWD-specific screening like bleeding time.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Desmopressin treats vWD by:", "a": "Activating thrombin", "b": "Releasing vWF from endothelial stores", "c": "Increasing platelet count", "d": "Increasing fibrinogen", "ans": "B", "e": "Releasing vWF from endothelial stores is desmopressin mechanism in vWD; this synthetic ADH analogue stimulates Weibel-Palade body release.<br><br>Standard dose 0.3 mcg/kg IV or subcutaneously. Effective for type 1 vWD and mild type 2A. Side effects include hyponatraemia, facial flushing, and tachyphylaxis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Activating thrombin (option A) is not desmopressin mechanism; increasing platelet count (option C) is not mechanism; increasing fibrinogen (option D) is unrelated, none being desmopressin mechanism like vWF release from stores.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Factor VIII replacement in vWD is indicated when:", "a": "Petechiae only", "b": "Minor bruising", "c": "Mild epistaxis", "d": "Major surgery or severe bleeding", "ans": "D", "e": "Factor VIII replacement in vWD is indicated for major surgery or severe bleeding; severe disease or non-responders to desmopressin require factor VIII/vWF concentrates.<br><br>Plasma-derived or recombinant concentrates containing vWF preferred. Standard dose 30-60 IU/kg before procedure. Combined with maintenance dosing as needed. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Petechiae only (option A) is not vWD presentation; minor bruising (option B) is observation; mild epistaxis (option C) is desmopressin or tranexamic acid, none requiring factor replacement like major surgery-severe bleeding.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Fresh frozen plasma helps vWD by providing:", "a": "vWF and clotting factors", "b": "Iron", "c": "Vitamin K", "d": "Platelets", "ans": "A", "e": "vWF and clotting factors are provided by fresh frozen plasma in vWD; contains all coagulation factors including vWF and factor VIII.<br><br>Used when specific factor concentrates unavailable. Volume overload limitation. Combined with addressing underlying vWD. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing FFP from cryoprecipitate (more concentrated vWF).<br><br>Iron (option B) is in supplements not FFP; vitamin K (option C) is in supplements; platelets (option D) are in platelet transfusion not FFP, none being FFP components for vWD like vWF and clotting factors.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Ristocetin cofactor assay evaluates:", "a": "RBC fragility", "b": "Thrombin generation", "c": "Platelet aggregation mediated by vWF", "d": "Fibrinolysis", "ans": "C", "e": "Platelet aggregation mediated by vWF is assessed by ristocetin cofactor assay; ristocetin promotes vWF binding to platelet GPIb measuring vWF activity.<br><br>Reduced in vWD reflecting reduced vWF function. Combined with vWF antigen (quantitative), factor VIII level, and bleeding time. Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>RBC fragility (option A) is osmotic fragility test; thrombin generation (option B) is thrombin time; fibrinolysis (option D) is D-dimer, none being assessed by ristocetin cofactor like vWF-mediated platelet aggregation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In vWD platelet count is usually:", "a": "Increased", "b": "Normal", "c": "Absent", "d": "Severely decreased", "ans": "B", "e": "Platelet count is usually normal in vWD; this distinguishes vWD from primary platelet disorders.<br><br>Platelet function abnormal due to impaired vWF-mediated adhesion. Combined with reduced vWF antigen, reduced vWF activity (ristocetin cofactor), reduced factor VIII, and prolonged bleeding time. Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Increased (option A) is essential thrombocythaemia; absent (option C) is not vWD; severely decreased (option D) is ITP or marrow failure, none being vWD platelet count like normal.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 6-year-old child develops bruising after viral infection; platelets 20,000/µL but Hb and WBC normal. Best initial management:", "a": "Chemotherapy", "b": "Immediate splenectomy", "c": "Observation if mild bleeding", "d": "Bone marrow transplant", "ans": "C", "e": "Observation if mild bleeding is best initial management for paediatric ITP with platelets 20,000/µL but only minimal symptoms; most cases self-resolve.<br><br>Treatment indications include significant bleeding (mucosal, GI, intracranial), platelets under 10,000/µL, or before procedures. Treatment options include corticosteroids, IVIG, and anti-D. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including paediatrician. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Chemotherapy (option A) is for malignancy; immediate splenectomy (option B) is for refractory disease; bone marrow transplant (option D) is for severe aplastic anaemia, none being paediatric mild-bleeding ITP management like observation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A woman with ITP develops severe menorrhagia and platelets 8,000/µL. Immediate therapy:", "a": "IV immunoglobulin", "b": "Aspirin", "c": "Warfarin", "d": "Folic acid", "ans": "A", "e": "IV immunoglobulin is immediate therapy for ITP woman with severe menorrhagia and platelets 8,000/µL; rapid response within 24-48 hours.<br><br>Standard dose 1 g/kg daily for 1-2 days. Saturates splenic macrophage Fc receptors blocking platelet destruction. Combined with corticosteroids and platelet transfusion for major bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Aspirin (option B) worsens bleeding (contraindicated in ITP); warfarin (option C) worsens bleeding; folic acid (option D) is for folate deficiency, none being severe ITP bleeding emergency therapy like IVIG.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with chronic ITP fails steroids. Next long-term therapy:", "a": "Antibiotics", "b": "Desmopressin", "c": "Iron infusion", "d": "Splenectomy", "ans": "D", "e": "Splenectomy is next long-term therapy for steroid-failure chronic ITP; removes principal site of antibody-mediated platelet destruction.<br><br>Indications include steroid-refractory or steroid-dependent disease. Response rates 60-80 percent with lasting remission. Pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib vaccinations before splenectomy. Long-term penicillin prophylaxis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Antibiotics (option A) are for infection; desmopressin (option B) is for vWD or haemophilia; iron infusion (option C) is for iron deficiency, none being chronic ITP steroid-failure long-term therapy like splenectomy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient has mucosal bleeding, normal platelet count, prolonged bleeding time and prolonged aPTT. Diagnosis:", "a": "DIC", "b": "Liver disease", "c": "Von Willebrand disease", "d": "Hemophilia B", "ans": "C", "e": "Von Willebrand disease fits mucosal bleeding with normal platelets, prolonged bleeding time, and prolonged aPTT; vWF deficiency causes both impaired platelet adhesion and reduced factor VIII (vWF carrier).<br><br>Diagnosis by reduced vWF antigen, reduced vWF activity (ristocetin cofactor), reduced factor VIII, and prolonged bleeding time. Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease.<br><br>DIC (option A) features prolonged PT, low fibrinogen, elevated D-dimer; haemophilia B (option D) features deep tissue bleeds with prolonged aPTT only, none fitting this mixed platelet-coagulation pattern like vWD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A vWD patient undergoing dental extraction should receive:", "a": "Heparin", "b": "Desmopressin", "c": "Aspirin", "d": "Warfarin", "ans": "B", "e": "Desmopressin treats vWD patient before dental extraction; releases stored vWF from endothelial Weibel-Palade bodies.<br><br>Standard dose 0.3 mcg/kg IV or subcutaneously 30 minutes before procedure. Combined with tranexamic acid for additional haemostasis. Effective for type 1 vWD and mild type 2A. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Heparin (option A) worsens bleeding; aspirin (option C) worsens bleeding; warfarin (option D) worsens bleeding, none being vWD pre-procedure therapy like desmopressin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Severe vWD with major trauma requires:", "a": "Factor VIII concentrate", "b": "Iron therapy", "c": "Vitamin K", "d": "Platelet transfusion only", "ans": "A", "e": "Factor VIII concentrate (vWF-containing) treats severe vWD with major trauma; severe disease or non-responders to desmopressin require factor concentrates.<br><br>Plasma-derived or recombinant concentrates containing vWF preferred. Standard dose 30-60 IU/kg before procedure with maintenance dosing as needed. Combined with addressing underlying trauma. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Iron therapy (option B) is for iron deficiency; vitamin K (option C) is for warfarin reversal; platelet transfusion only (option D) does not address vWF deficiency, none being severe vWD major trauma therapy like factor VIII/vWF concentrate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A teenager presents with recurrent epistaxis since childhood and family history positive. Platelets normal, bleeding time prolonged. Diagnosis:", "a": "Leukemia", "b": "Hemophilia", "c": "ITP", "d": "vWD", "ans": "D", "e": "vWD fits teenager with recurrent childhood epistaxis, positive family history, normal platelets, and prolonged bleeding time; impaired platelet adhesion causes mucocutaneous bleeding.<br><br>Diagnosis by reduced vWF antigen, reduced vWF activity (ristocetin cofactor), reduced factor VIII, and prolonged bleeding time. Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Leukaemia (option A) features pancytopenia; haemophilia (option B) features deep tissue bleeds with prolonged aPTT only; ITP (option C) features low platelets, none fitting normal-platelet mucocutaneous family-history pattern like vWD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In ITP petechiae occur because:", "a": "Vasculitis", "b": "Platelet destruction", "c": "Coagulation factor deficiency", "d": "Fibrinogen deficiency", "ans": "B", "e": "Platelet destruction causes petechiae in ITP; reduced platelet count from autoimmune destruction impairs primary haemostasis.<br><br>Treatment includes observation for mild disease, corticosteroids for symptomatic disease, IVIG for life-threatening bleeding, and splenectomy or rituximab for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Vasculitis (option A) causes palpable purpura; coagulation factor deficiency (option C) causes deep tissue bleeds; fibrinogen deficiency (option D) causes mixed pattern, none being ITP petechiae mechanism like platelet destruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with ITP and intracranial bleed requires:", "a": "Aspirin", "b": "Observation", "c": "Warfarin", "d": "Platelets plus IVIG and steroids", "ans": "D", "e": "Platelets plus IVIG and steroids treat ITP with intracranial bleed; combination provides immediate platelets, blocks destruction, and reduces antibody production.<br><br>Standard platelet transfusion, IVIG 1 g/kg daily for 1-2 days, and high-dose corticosteroids. Consider emergency splenectomy for refractory severe bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Aspirin (option A) worsens bleeding; observation (option B) is inappropriate for intracranial bleed; warfarin (option C) worsens bleeding, none being ITP intracranial bleed therapy like combination platelets-IVIG-steroids.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Failure of platelets to aggregate with ristocetin suggests:", "a": "Polycythemia", "b": "Thrombocytosis", "c": "Von Willebrand disease", "d": "Hemophilia", "ans": "C", "e": "Von Willebrand disease causes failure of platelet aggregation with ristocetin; vWF deficiency or dysfunction impairs ristocetin-mediated vWF-GPIb interaction.<br><br>Combined with reduced vWF antigen (quantitative), reduced factor VIII, and prolonged bleeding time. Bernard-Soulier syndrome also shows failed ristocetin aggregation (GPIb deficiency). Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Polycythaemia (option A) has normal aggregation; thrombocytosis (option B) has normal aggregation; haemophilia (option D) has normal aggregation (coagulation defect not platelet), none failing ristocetin aggregation like vWD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A pregnant woman with vWD in labor is best managed by:", "a": "Desmopressin or factor replacement", "b": "Heparin", "c": "Aspirin", "d": "Warfarin", "ans": "A", "e": "Desmopressin or factor replacement manages vWD pregnant woman in labour; addresses bleeding risk during delivery.<br><br>Type 1 vWD often improves in pregnancy due to oestrogen-induced vWF rise. Desmopressin or factor concentrates for symptomatic or type 2/3 disease. Combined with active third-stage management. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Heparin (option B) worsens bleeding; aspirin (option C) worsens bleeding; warfarin (option D) worsens bleeding and teratogenic, none being vWD labour management like desmopressin or factor replacement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Large platelets on smear in thrombocytopenia suggest:", "a": "DIC", "b": "Leukemia", "c": "Marrow failure", "d": "Peripheral destruction (ITP)", "ans": "D", "e": "Peripheral destruction (ITP) is suggested by large platelets in thrombocytopenia; bone marrow responds by releasing larger immature platelets to compensate.<br><br>Combined with normal CBC otherwise, normal coagulation, and increased megakaryocytes on bone marrow (if performed). Treatment includes observation for mild disease, corticosteroids, IVIG, and splenectomy or rituximab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>DIC (option A) features schistocytes and coagulation abnormalities; leukaemia (option B) features blasts; marrow failure (option C) features small platelets without compensation, none being large-platelet thrombocytopenia like peripheral destruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child with ITP but no bleeding and platelets 40,000/µL should be:", "a": "Splenectomized immediately", "b": "Observed only", "c": "Transfused routinely", "d": "Given chemotherapy", "ans": "B", "e": "Observation only is appropriate for paediatric ITP without bleeding and platelets 40,000/µL; most cases self-resolve without treatment.<br><br>Treatment indications include significant bleeding (mucosal, GI, intracranial), platelets under 10,000/µL, or before procedures. Treatment options include corticosteroids, IVIG, and anti-D. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including paediatrician. Long-term follow-up is essential. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Splenectomised immediately (option A) is for refractory disease; transfused routinely (option C) provides only transient effect; chemotherapy (option D) is for malignancy, none being paediatric stable ITP management like observation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with vWD undergoing major surgery needs:", "a": "No therapy", "b": "Aspirin", "c": "vWF-containing factor concentrate", "d": "Platelet inhibitors", "ans": "C", "e": "vWF-containing factor concentrate is required for vWD patient undergoing major surgery; provides vWF and factor VIII for adequate haemostasis.<br><br>Plasma-derived or recombinant concentrates preferred. Standard dose 30-60 IU/kg before procedure with maintenance dosing as needed. Combined with tranexamic acid for additional haemostasis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>No therapy (option A) risks bleeding; aspirin (option B) worsens bleeding; platelet inhibitors (option D) worsen bleeding, none being vWD major surgery preparation like vWF-containing factor concentrate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Recurrent gum bleeding with normal platelet count and family history suggests defect in:", "a": "Platelet adhesion", "b": "Complement", "c": "Coagulation factor X", "d": "RBC membrane", "ans": "A", "e": "Platelet adhesion defect causes recurrent gum bleeding with normal platelets and family history; impaired vWF-mediated platelet adhesion produces mucocutaneous bleeding.<br><br>Common in vWD (most common inherited bleeding disorder) and Bernard-Soulier syndrome (GPIb deficiency). Diagnosis by bleeding time, ristocetin cofactor, and vWF antigen. Treatment includes desmopressin for vWD type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease.<br><br>Complement (option B) defects cause infection; coagulation factor X (option C) deficiency is rare and causes deep tissue bleeds; RBC membrane (option D) defects cause haemolysis, none being normal-platelet mucocutaneous bleeding mechanism like platelet adhesion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "ITP associated with SLE occurs due to:", "a": "Vitamin deficiency", "b": "Infection", "c": "Autoimmune platelet destruction", "d": "Bone marrow fibrosis", "ans": "C", "e": "Autoimmune platelet destruction causes SLE-associated ITP; lupus autoantibodies target platelets producing peripheral destruction in spleen.<br><br>Combined with other SLE features (cytopenias, ANA, anti-dsDNA, complement consumption). Treatment of underlying SLE with immunosuppression often improves platelet count. ITP-specific therapies (corticosteroids, IVIG, rituximab) also effective. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Vitamin deficiency (option A) is not principal SLE-ITP mechanism; infection (option B) is non-specific; bone marrow fibrosis (option D) is myelofibrosis, none being SLE-ITP mechanism like autoimmune platelet destruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with vWD type 1 mild bleeding best treated with:", "a": "Desmopressin", "b": "Warfarin", "c": "Platelet inhibitor", "d": "Heparin", "ans": "A", "e": "Desmopressin treats vWD type 1 mild bleeding; releases stored vWF from endothelial Weibel-Palade bodies.<br><br>Standard dose 0.3 mcg/kg IV or subcutaneously. Effective for type 1 vWD and mild type 2A. Side effects include hyponatraemia, facial flushing, and tachyphylaxis. Combined with tranexamic acid for mucosal bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Warfarin (option B) worsens bleeding; platelet inhibitor (option C) worsens bleeding; heparin (option D) worsens bleeding, none being vWD type 1 mild bleeding therapy like desmopressin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Persistent thrombocytopenia after splenectomy in ITP suggests:", "a": "Hemophilia", "b": "Ongoing antibody production", "c": "Infection", "d": "Iron deficiency", "ans": "B", "e": "Ongoing antibody production explains persistent thrombocytopenia after ITP splenectomy; accessory splenic tissue or extra-splenic destruction maintains platelet destruction.<br><br>Treatment options for post-splenectomy failure include rituximab (depletes B-cells), thrombopoietin receptor agonists (eltrombopag, romiplostim), and immunosuppression. Combined with searching for accessory spleen. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemophilia (option A) is unrelated; infection (option C) is uncommon cause; iron deficiency (option D) causes anaemia not thrombocytopenia, none being post-splenectomy ITP failure mechanism like ongoing antibody production.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In vWD prolonged aPTT corrects after mixing study because:", "a": "Heparin effect", "b": "DIC", "c": "Platelet destruction", "d": "Factor deficiency rather than inhibitor", "ans": "D", "e": "Factor deficiency rather than inhibitor explains aPTT correction with mixing study in vWD; factor VIII deficiency (from absent vWF carrier protein) corrects when normal plasma added.<br><br>Distinguishing from acquired factor inhibitors (do not correct on mixing). Combined with reduced vWF antigen, reduced vWF activity, and reduced factor VIII for diagnosis.<br><br>Heparin effect (option A) does not correct on mixing; DIC (option B) shows multiple abnormalities; platelet destruction (option C) is unrelated to aPTT, none being vWD aPTT correction mechanism like factor deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with severe epistaxis and platelet count 5,000/µL from ITP requires urgent:", "a": "Anticoagulation", "b": "Vitamin K", "c": "IVIG and steroids", "d": "Iron tablets", "ans": "C", "e": "IVIG and steroids are urgent therapy for severe ITP epistaxis with platelets 5,000/µL; combination provides rapid response.<br><br>Standard IVIG 1 g/kg daily for 1-2 days plus high-dose corticosteroids. Combined with platelet transfusion for active bleeding. Tranexamic acid for mucosal bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Anticoagulation (option A) worsens bleeding; vitamin K (option B) is for warfarin reversal; iron tablets (option D) are for iron deficiency, none being severe ITP bleeding emergency therapy like IVIG-steroids combination.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 24-year-old woman presents with recurrent nosebleeds, easy bruising since childhood, normal platelet count and family history positive; labs show prolonged bleeding time and mildly prolonged aPTT. Most likely disorder:", "a": "ITP", "b": "DIC", "c": "Hemophilia A", "d": "Von Willebrand disease", "ans": "D", "e": "Von Willebrand disease fits 24-year-old woman with recurrent childhood nosebleeds, easy bruising, family history, normal platelets, prolonged bleeding time, and mildly prolonged aPTT; impaired platelet adhesion plus reduced factor VIII (vWF carrier).<br><br>Diagnosis by reduced vWF antigen, reduced vWF activity (ristocetin cofactor), reduced factor VIII, and prolonged bleeding time. Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease.<br><br>ITP (option A) features low platelets; haemophilia A (option C) is X-linked male-predominant with deep tissue bleeds, none fitting normal-platelet mucocutaneous female-with-family-history like vWD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 5-year-old child develops petechiae two weeks after viral infection; platelet count 18,000/µL but other counts normal and no hepatosplenomegaly. Appropriate management:", "a": "Observation and reassurance", "b": "Long-term anticoagulation", "c": "Bone marrow transplant", "d": "Immediate chemotherapy", "ans": "A", "e": "Observation and reassurance manages paediatric ITP with petechiae after viral infection, platelets 18,000/µL, no hepatosplenomegaly, and otherwise normal counts; most cases self-resolve.<br><br>Treatment indications include significant bleeding (mucosal, GI, intracranial), platelets under 10,000/µL, or before procedures. Treatment options include corticosteroids, IVIG, and anti-D. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including paediatrician. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Long-term anticoagulation (option B) worsens bleeding; bone marrow transplant (option C) is for aplastic anaemia; immediate chemotherapy (option D) is for malignancy, none being paediatric stable ITP management like observation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with chronic ITP presents with severe intracranial hemorrhage and platelets 4,000/µL. Best emergency therapy combination:", "a": "Aspirin and heparin", "b": "Platelet transfusion plus IVIG", "c": "Vitamin K only", "d": "Desmopressin only", "ans": "B", "e": "Platelet transfusion plus IVIG is best emergency therapy for chronic ITP with intracranial haemorrhage and platelets 4,000/µL; combination provides immediate platelets and blocks destruction.<br><br>Standard platelet transfusion with IVIG 1 g/kg daily for 1-2 days plus high-dose corticosteroids. Consider emergency splenectomy for refractory severe bleeding. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Aspirin and heparin (option A) worsen bleeding; vitamin K only (option C) is for warfarin reversal; desmopressin only (option D) is for vWD not ITP, none being chronic ITP intracranial bleed emergency therapy like platelets-IVIG.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "During surgery a patient has persistent oozing, normal platelet count, prolonged bleeding time and abnormal ristocetin test. Immediate management:", "a": "Heparin", "b": "Warfarin", "c": "Desmopressin", "d": "Aspirin", "ans": "C", "e": "Desmopressin manages persistent surgical oozing with normal platelets, prolonged bleeding time, and abnormal ristocetin (vWD); releases stored vWF from endothelial Weibel-Palade bodies.<br><br>Standard dose 0.3 mcg/kg IV or subcutaneously. Effective for type 1 vWD and mild type 2A. Combined with tranexamic acid for additional haemostasis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Heparin (option A) worsens bleeding; warfarin (option B) worsens bleeding; aspirin (option D) worsens bleeding, none being intra-operative vWD-pattern management like desmopressin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A teenager with known vWD suffers major trauma with severe bleeding; desmopressin ineffective. Next treatment:", "a": "Observation", "b": "Iron infusion", "c": "Platelet inhibitors", "d": "Factor VIII/vWF concentrate", "ans": "D", "e": "Factor VIII/vWF concentrate treats vWD teenager with major trauma when desmopressin ineffective; severe disease or desmopressin non-responders require factor concentrates.<br><br>Plasma-derived or recombinant concentrates containing vWF preferred. Standard dose 30-60 IU/kg with maintenance dosing as needed. Combined with addressing underlying trauma. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Observation (option A) is inappropriate for severe bleeding; iron infusion (option B) is for iron deficiency; platelet inhibitors (option C) worsen bleeding, none being desmopressin-failure vWD severe bleeding therapy like factor VIII/vWF concentrate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with ITP fails steroids and IVIG and continues bleeding. Definitive therapy:", "a": "Splenectomy", "b": "Vitamin C", "c": "Plasma exchange", "d": "Anticoagulants", "ans": "A", "e": "Splenectomy is definitive therapy for ITP refractory to steroids and IVIG with continued bleeding; removes principal site of antibody-mediated platelet destruction.<br><br>Indications include steroid-refractory or steroid-dependent disease. Response rates 60-80 percent with lasting remission. Pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib vaccinations before splenectomy. Long-term penicillin prophylaxis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Vitamin C (option B) is for scurvy; plasma exchange (option C) is for TTP; anticoagulants (option D) worsen bleeding, none being refractory ITP definitive therapy like splenectomy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A woman with heavy menstrual bleeding has normal PT, normal platelets but prolonged aPTT and abnormal ristocetin aggregation. Mechanism of bleeding:", "a": "Excess thrombin", "b": "Defective platelet adhesion", "c": "Platelet destruction", "d": "Fibrin deficiency", "ans": "B", "e": "Defective platelet adhesion is the bleeding mechanism for woman with menorrhagia, normal PT, normal platelets, prolonged aPTT, and abnormal ristocetin (vWD); impaired vWF function prevents platelet binding to subendothelium.<br><br>Diagnosis by reduced vWF antigen, reduced vWF activity (ristocetin cofactor), reduced factor VIII, and prolonged bleeding time. Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease.<br><br>Excess thrombin (option A) causes thrombosis; platelet destruction (option C) is ITP with low platelets; fibrin deficiency (option D) is afibrinogenaemia, none being vWD bleeding mechanism like defective platelet adhesion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child with vWD undergoes tooth extraction and develops delayed bleeding 12 hours later due to reduced:", "a": "Factor VIII stabilization", "b": "Platelet count", "c": "Fibrinolysis inhibition", "d": "RBC production", "ans": "A", "e": "Reduced factor VIII stabilisation causes delayed bleeding 12 hours after vWD tooth extraction; vWF normally protects factor VIII from degradation.<br><br>Delayed bleeding (versus immediate platelet-type bleeding) reflects factor VIII-mediated secondary haemostasis defect. Treatment includes desmopressin for type 1 and factor concentrates for severe disease. Combined with tranexamic acid for mucosal bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Platelet count (option B) is normal in vWD; fibrinolysis inhibition (option C) is unrelated; RBC production (option D) is unrelated, none being vWD delayed bleeding mechanism like factor VIII stabilisation reduction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient presents with purpura, platelets 12,000/µL, normal coagulation tests and increased megakaryocytes in marrow. Pathogenesis involves:", "a": "Vitamin K deficiency", "b": "Autoimmune peripheral destruction", "c": "Liver failure", "d": "DIC", "ans": "B", "e": "Autoimmune peripheral destruction is the ITP pathogenesis: purpura, platelets 12,000/µL, normal coagulation, and increased megakaryocytes confirm peripheral destruction with compensatory marrow response.<br><br>Most common antibodies against GPIIb/IIIa or GPIb/IX. Treatment includes observation for mild disease, corticosteroids for symptomatic disease, IVIG for life-threatening bleeding, and splenectomy or rituximab for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Vitamin K deficiency (option A) prolongs PT; liver failure (option C) prolongs PT; DIC (option D) features prolonged PT-aPTT and elevated D-dimer, none being ITP-specific peripheral immune destruction mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A surgical patient with vWD receives FFP because it provides:", "a": "Antibodies against platelets", "b": "Platelet destruction inhibition", "c": "Iron replacement", "d": "Clotting factors including vWF when concentrates unavailable", "ans": "D", "e": "Clotting factors including vWF when concentrates unavailable is the rationale for FFP in surgical vWD; provides all coagulation factors including vWF and factor VIII.<br><br>Volume overload limitation. Specific factor concentrates preferred when available. Combined with desmopressin for type 1 and addressing underlying surgical bleeding. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Antibodies against platelets (option A) worsen bleeding; platelet destruction inhibition (option B) is not FFP function; iron replacement (option C) is not in FFP, none being FFP function in vWD like vWF and coagulation factor provision.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 5-year-old boy presents with recurrent hemarthrosis and prolonged aPTT with normal PT and platelet count. The most likely diagnosis is:", "a": "Hemophilia A", "b": "Von Willebrand disease", "c": "Disseminated intravascular coagulation", "d": "Immune thrombocytopenia", "ans": "A", "e": "Haemophilia A fits 5-year-old boy with recurrent haemarthrosis, prolonged aPTT, normal PT, and normal platelets; X-linked factor VIII deficiency produces deep tissue bleeds.<br><br>Diagnosis by reduced factor VIII activity (severe under 1 percent, moderate 1-5 percent, mild 5-40 percent). Treatment with factor VIII concentrate replacement (recombinant or plasma-derived).<br><br>Von Willebrand disease (option B) features mucocutaneous bleeding with prolonged bleeding time; DIC (option C) features prolonged PT and aPTT with elevated D-dimer; ITP (option D) features low platelets, none fitting male child haemarthrosis with isolated aPTT prolongation like haemophilia A.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hemophilia B results from deficiency of:", "a": "Factor VIII", "b": "Factor VII", "c": "Factor IX", "d": "Factor X", "ans": "C", "e": "Factor IX deficiency causes haemophilia B; this X-linked recessive disorder produces identical clinical phenotype to haemophilia A but with different factor deficiency.<br><br>Diagnosis by reduced factor IX activity (severe under 1 percent, moderate 1-5 percent, mild 5-40 percent). Treatment with factor IX concentrate replacement (recombinant or plasma-derived). Prophylaxis for severe disease.<br><br>Factor VIII (option A) is haemophilia A; factor VII (option B) deficiency has prolonged PT; factor X (option D) deficiency is rare and prolongs both PT and aPTT, none being haemophilia B factor like factor IX.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Inheritance pattern of hemophilia is:", "a": "Mitochondrial", "b": "Autosomal dominant", "c": "X-linked recessive", "d": "Autosomal recessive", "ans": "C", "e": "X-linked recessive inheritance characterises haemophilia A and B; both factor VIII and factor IX genes located on X chromosome with affected males and carrier females.<br><br>Family history typically maternal uncles or grandfathers affected. Female carriers may show mild reduction in factor levels with occasional bleeding. Genetic counselling for affected families. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Mitochondrial (option A) is maternal inheritance pattern (not haemophilia); autosomal dominant (option B) is hereditary spherocytosis; autosomal recessive (option D) is sickle cell, none being haemophilia inheritance like X-linked recessive.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most characteristic bleeding manifestation in hemophilia:", "a": "Epistaxis only", "b": "Purpura", "c": "Hemarthrosis", "d": "Petechiae", "ans": "C", "e": "Haemarthrosis is the most characteristic bleeding manifestation in haemophilia; factor VIII or IX deficiency impairs secondary haemostasis producing deep tissue bleeds particularly joints.<br><br>Common sites include knees, ankles, and elbows. Repeated haemarthrosis causes haemophilic arthropathy with chronic synovitis, cartilage destruction, and joint deformity. Treatment with factor replacement, RICE (rest, ice, compression, elevation), and physiotherapy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Epistaxis only (option A) is mucocutaneous pattern; purpura (option B) is platelet disorder; petechiae (option D) is platelet disorder, none being haemophilia characteristic bleeding like haemarthrosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Screening test most prolonged in hemophilia:", "a": "PT", "b": "Thrombin time", "c": "Bleeding time", "d": "aPTT", "ans": "D", "e": "aPTT is the most prolonged screening test in haemophilia; factor VIII and IX are intrinsic pathway components measured by aPTT.<br><br>Combined with normal PT (extrinsic pathway intact), normal platelet count, and normal bleeding time. Diagnosis confirmed by factor VIII or IX assay (severe under 1 percent, moderate 1-5 percent, mild 5-40 percent). Treatment with factor replacement.<br><br>PT (option A) is normal in haemophilia; thrombin time (option B) is normal; bleeding time (option C) is normal (platelet function intact), none being haemophilia prolonged screening test like aPTT.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Factor VIII replacement is indicated in:", "a": "DIC", "b": "Hemophilia A bleeding episode", "c": "Vitamin K deficiency", "d": "Platelet disorder", "ans": "B", "e": "Haemophilia A bleeding episode is the indication for factor VIII replacement; restoring factor VIII activity provides haemostasis.<br><br>Standard dose 25-50 IU/kg for minor bleeding, 50 IU/kg for major bleeding, with maintenance dosing as needed. Prophylactic replacement for severe disease (2-3 times weekly). Recombinant or plasma-derived concentrates. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>DIC (option A) requires FFP and addressing underlying cause; vitamin K deficiency (option C) requires vitamin K; platelet disorder (option D) requires platelets, none being factor VIII indication like haemophilia A bleeding.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Desmopressin is useful in mild hemophilia A because it:", "a": "Inhibits fibrinolysis", "b": "Releases factor VIII from endothelium", "c": "Increases vitamin K", "d": "Activates platelets", "ans": "B", "e": "Releasing factor VIII from endothelium is desmopressin mechanism in mild haemophilia A; this synthetic ADH analogue stimulates endothelial release of factor VIII and vWF.<br><br>Standard dose 0.3 mcg/kg IV or subcutaneously. Effective for mild haemophilia A (factor VIII 5-40 percent). Side effects include hyponatraemia, facial flushing, and tachyphylaxis.<br><br>Inhibits fibrinolysis (option A) is tranexamic acid; increases vitamin K (option C) is not desmopressin mechanism; activates platelets (option D) is not desmopressin function, none being mild haemophilia A mechanism like factor VIII release from endothelium.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hemophilia A and B are best differentiated by:", "a": "Bleeding time", "b": "PT test", "c": "Platelet count", "d": "Factor assay levels", "ans": "D", "e": "Factor assay levels best differentiate haemophilia A from B; specific factor VIII assay (low in A) and factor IX assay (low in B) distinguish identical clinical phenotypes.<br><br>Both diseases share X-linked inheritance, deep tissue bleeds, prolonged aPTT, and identical clinical phenotypes. Treatment differs (factor VIII concentrate for A, factor IX concentrate for B). Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Bleeding time (option A) is normal in both; PT (option B) is normal in both; platelet count (option C) is normal in both, none differentiating haemophilia A from B like factor assay.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with hemophilia develops joint deformity due to repeated:", "a": "Hemarthrosis", "b": "Petechiae", "c": "Thrombosis", "d": "Muscle hematomas", "ans": "A", "e": "Joint deformity in haemophilia results from repeated haemarthrosis; recurrent joint bleeding produces haemophilic arthropathy with chronic synovitis, cartilage destruction, and bone changes.<br><br>Common sites include knees, ankles, and elbows. Treatment with factor replacement during acute haemarthrosis, RICE, physiotherapy, and joint replacement for severe arthropathy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including orthopaedic surgeon. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Petechiae (option B) are platelet disorder skin findings; thrombosis (option C) is opposite of bleeding; muscle haematomas (option D) cause muscle damage not joint deformity, none being haemophilic joint deformity mechanism like recurrent haemarthrosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Inhibitors against factor VIII cause treatment failure in hemophilia A; management includes:", "a": "Vitamin K", "b": "Bypassing agents", "c": "Iron therapy", "d": "Platelets", "ans": "B", "e": "Bypassing agents manage haemophilia A with factor VIII inhibitors; activated prothrombin complex concentrate (FEIBA) or recombinant factor VIIa bypass the inhibitor-affected step.<br><br>Indications include inhibitor titre over 5 BU. Alternative includes immune tolerance induction with high-dose factor VIII to eliminate inhibitor. Emicizumab (bispecific antibody mimicking factor VIII function) for prophylaxis. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Vitamin K (option A) is for vitamin K deficiency; iron therapy (option C) is for iron deficiency; platelets (option D) are for thrombocytopenia, none being inhibitor management like bypassing agents.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Severe hemophilia is defined when factor activity is:", "a": "5–10%", "b": "20–40%", "c": ">50%", "d": "<1%", "ans": "D", "e": "Severe haemophilia is defined when factor activity is under 1 percent; this classification predicts clinical severity.<br><br>Severe: under 1 percent (spontaneous bleeding). Moderate: 1-5 percent (bleeding after minor trauma). Mild: 5-40 percent (bleeding after major trauma or surgery). Treatment with factor replacement adjusted to severity and clinical scenario. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>5-10 percent (option A) is moderate; 20-40 percent (option B) is mild; over 50 percent (option C) is normal range, none being severe haemophilia definition like under 1 percent.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Intracranial hemorrhage risk is highest in:", "a": "Carrier females", "b": "Mild hemophilia", "c": "Severe hemophilia", "d": "Moderate hemophilia", "ans": "C", "e": "Severe haemophilia carries highest intracranial haemorrhage risk; factor activity under 1 percent permits spontaneous bleeding including intracranial.<br><br>Standard prophylactic factor replacement (2-3 times weekly) reduces bleeding risk. Treatment of acute intracranial bleed with immediate factor replacement to 100 percent activity. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Carrier females (option A) usually have mild factor reduction; mild haemophilia (option B) has lower ICH risk; moderate haemophilia (option D) has lower ICH risk than severe, none having highest ICH risk like severe haemophilia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hemophilia carriers are typically:", "a": "Homozygous females", "b": "Autosomal carriers", "c": "Heterozygous females", "d": "Affected males", "ans": "C", "e": "Heterozygous females are typical haemophilia carriers; one normal and one mutant X chromosome produces variable factor levels.<br><br>Variable expression depends on lyonisation (X-inactivation pattern). May show mild reduction in factor levels with occasional bleeding particularly after trauma or surgery. Genetic counselling for affected families. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Homozygous females (option A) are clinically affected like males (rare); autosomal carriers (option B) is incorrect (X-linked); affected males (option D) are patients not carriers, none being typical haemophilia carrier like heterozygous females.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common site of bleeding in hemophilia:", "a": "Mucosa", "b": "Joints", "c": "Skin", "d": "Retina", "ans": "B", "e": "Joints are the most common bleeding site in haemophilia; weight-bearing joints particularly susceptible to spontaneous and trauma-induced bleeding.<br><br>Common sites include knees, ankles, and elbows. Repeated haemarthrosis causes haemophilic arthropathy with chronic synovitis, cartilage destruction, and joint deformity. Treatment with factor replacement, RICE, and physiotherapy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Mucosa (option A) is platelet disorder bleeding pattern; skin (option C) is mucocutaneous pattern; retina (option D) is uncommon site, none being most common haemophilia bleeding site like joints.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Factor IX deficiency is also called:", "a": "Hageman disease", "b": "Stuart disease", "c": "Rosenthal syndrome", "d": "Christmas disease", "ans": "D", "e": "Christmas disease is the historical name for factor IX deficiency (haemophilia B); named after Stephen Christmas, the first patient described with the condition.<br><br>X-linked recessive disorder producing identical clinical phenotype to haemophilia A but with different factor deficiency. Diagnosis by reduced factor IX activity. Treatment with factor IX concentrate replacement. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Hageman disease (option A) is factor XII deficiency (typically asymptomatic); Stuart disease (option B) is factor X deficiency; Rosenthal syndrome (option C) is factor XI deficiency, none being factor IX deficiency name like Christmas disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Vitamin K deficiency primarily prolongs:", "a": "aPTT only", "b": "Thrombin time", "c": "Bleeding time", "d": "PT first", "ans": "D", "e": "PT first prolongs in vitamin K deficiency; factor VII has shortest half-life (4-6 hours) of vitamin K-dependent factors and depletes first.<br><br>Subsequently aPTT prolongs as factors II, IX, and X deplete. Diagnosis by prolonged PT corrected by vitamin K. Treatment with vitamin K administration (oral, IV, or subcutaneous) and FFP for severe bleeding.<br><br>aPTT only (option A) is not first affected; thrombin time (option B) is for fibrinogen abnormalities; bleeding time (option C) is for platelet function, none being first prolonged in vitamin K deficiency like PT.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Vitamin K dependent clotting factors include:", "a": "II, VII, IX, X", "b": "I, II, III", "c": "XII, XIII", "d": "V, VIII, XI", "ans": "A", "e": "Factors II, VII, IX, and X are vitamin K-dependent; gamma-carboxylation of glutamate residues requires vitamin K as cofactor.<br><br>Also protein C and protein S (anticoagulant proteins). Warfarin blocks vitamin K epoxide reductase reducing functional levels of these factors. Vitamin K deficiency causes bleeding from reduced functional factor levels.<br><br>I, II, III (option B) includes fibrinogen (I) and tissue factor (III), not vitamin K-dependent; XII, XIII (option C) are not vitamin K-dependent; V, VIII, XI (option D) are not vitamin K-dependent, none being vitamin K-dependent group like II/VII/IX/X.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Newborn hemorrhagic disease occurs due to deficiency of:", "a": "Vitamin C", "b": "Vitamin K", "c": "Folate", "d": "Iron", "ans": "B", "e": "Vitamin K deficiency causes newborn haemorrhagic disease; reduced placental transfer, lack of intestinal flora, and low vitamin K in breast milk produce deficiency.<br><br>Prevention with vitamin K 1 mg IM at birth. Three forms: early (within 24 hours, from maternal warfarin/antiepileptics), classical (2-7 days, breast-fed infants), and late (2-12 weeks, breast-fed infants with malabsorption). Treatment with vitamin K.<br><br>Vitamin C (option A) is for scurvy; folate (option C) is for megaloblastic anaemia; iron (option D) is for iron deficiency, none being newborn haemorrhagic disease cause like vitamin K deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common cause of vitamin K deficiency in adults:", "a": "Malnutrition only", "b": "Fat malabsorption", "c": "Renal failure", "d": "Hemolysis", "ans": "B", "e": "Fat malabsorption is the most common cause of vitamin K deficiency in adults; vitamin K is fat-soluble requiring bile salts and pancreatic enzymes for absorption.<br><br>Causes include coeliac disease, Crohn disease, cystic fibrosis, biliary obstruction, and chronic pancreatitis. Diagnosis by prolonged PT corrected by parenteral vitamin K.<br><br>Malnutrition only (option A) is contributory but uncommon principal cause; renal failure (option C) does not cause vitamin K deficiency; haemolysis (option D) is unrelated, none being principal adult vitamin K deficiency cause like fat malabsorption.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Warfarin causes bleeding because it inhibits synthesis of:", "a": "Fibrinogen", "b": "Factor V", "c": "Vitamin K dependent factors", "d": "Platelets", "ans": "C", "e": "Warfarin inhibits synthesis of vitamin K-dependent factors causing bleeding; this oral anticoagulant blocks vitamin K epoxide reductase reducing functional factors II, VII, IX, X, protein C, and protein S.<br><br>Monitoring by INR (international normalised ratio). Reversal with vitamin K (oral or IV) for elevated INR without bleeding, plus FFP or prothrombin complex concentrate for active bleeding.<br><br>Fibrinogen (option A) is not vitamin K-dependent; factor V (option B) is not vitamin K-dependent; platelets (option D) are not affected by warfarin, none being warfarin target like vitamin K-dependent factors.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Treatment of vitamin K deficiency bleeding:", "a": "Desmopressin", "b": "Vitamin K administration", "c": "Platelet transfusion", "d": "Heparin", "ans": "B", "e": "Vitamin K administration treats vitamin K deficiency bleeding; replaces missing cofactor for gamma-carboxylation of factors II, VII, IX, and X.<br><br>Standard dose 10 mg IV for adults with bleeding, oral for prevention. Subcutaneous injection produces erratic absorption. FFP for severe bleeding while awaiting vitamin K effect (6-24 hours). Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Desmopressin (option A) is for vWD and mild haemophilia A; platelet transfusion (option C) is for thrombocytopenia; heparin (option D) worsens bleeding, none being vitamin K deficiency treatment like vitamin K administration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In obstructive jaundice bleeding occurs due to:", "a": "Increased fibrinolysis", "b": "Hemolysis", "c": "Platelet destruction", "d": "Reduced vitamin K absorption", "ans": "D", "e": "Reduced vitamin K absorption causes obstructive jaundice bleeding; absent bile salts prevent intestinal absorption of fat-soluble vitamin K.<br><br>Mechanism includes reduced gamma-carboxylation of factors II, VII, IX, and X producing bleeding. Treatment with parenteral vitamin K and addressing underlying biliary obstruction. Combined with FFP for severe bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Increased fibrinolysis (option A) is not principal mechanism; haemolysis (option B) is unrelated; platelet destruction (option C) is unrelated, none being obstructive jaundice bleeding mechanism like reduced vitamin K absorption.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hemophilia typically shows:", "a": "Low fibrinogen", "b": "Normal platelet count", "c": "Prolonged bleeding time", "d": "Prolonged PT", "ans": "B", "e": "Normal platelet count characterises haemophilia; this distinguishes coagulation factor deficiency from platelet disorders.<br><br>Combined with prolonged aPTT, normal PT, normal bleeding time, and reduced factor VIII or IX activity. Diagnosis confirmed by specific factor assays. Treatment with factor replacement. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Low fibrinogen (option A) is DIC or afibrinogenaemia; prolonged bleeding time (option C) is platelet or vWD disorder; prolonged PT (option D) is liver disease, vitamin K deficiency, or warfarin, none being haemophilia feature like normal platelets.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Mixing study correction of aPTT indicates:", "a": "Factor deficiency", "b": "DIC", "c": "Platelet disorder", "d": "Inhibitor presence", "ans": "A", "e": "Factor deficiency is indicated by mixing study correction of aPTT; adding normal plasma corrects the deficiency restoring normal aPTT.<br><br>Distinguishing from acquired factor inhibitors (do not correct on mixing). Combined with specific factor assays for diagnosis. Treatment with factor replacement for confirmed deficiency. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>DIC (option B) features multiple abnormalities and elevated D-dimer; platelet disorder (option C) does not affect aPTT; inhibitor presence (option D) does not correct on mixing, none being aPTT-correction interpretation like factor deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Prophylactic therapy in severe hemophilia involves:", "a": "Platelet transfusion", "b": "Daily vitamin K", "c": "Antibiotics", "d": "Regular factor replacement", "ans": "D", "e": "Regular factor replacement is prophylactic therapy for severe haemophilia; 2-3 times weekly factor VIII or IX infusions prevent spontaneous bleeding.<br><br>Maintains trough factor levels above 1 percent reducing spontaneous bleeding. Combined with on-demand treatment for breakthrough bleeding. Long-acting factor concentrates and emicizumab improving prophylaxis convenience. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Platelet transfusion (option A) is for thrombocytopenia; daily vitamin K (option B) is for vitamin K deficiency; antibiotics (option C) are for infection prophylaxis, none being severe haemophilia prophylaxis like regular factor replacement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hemophilia A prevalence compared to B is:", "a": "More common", "b": "Equal", "c": "Less common", "d": "Rare", "ans": "A", "e": "Haemophilia A is more common than haemophilia B; factor VIII deficiency accounts for 80-85 percent of haemophilia cases.<br><br>Haemophilia A affects 1 in 5000 males. Haemophilia B affects 1 in 30,000 males. Both X-linked recessive with identical clinical phenotypes. Treatment differs (factor VIII versus factor IX concentrate). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Equal (option B) is incorrect; less common (option C) is incorrect; rare (option D) is incorrect (haemophilia A is the most common haemophilia), none being haemophilia A prevalence like more common.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Spontaneous bleeding without trauma occurs in:", "a": "Moderate hemophilia", "b": "Carriers", "c": "Mild hemophilia", "d": "Severe hemophilia", "ans": "D", "e": "Severe haemophilia causes spontaneous bleeding without trauma; factor activity under 1 percent permits unprovoked bleeding into joints, muscles, and other tissues.<br><br>Standard prophylactic factor replacement (2-3 times weekly) reduces spontaneous bleeding. Treatment of acute bleeds with immediate factor replacement. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Moderate haemophilia (option A) features bleeding after minor trauma; carriers (option B) usually have mild reduction with rare bleeding; mild haemophilia (option C) features bleeding after major trauma or surgery, none featuring spontaneous bleeding like severe haemophilia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Fresh frozen plasma in hemophilia provides:", "a": "Vitamin K", "b": "Platelets", "c": "RBCs", "d": "Clotting factors", "ans": "D", "e": "Clotting factors are provided by fresh frozen plasma in haemophilia; FFP contains all coagulation factors including factor VIII and IX.<br><br>Used when specific factor concentrates unavailable. Volume overload limitation with risk of TRALI and transfusion reactions. Specific factor concentrates (recombinant or plasma-derived) preferred when available. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Vitamin K (option A) is in supplements not FFP; platelets (option B) are in platelet transfusion; RBCs (option C) are in red cell transfusion, none being FFP components like clotting factors.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Vitamin K acts in coagulation by:", "a": "Gamma carboxylation of clotting factors", "b": "Activating fibrinolysis", "c": "Platelet aggregation", "d": "Thrombin inhibition", "ans": "A", "e": "Gamma-carboxylation of clotting factors is vitamin K mechanism in coagulation; vitamin K serves as cofactor for gamma-glutamyl carboxylase adding carboxyl groups to glutamate residues on factors II, VII, IX, and X.<br><br>Carboxylated residues bind calcium enabling phospholipid binding and active enzyme function. Deficiency or warfarin inhibition reduces functional factor levels. Treatment with vitamin K administration. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Activating fibrinolysis (option B) is plasmin activator function; platelet aggregation (option C) is platelet function; thrombin inhibition (option D) is antithrombin function, none being vitamin K mechanism like gamma-carboxylation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Antibiotic therapy predisposes to vitamin K deficiency by:", "a": "Increasing platelets", "b": "Increasing factor VIII", "c": "Increasing bile", "d": "Destroying gut flora", "ans": "D", "e": "Destroying gut flora produces vitamin K deficiency from prolonged antibiotic therapy; intestinal bacteria synthesise vitamin K2 which contributes to body stores.<br><br>Particularly with broad-spectrum antibiotics. Combined with reduced dietary intake during illness produces clinically significant deficiency. Diagnosis by prolonged PT corrected by parenteral vitamin K. Treatment with parenteral vitamin K.<br><br>Increasing platelets (option A) is incorrect; increasing factor VIII (option B) is not antibiotic effect; increasing bile (option C) would enhance vitamin K absorption, none being antibiotic vitamin K deficiency mechanism like gut flora destruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child with prolonged bleeding after circumcision and prolonged aPTT but normal PT most likely has:", "a": "DIC", "b": "Vitamin K deficiency", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "Liver disease", "ans": "C", "e": "Haemophilia is the most likely diagnosis for child with prolonged post-circumcision bleeding and isolated aPTT prolongation; X-linked factor VIII or IX deficiency produces this pattern.<br><br>Diagnosis by reduced factor VIII or IX activity. Treatment with factor concentrate replacement. Prophylaxis for severe disease. Combined with genetic counselling for family.<br><br>DIC (option A) features prolonged PT and aPTT with elevated D-dimer; vitamin K deficiency (option B) prolongs PT first; liver disease (option D) prolongs both PT and aPTT, none fitting isolated aPTT prolongation with male child bleeding like haemophilia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A newborn develops intracranial bleeding on day 3 of life due to vitamin deficiency; immediate therapy:", "a": "Heparin", "b": "Platelets", "c": "Vitamin K injection", "d": "Iron", "ans": "C", "e": "Vitamin K injection is immediate therapy for newborn intracranial bleed from vitamin deficiency on day 3; this is classical haemorrhagic disease of newborn.<br><br>Standard dose 1 mg IM. Combined with FFP for severe bleeding (provides immediate factor replacement while awaiting vitamin K effect). Prevention by routine vitamin K 1 mg IM at birth.<br><br>Heparin (option A) worsens bleeding; platelets (option B) do not address factor deficiency; iron (option D) is for iron deficiency, none being neonatal vitamin K deficiency bleeding therapy like vitamin K injection.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A hemophilia patient with joint swelling and pain should receive:", "a": "Aspirin", "b": "NSAIDs", "c": "Warfarin", "d": "Factor replacement", "ans": "D", "e": "Factor replacement treats haemophilia patient with joint swelling and pain; haemarthrosis requires immediate factor VIII or IX replacement.<br><br>Standard dose 40-50 IU/kg factor VIII for haemophilia A or 80-100 IU/kg factor IX for haemophilia B. Combined with RICE (rest, ice, compression, elevation) and physiotherapy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including orthopaedic surgeon. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Aspirin (option A) worsens bleeding; NSAIDs (option B) worsen bleeding (avoid in haemophilia); warfarin (option C) worsens bleeding, none being haemophilic haemarthrosis therapy like factor replacement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Persistent prolonged PT corrected by vitamin K indicates:", "a": "Liver failure", "b": "Vitamin K deficiency", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "DIC", "ans": "B", "e": "Vitamin K deficiency is indicated by persistent prolonged PT corrected by vitamin K; replacement of missing cofactor restores gamma-carboxylation.<br><br>Causes include malabsorption (coeliac, Crohn, biliary obstruction), prolonged antibiotic therapy, malnutrition, and warfarin therapy. Treatment with vitamin K administration. Combined with FFP for severe bleeding. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Liver failure (option A) does not correct fully with vitamin K (synthesis defect); haemophilia (option C) is unaffected by vitamin K; DIC (option D) does not correct with vitamin K, none correcting with vitamin K like vitamin K deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "An infant fed only breast milk develops bleeding; cause:", "a": "DIC", "b": "Platelet disorder", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "Vitamin K deficiency", "ans": "D", "e": "Vitamin K deficiency causes bleeding in breast-fed infants; low vitamin K content in breast milk plus lack of intestinal flora producing vitamin K causes deficiency.<br><br>Three forms: early (within 24 hours, from maternal warfarin/antiepileptics), classical (2-7 days, breast-fed infants), and late (2-12 weeks, breast-fed infants with malabsorption). Prevention with vitamin K 1 mg IM at birth.<br><br>DIC (option A) features prolonged PT-aPTT with elevated D-dimer; haemophilia (option C) features factor VIII or IX deficiency, none being breast-fed infant bleeding cause like vitamin K deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient on warfarin overdose presents with bleeding; treatment:", "a": "Platelets", "b": "Desmopressin", "c": "Vitamin K", "d": "Heparin", "ans": "C", "e": "Vitamin K treats warfarin overdose bleeding; replaces inhibited cofactor allowing restoration of functional factors II, VII, IX, and X.<br><br>Standard dose 5-10 mg IV slowly for severe bleeding, oral for mild elevations of INR without bleeding. Combined with FFP or prothrombin complex concentrate for immediate factor replacement in severe bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Platelets (option A) are for thrombocytopenia; desmopressin (option B) is for vWD; heparin (option D) worsens bleeding (also anticoagulant), none being warfarin overdose reversal like vitamin K.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Severe hemophilia patient requires dental extraction; best prophylaxis:", "a": "Vitamin C", "b": "Antibiotics only", "c": "Iron therapy", "d": "Factor infusion", "ans": "D", "e": "Factor infusion is best prophylaxis for severe haemophilia patient before dental extraction; raises factor activity to allow safe procedure.<br><br>Standard dose factor VIII 40-50 IU/kg for haemophilia A or factor IX 80-100 IU/kg for haemophilia B before procedure. Combined with tranexamic acid for adjunctive haemostasis. Local measures including pressure and gelfoam. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Vitamin C (option A) is for scurvy; antibiotics only (option B) prevent infection not bleeding; iron therapy (option C) is for iron deficiency, none being haemophilia dental procedure prophylaxis like factor infusion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with prolonged PT and normal aPTT likely has deficiency of:", "a": "Factor IX", "b": "Factor VIII", "c": "Factor VII", "d": "Factor XI", "ans": "C", "e": "Factor VII deficiency causes prolonged PT with normal aPTT; this extrinsic pathway factor has shortest half-life (4-6 hours).<br><br>Inherited as autosomal recessive or acquired (vitamin K deficiency, warfarin, liver disease). Treatment with recombinant factor VIIa concentrate for inherited disease, addressing underlying cause for acquired. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Factor IX (option A) deficiency prolongs aPTT (haemophilia B); factor VIII (option B) deficiency prolongs aPTT (haemophilia A); factor XI (option D) deficiency prolongs aPTT (haemophilia C), none being isolated PT prolongation like factor VII deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Bleeding in fat malabsorption improves with:", "a": "Vitamin K supplementation", "b": "Platelets", "c": "Heparin", "d": "Iron therapy", "ans": "A", "e": "Vitamin K supplementation improves bleeding in fat malabsorption; absent bile salts impair fat-soluble vitamin K absorption.<br><br>Treatment with parenteral vitamin K (10 mg IV slowly) and addressing underlying malabsorption (coeliac disease, Crohn disease, biliary obstruction, chronic pancreatitis). Combined with FFP for severe bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Platelets (option B) are for thrombocytopenia; heparin (option C) worsens bleeding; iron therapy (option D) is for iron deficiency, none being fat malabsorption bleeding therapy like vitamin K supplementation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hemarthrosis in hemophilia leads to:", "a": "Skin petechiae", "b": "Thrombosis", "c": "Joint destruction", "d": "Muscle necrosis", "ans": "C", "e": "Joint destruction follows haemarthrosis in haemophilia; repeated joint bleeding produces chronic synovitis, cartilage damage, and haemophilic arthropathy.<br><br>Common sites include knees, ankles, and elbows. Treatment with factor replacement during acute bleeds, prophylactic replacement to prevent bleeding, RICE, physiotherapy, and joint replacement for severe arthropathy. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Skin petechiae (option A) are platelet disorder finding; thrombosis (option B) is opposite of bleeding; muscle necrosis (option D) is from muscle haematoma not haemarthrosis, none being haemarthrosis consequence like joint destruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A mixing study fails to correct prolonged aPTT suggesting:", "a": "Vitamin K deficiency", "b": "Platelet disorder", "c": "Factor deficiency", "d": "Inhibitor presence", "ans": "D", "e": "Inhibitor presence is suggested when mixing study fails to correct prolonged aPTT; antibody against coagulation factor neutralises factor in normal plasma added.<br><br>Common inhibitors include factor VIII inhibitors in haemophilia A (10-30 percent of severe cases) and lupus anticoagulant. Treatment includes bypassing agents (FEIBA, recombinant factor VIIa) for haemophilia inhibitors. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Vitamin K deficiency (option A) corrects on mixing; platelet disorder (option B) does not affect aPTT; factor deficiency (option C) corrects on mixing, none being non-correcting mixing study cause like inhibitor presence.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A newborn bleeding from umbilical stump after 48 hours likely lacks:", "a": "Factor VIII", "b": "Vitamin K", "c": "Platelets", "d": "Fibrinogen", "ans": "B", "e": "Vitamin K deficiency causes newborn umbilical stump bleeding after 48 hours; this is classical haemorrhagic disease of newborn.<br><br>Mechanism includes low placental transfer, lack of intestinal flora, and low vitamin K content in breast milk. Prevention with vitamin K 1 mg IM at birth. Treatment with vitamin K injection and FFP for severe bleeding.<br><br>Factor VIII (option A) deficiency is haemophilia A (X-linked male); platelets (option C) deficiency causes mucocutaneous bleeding; fibrinogen (option D) deficiency is afibrinogenaemia (rare), none being umbilical stump bleeding cause like vitamin K deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hemophilia patients should avoid:", "a": "Factor therapy", "b": "Vaccination", "c": "Aspirin", "d": "Paracetamol", "ans": "C", "e": "Aspirin should be avoided in haemophilia patients; this irreversibly inhibits platelet aggregation worsening bleeding risk.<br><br>Other contraindicated medications include other NSAIDs, anticoagulants (warfarin, heparin), and antiplatelets (clopidogrel). Paracetamol safe for analgesia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Factor therapy (option A) is essential haemophilia treatment; vaccination (option B) is recommended; paracetamol (option D) is safe analgesic, none being contraindicated in haemophilia like aspirin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Severe bleeding in hemophilia unresponsive to factor VIII indicates:", "a": "Platelet disorder", "b": "Vitamin deficiency", "c": "DIC", "d": "Factor VIII inhibitors", "ans": "D", "e": "Factor VIII inhibitors cause severe bleeding unresponsive to factor VIII replacement in haemophilia A; antibodies neutralise infused factor VIII.<br><br>Develops in 10-30 percent of severe haemophilia A patients. Treatment with bypassing agents (FEIBA, recombinant factor VIIa). Immune tolerance induction with high-dose factor VIII may eliminate inhibitor. Emicizumab (bispecific antibody mimicking factor VIII function) for prophylaxis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Platelet disorder (option A) does not explain factor unresponsiveness; vitamin deficiency (option B) is unrelated; DIC (option C) features multiple abnormalities, none being factor VIII unresponsiveness mechanism like inhibitors.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Vitamin K dependent factors synthesized in:", "a": "Bone marrow", "b": "Liver", "c": "Kidney", "d": "Spleen", "ans": "B", "e": "Liver synthesises vitamin K-dependent factors; hepatocytes produce factors II, VII, IX, and X requiring vitamin K-mediated gamma-carboxylation for function.<br><br>Also produces fibrinogen, factor V, and most other coagulation factors. Liver disease causes generalised coagulopathy affecting multiple factors. Treatment with vitamin K (if deficient) and FFP for severe bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Bone marrow (option A) produces blood cells not coagulation factors; kidney (option C) produces erythropoietin; spleen (option D) is reticuloendothelial system, none being vitamin K-dependent factor synthesis site like liver.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Late vitamin K deficiency bleeding occurs:", "a": "First 24 hours", "b": "At birth", "c": "In adulthood only", "d": "2–12 weeks age", "ans": "D", "e": "Late vitamin K deficiency bleeding occurs at 2-12 weeks age; breast-fed infants with malabsorption or cholestasis develop bleeding from vitamin K deficiency.<br><br>Common presentation includes intracranial haemorrhage with high mortality. Prevention with vitamin K 1 mg IM at birth provides protection through this period. Treatment with vitamin K injection and FFP for severe bleeding.<br><br>First 24 hours (option A) is early form (maternal warfarin/antiepileptics); at birth (option B) is incorrect timing; adulthood only (option C) is incorrect, none being late VKDB timing like 2-12 weeks.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Mild hemophilia bleeding typically occurs:", "a": "During sleep", "b": "Spontaneously", "c": "After trauma or surgery", "d": "With infection", "ans": "C", "e": "After trauma or surgery is typical mild haemophilia bleeding pattern; factor activity 5-40 percent permits adequate baseline haemostasis but bleeding occurs with significant haemostatic challenge.<br><br>Combined with prolonged aPTT, normal PT, normal bleeding time, and reduced factor activity. Treatment with factor replacement for procedures or trauma. Desmopressin effective for mild haemophilia A. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>During sleep (option A) is not typical mild pattern; spontaneously (option B) is severe haemophilia pattern; with infection (option D) is non-specific, none being mild haemophilia pattern like after trauma or surgery.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with prolonged PT and aPTT due to warfarin overdose requires:", "a": "Vitamin K and possibly FFP", "b": "Iron", "c": "Platelets only", "d": "Factor VIII", "ans": "A", "e": "Vitamin K and possibly FFP treat warfarin overdose with prolonged PT and aPTT; vitamin K reverses warfarin effect (6-24 hours) while FFP or prothrombin complex concentrate provides immediate factor replacement.<br><br>Standard vitamin K 5-10 mg IV slowly. FFP or PCC for active bleeding or emergency surgery. Combined with stopping warfarin. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Iron (option B) is for iron deficiency; platelets only (option C) do not address factor deficiency; factor VIII (option D) is for haemophilia A, none being warfarin overdose reversal like vitamin K plus FFP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Recurrent deep muscle hematomas suggest:", "a": "Platelet disorder", "b": "Vasculitis", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "Vitamin deficiency", "ans": "C", "e": "Haemophilia causes recurrent deep muscle haematomas; factor VIII or IX deficiency impairs secondary haemostasis producing characteristic deep tissue bleeds.<br><br>Common sites include iliopsoas, calf, and forearm muscles. Compartment syndrome may complicate severe muscle haematomas. Treatment with factor replacement, RICE, and compartment monitoring. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Platelet disorder (option A) features mucocutaneous bleeding; vasculitis (option B) features palpable purpura; vitamin deficiency (option D) features prolonged PT first, none being recurrent deep muscle haematoma cause like haemophilia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Primary prevention of neonatal hemorrhagic disease:", "a": "Vitamin K at birth", "b": "Antibiotics", "c": "Factor VIII", "d": "Iron injection", "ans": "A", "e": "Vitamin K at birth is primary prevention of neonatal haemorrhagic disease; routine 1 mg IM dose protects through high-risk period.<br><br>Combined with addressing maternal medications (warfarin, antiepileptics) before delivery. Protection extends through 6 months for breast-fed infants. Some countries use oral regimen but IM remains gold standard. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including paediatrician.<br><br>Antibiotics (option B) are for infection prevention; factor VIII (option C) is for haemophilia A; iron injection (option D) is for iron deficiency, none being neonatal haemorrhagic disease prevention like vitamin K at birth.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Disseminated intravascular coagulation is best described as:", "a": "Isolated factor VIII deficiency", "b": "Localized thrombosis only", "c": "Systemic activation of coagulation with consumption of clotting factors", "d": "Primary platelet disorder", "ans": "C", "e": "Systemic activation of coagulation with consumption of clotting factors describes DIC; widespread coagulation activation depletes factors and platelets producing paradoxical bleeding.<br><br>Causes include sepsis, malignancy, obstetric complications, trauma, and severe haemorrhage. Diagnosis by prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, low platelets, elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes on smear.<br><br>Isolated factor VIII deficiency (option A) is haemophilia A; localised thrombosis only (option B) is venous thromboembolism; primary platelet disorder (option D) is ITP or other thrombocytopenia, none describing DIC like systemic coagulation activation with consumption.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common obstetric cause of DIC:", "a": "Abruptio placentae", "b": "Placenta previa", "c": "Ectopic pregnancy", "d": "Hyperemesis gravidarum", "ans": "A", "e": "Abruptio placentae is the most common obstetric cause of DIC; massive thromboplastin release from decidua triggers widespread coagulation activation.<br><br>Other obstetric DIC causes include amniotic fluid embolism, retained dead fetus, severe pre-eclampsia, and septic abortion. Treatment includes urgent delivery of fetus and placenta, addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, and platelet support. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician.<br><br>Placenta previa (option B) causes bleeding without DIC typically; ectopic pregnancy (option C) is intra-abdominal bleeding; hyperemesis gravidarum (option D) is nausea without coagulopathy, none being principal obstetric DIC trigger like abruptio placentae.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Laboratory hallmark of DIC:", "a": "Increased fibrinogen", "b": "Thrombocytosis", "c": "Shortened PT", "d": "Elevated fibrin degradation products", "ans": "D", "e": "Elevated fibrin degradation products is the laboratory hallmark of DIC; widespread fibrinolysis produces fragments including D-dimer.<br><br>Combined with prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, low platelets, and schistocytes on smear. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP for clotting factors, cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen, platelets for severe thrombocytopenia, and heparin for thrombotic predominance. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Increased fibrinogen (option A) is opposite (consumed in DIC); thrombocytosis (option B) is opposite (consumed); shortened PT (option C) is opposite (prolonged in DIC), none being DIC hallmark like elevated FDPs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Platelet count in DIC is typically:", "a": "Increased", "b": "Variable high", "c": "Decreased", "d": "Normal", "ans": "C", "e": "Platelet count is typically decreased in DIC; widespread coagulation activation consumes platelets producing thrombocytopenia.<br><br>Combined with prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes on smear. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, and platelets for severe thrombocytopenia with bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Increased (option A) is reactive thrombocytosis or essential thrombocythaemia; variable high (option B) is incorrect; normal (option D) is not DIC feature, none being DIC platelet trend like decreased.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Peripheral smear in DIC commonly shows:", "a": "Spherocytes", "b": "Schistocytes", "c": "Target cells", "d": "Macrocytes", "ans": "B", "e": "Schistocytes commonly appear on DIC peripheral smear; microvascular fibrin strands shear red cells producing fragmented erythrocytes.<br><br>Combined with thrombocytopenia, prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, and elevated D-dimer. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, and platelet support. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Spherocytes (option A) are hereditary spherocytosis or warm AIHA; target cells (option C) are thalassaemia or liver disease; macrocytes (option D) are megaloblastic, none being DIC smear finding like schistocytes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Fibrinogen level in DIC is usually:", "a": "Decreased", "b": "Extremely high", "c": "Increased", "d": "Normal", "ans": "A", "e": "Fibrinogen level is usually decreased in DIC; widespread coagulation activation consumes fibrinogen converting it to fibrin.<br><br>Combined with prolonged PT and aPTT, low platelets, elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes on smear. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP for clotting factors, cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen replacement, and platelets for severe thrombocytopenia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Extremely high (option B) is acute phase reactant in inflammation without DIC; increased (option C) is opposite; normal (option D) is not DIC pattern, none being DIC fibrinogen trend like decreased.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Initial management step in DIC:", "a": "Vitamin K", "b": "Anticoagulation immediately", "c": "Splenectomy", "d": "Treat underlying cause", "ans": "D", "e": "Treating underlying cause is initial management step in DIC; without addressing trigger (sepsis, malignancy, obstetric complication, trauma), coagulation activation continues.<br><br>Combined with FFP for clotting factors, cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen replacement, platelets for severe thrombocytopenia with bleeding, and heparin for thrombotic predominance. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Vitamin K (option A) is for vitamin K deficiency; anticoagulation immediately (option B) is reserved for thrombotic DIC; splenectomy (option C) is for hereditary spherocytosis, none being DIC initial step like addressing underlying cause.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Fresh frozen plasma is given in DIC to:", "a": "Replace clotting factors", "b": "Increase RBCs", "c": "Increase platelets", "d": "Stop fibrinolysis", "ans": "A", "e": "Replacing clotting factors is the role of fresh frozen plasma in DIC; FFP contains all consumed coagulation factors.<br><br>Standard dose 10-15 mL/kg. Combined with cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen (when under 1 g/L), platelet transfusion for severe thrombocytopenia with bleeding, and addressing underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Increase RBCs (option B) is red cell transfusion role; increase platelets (option C) is platelet transfusion role; stop fibrinolysis (option D) is tranexamic acid role, none being FFP role in DIC like clotting factor replacement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Heparin may be used in DIC when:", "a": "Platelets very low", "b": "Fibrinogen normal", "c": "Severe bleeding present", "d": "Predominant thrombosis", "ans": "D", "e": "Predominant thrombosis is indication for heparin in DIC; thrombotic phenotype (organ ischaemia, microvascular thrombosis) benefits from anticoagulation.<br><br>Standard low-dose heparin infusion under haematology supervision. Contraindicated in haemorrhagic DIC predominance. Combined with addressing underlying cause and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Platelets very low (option A) contraindicates heparin (bleeding risk); fibrinogen normal (option B) is non-specific; severe bleeding present (option C) contraindicates heparin, none being heparin indication in DIC like thrombosis predominance.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which condition most commonly triggers DIC in ICU patients:", "a": "Diabetes", "b": "Sepsis", "c": "Asthma", "d": "Hypertension", "ans": "B", "e": "Sepsis most commonly triggers DIC in ICU patients; bacterial endotoxin and inflammatory cytokines activate widespread coagulation.<br><br>Combined with antimicrobial therapy targeting infection, source control, and addressing organ failure. Treatment includes FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Diabetes (option A) is not principal DIC trigger; asthma (option C) is unrelated; hypertension (option D) is unrelated, none being ICU DIC principal trigger like sepsis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A septic patient develops bleeding from IV sites, prolonged PT and aPTT, low platelets and elevated D-dimer after 48 hours in ICU. The most likely diagnosis is:", "a": "ITP", "b": "Liver cirrhosis", "c": "DIC", "d": "Hemophilia", "ans": "C", "e": "DIC is the most likely diagnosis for septic ICU patient with bleeding from IV sites, prolonged PT and aPTT, low platelets, and elevated D-dimer; sepsis-driven coagulation activation produces this classical pattern.<br><br>Combined with low fibrinogen and schistocytes on smear. Treatment includes addressing underlying sepsis, FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, and supportive care.<br><br>ITP (option A) features isolated thrombocytopenia with normal coagulation; liver cirrhosis (option B) prolongs PT and aPTT but D-dimer not principally elevated; haemophilia (option D) features prolonged aPTT only with normal platelets, none fitting sepsis-driven panel like DIC.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A trauma patient develops oozing wounds, hypotension and lab evidence of low fibrinogen with schistocytes. This occurs due to widespread:", "a": "Platelet deficiency", "b": "Vitamin K deficiency", "c": "Factor VIII inhibitor", "d": "Microvascular thrombosis", "ans": "D", "e": "Microvascular thrombosis explains trauma DIC with oozing wounds, hypotension, low fibrinogen, and schistocytes; widespread fibrin deposition in small vessels consumes coagulation factors and shears red cells.<br><br>Treatment includes urgent damage control, FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, tranexamic acid in major haemorrhage, and addressing underlying trauma. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Platelet deficiency (option A) alone is ITP; vitamin K deficiency (option B) prolongs PT but lacks schistocytes; factor VIII inhibitor (option C) is haemophilia inhibitor, none being trauma DIC mechanism like widespread microvascular thrombosis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with DIC and severe bleeding should receive:", "a": "Desmopressin", "b": "Platelets and FFP", "c": "Aspirin", "d": "Warfarin", "ans": "B", "e": "Platelets and FFP treat DIC with severe bleeding; combination provides platelets and consumed coagulation factors.<br><br>Combined with cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen under 1 g/L, addressing underlying cause, and tranexamic acid in massive haemorrhage. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Desmopressin (option A) is for vWD and mild haemophilia A; aspirin (option C) worsens bleeding; warfarin (option D) worsens bleeding, none being severe DIC bleeding therapy like platelets-FFP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A postpartum woman with massive hemorrhage develops DIC. Most appropriate first step:", "a": "Give heparin", "b": "Iron therapy", "c": "Control obstetric cause", "d": "Splenectomy", "ans": "C", "e": "Controlling obstetric cause is first step in postpartum massive haemorrhage with DIC; uterine atony, retained placenta, or trauma must be addressed alongside coagulopathy correction.<br><br>Combined with FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, tranexamic acid (high dose), and uterotonics (oxytocin, ergometrine, carboprost). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Heparin (option A) worsens haemorrhagic bleeding; iron therapy (option B) is supportive not emergency; splenectomy (option D) is for hereditary spherocytosis, none being postpartum DIC first step like obstetric cause control.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A cancer patient develops chronic DIC with thrombosis predominance. Best therapy:", "a": "Heparin", "b": "Vitamin K", "c": "Platelets", "d": "Folic acid", "ans": "A", "e": "Heparin is best therapy for cancer-associated chronic DIC with thrombosis predominance; anticoagulation interrupts widespread microvascular thrombosis.<br><br>Common in adenocarcinomas (pancreatic, gastric, prostate). Standard low-molecular-weight heparin therapy. Combined with addressing underlying malignancy and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Vitamin K (option B) worsens thrombosis; platelets (option C) worsen thrombosis; folic acid (option D) is for megaloblastic anaemia, none being chronic thrombotic DIC therapy like heparin.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "DIC differs from TTP because DIC shows:", "a": "Normal coagulation tests", "b": "Prolonged PT and aPTT", "c": "Only thrombocytopenia", "d": "Normal fibrinogen", "ans": "B", "e": "Prolonged PT and aPTT distinguish DIC from TTP; consumption of coagulation factors in DIC prolongs both screening tests while TTP shows normal coagulation.<br><br>Combined with low fibrinogen, low platelets, elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes in DIC. TTP features normal PT and aPTT with isolated thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolysis. Treatment differs significantly. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Normal coagulation tests (option A) is TTP feature; only thrombocytopenia (option C) is ITP or TTP; normal fibrinogen (option D) is TTP feature, none distinguishing DIC from TTP like prolonged PT-aPTT.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura pentad includes all except:", "a": "Hypercalcemia", "b": "Renal failure", "c": "Neurological symptoms", "d": "Fever", "ans": "A", "e": "Hypercalcaemia is NOT part of TTP pentad; the classical TTP pentad includes microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, neurological symptoms, fever, and renal failure.<br><br>Complete pentad uncommon; diagnosis often made with thrombocytopenia plus microangiopathic haemolysis (schistocytes). Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, and rituximab for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Renal failure (option B) is part of pentad; neurological symptoms (option C) are part of pentad; fever (option D) is part of pentad, none being absent from TTP pentad like hypercalcaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Pathogenesis of TTP involves deficiency of:", "a": "Antithrombin", "b": "Protein C", "c": "Factor VIII", "d": "ADAMTS13", "ans": "D", "e": "ADAMTS13 deficiency causes TTP pathogenesis; this metalloprotease normally cleaves ultra-large vWF multimers, and deficiency produces vWF-platelet microthrombi.<br><br>Mechanism includes either autoimmune (acquired TTP, more common) with antibodies against ADAMTS13 or congenital deficiency (Upshaw-Schulman syndrome). Diagnosis by ADAMTS13 activity under 10 percent. Treatment with urgent plasma exchange, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Antithrombin (option A) deficiency causes thrombophilia; protein C (option B) deficiency causes thrombophilia; factor VIII (option C) deficiency is haemophilia A, none being TTP-specific deficiency like ADAMTS13.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most effective treatment for TTP:", "a": "Vitamin K", "b": "Platelet transfusion", "c": "Plasma exchange", "d": "Heparin", "ans": "C", "e": "Plasma exchange is the most effective TTP treatment; removes ADAMTS13 antibodies and replaces missing enzyme.<br><br>Standard daily plasma exchange (40-60 mL/kg) with FFP replacement until platelet recovery. Combined with corticosteroids and rituximab for refractory disease. Caplacizumab (anti-vWF nanobody) reduces refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Vitamin K (option A) is for vitamin K deficiency; platelet transfusion (option B) worsens TTP thrombosis; heparin (option D) is for DIC thrombotic predominance, none being TTP definitive therapy like plasma exchange.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Platelet transfusion in TTP is avoided because it:", "a": "Worsens thrombosis", "b": "Causes anemia", "c": "Raises PT", "d": "Causes leukocytosis", "ans": "A", "e": "Platelet transfusion in TTP worsens thrombosis; supplied platelets immediately aggregate on ultra-large vWF multimers exacerbating microvascular thrombosis.<br><br>Reserved only for life-threatening bleeding. Standard treatment is urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, and rituximab for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Causes anaemia (option B) is uncommon; raises PT (option C) is incorrect; causes leukocytosis (option D) is incorrect, none being principal platelet-transfusion-in-TTP risk like worsening thrombosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A young woman presents with confusion, fever, petechiae, anemia and renal impairment. Peripheral smear shows schistocytes but PT and aPTT are normal. Diagnosis:", "a": "DIC", "b": "TTP", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "ITP", "ans": "B", "e": "TTP fits young woman with confusion, fever, petechiae, anaemia, renal impairment, schistocytes, and normal coagulation; pentad of TTP features with microangiopathic haemolysis distinguishes from DIC.<br><br>Diagnosis confirmed by ADAMTS13 activity under 10 percent. Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>DIC (option A) features prolonged PT and aPTT and low fibrinogen; haemophilia (option C) features prolonged aPTT and male X-linked; ITP (option D) features isolated thrombocytopenia without schistocytes or renal failure, none fitting this pentad like TTP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hemolytic uremic syndrome is characterized by triad of:", "a": "Hemarthrosis, anemia, splenomegaly", "b": "Fever, rash, arthritis", "c": "Hemolysis, renal failure, thrombocytopenia", "d": "Jaundice, ascites, edema", "ans": "C", "e": "Haemolysis, renal failure, and thrombocytopenia form the HUS triad; microangiopathic process produces this classical clinical pattern.<br><br>Distinguishing from TTP (pentad includes neurological symptoms and fever, less renal predominance) and DIC (prolonged coagulation tests). Treatment varies by type: supportive care plus dialysis for typical (Shiga toxin), plasma exchange and eculizumab for atypical. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Haemarthrosis-anaemia-splenomegaly (option A) is not HUS; fever-rash-arthritis (option B) is rheumatological; jaundice-ascites-oedema (option D) is liver disease, none being HUS triad like haemolysis-renal failure-thrombocytopenia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Typical HUS commonly follows infection with:", "a": "Salmonella typhi", "b": "Mycoplasma", "c": "Staphylococcus aureus", "d": "E. coli O157:H7", "ans": "D", "e": "E. coli O157:H7 commonly triggers typical HUS; Shiga toxin-producing strains cause this microangiopathic syndrome after bloody diarrhoea.<br><br>Other Shiga toxin-producing organisms include Shigella dysenteriae. Treatment includes supportive care, dialysis if needed, and avoiding antibiotics (may worsen by releasing more toxin). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Salmonella typhi (option A) causes typhoid not HUS; Mycoplasma (option B) causes cold agglutinin disease; Staphylococcus aureus (option C) causes various infections, none being typical HUS principal trigger like E. coli O157:H7.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Primary pathology in HUS involves:", "a": "Factor VIII inhibitor", "b": "Platelet destruction by antibodies", "c": "Endothelial damage by Shiga toxin", "d": "Vitamin deficiency", "ans": "C", "e": "Endothelial damage by Shiga toxin is primary HUS pathology; toxin binds Gb3 receptors on endothelial cells producing damage with platelet aggregation, microthrombi, and microangiopathic haemolysis.<br><br>Particularly affects glomerular endothelium producing acute kidney injury. Combined with thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia. Treatment includes supportive care and dialysis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Factor VIII inhibitor (option A) is haemophilia inhibitor; platelet destruction by antibodies (option B) is ITP; vitamin deficiency (option D) is unrelated, none being HUS primary pathology like Shiga toxin endothelial damage.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Management of typical HUS mainly:", "a": "Steroids", "b": "Supportive care and dialysis if needed", "c": "Heparin", "d": "Plasma exchange", "ans": "B", "e": "Supportive care and dialysis if needed is mainstay of typical HUS management; self-limiting course with renal support during acute phase.<br><br>Antibiotic therapy controversial (may worsen Shiga toxin release). Avoiding antimotility drugs important. Eculizumab not standard for typical HUS (used in atypical). Recovery usually complete with appropriate supportive care. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Steroids (option A) are not standard typical HUS therapy; heparin (option C) worsens bleeding risk; plasma exchange (option D) is for TTP or atypical HUS, none being typical HUS standard management like supportive care plus dialysis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Normal coagulation profile helps differentiate TTP/HUS from:", "a": "DIC", "b": "ITP", "c": "vWD", "d": "Hemophilia", "ans": "A", "e": "DIC is distinguished from TTP/HUS by normal coagulation profile in TTP/HUS; TTP/HUS shows normal PT, normal aPTT, and normal fibrinogen with isolated thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolysis.<br><br>DIC features prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, elevated D-dimer, and consumption coagulopathy. Distinguishing guides treatment (plasma exchange for TTP, addressing underlying cause for DIC). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>ITP (option B) features isolated thrombocytopenia without schistocytes; vWD (option C) features mucocutaneous bleeding; haemophilia (option D) features deep tissue bleeds, none being DIC differential like normal-coagulation TTP/HUS.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Schistocytes in TTP result from:", "a": "Immune hemolysis", "b": "Osmotic fragility", "c": "Iron deficiency", "d": "Microangiopathic hemolysis", "ans": "D", "e": "Microangiopathic haemolysis produces schistocytes in TTP; vWF-platelet microthrombi in small vessels mechanically shear red cells.<br><br>Combined with thrombocytopenia, elevated LDH, low haptoglobin, and elevated indirect bilirubin. Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Immune haemolysis (option A) produces spherocytes with positive Coombs; osmotic fragility (option B) is hereditary spherocytosis; iron deficiency (option C) produces pencil cells, none being TTP schistocyte mechanism like microangiopathic haemolysis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Renal involvement is most prominent in:", "a": "vWD", "b": "HUS", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "TTP", "ans": "B", "e": "HUS features most prominent renal involvement; Shiga toxin particularly damages glomerular endothelium producing acute kidney injury as dominant feature.<br><br>Combined with microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia and thrombocytopenia. Treatment includes supportive care and dialysis if needed. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>vWD (option A) features mucocutaneous bleeding without renal involvement; haemophilia (option C) features deep tissue bleeds; TTP (option D) features more prominent neurological involvement, none being as renal-predominant as HUS.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Neurological symptoms are more severe in:", "a": "HUS", "b": "Hemophilia", "c": "ITP", "d": "TTP", "ans": "D", "e": "TTP features more severe neurological symptoms; ADAMTS13 deficiency-driven microthrombi in cerebral microvasculature produce confusion, headache, seizures, and focal deficits.<br><br>Combined with thrombocytopenia, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, renal involvement, and fever (pentad). Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>HUS (option A) features more renal involvement; haemophilia (option B) features deep tissue bleeds without neurological symptoms; ITP (option C) features isolated thrombocytopenia, none being as neurology-prominent as TTP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Plasma exchange works in TTP by:", "a": "Removing antibodies and supplying ADAMTS13", "b": "Preventing hemolysis", "c": "Increasing fibrinogen", "d": "Increasing platelets", "ans": "A", "e": "Removing antibodies and supplying ADAMTS13 is plasma exchange mechanism in TTP; removes anti-ADAMTS13 antibodies and replaces missing enzyme through FFP.<br><br>Standard daily plasma exchange (40-60 mL/kg) with FFP replacement until platelet recovery. Combined with corticosteroids and rituximab for refractory disease. Caplacizumab (anti-vWF nanobody) reduces refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Preventing haemolysis (option B) is consequence not mechanism; increasing fibrinogen (option C) is not principal mechanism; increasing platelets (option D) is consequence not mechanism, none being plasma exchange TTP mechanism like ADAMTS13 supply with antibody removal.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Disseminated intravascular coagulation is best described as:", "a": "Localized thrombosis only", "b": "Primary platelet disorder", "c": "Systemic activation of coagulation with consumption of clotting factors", "d": "Isolated factor VIII deficiency", "ans": "C", "e": "Systemic activation of coagulation with consumption of clotting factors describes DIC; widespread coagulation activation depletes factors and platelets producing paradoxical bleeding.<br><br>Causes include sepsis, malignancy, obstetric complications, trauma, and severe haemorrhage. Diagnosis by prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, low platelets, elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes on smear.<br><br>Localised thrombosis only (option A) is venous thromboembolism; primary platelet disorder (option B) is ITP or other thrombocytopenia; isolated factor VIII deficiency (option D) is haemophilia A, none describing DIC like systemic activation with consumption.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most common obstetric cause of DIC:", "a": "Abruptio placentae", "b": "Hyperemesis gravidarum", "c": "Ectopic pregnancy", "d": "Placenta previa", "ans": "A", "e": "Abruptio placentae is most common obstetric DIC cause; placental separation releases massive thromboplastin triggering widespread coagulation activation.<br><br>Other obstetric DIC causes include amniotic fluid embolism, retained dead fetus, severe pre-eclampsia, and septic abortion. Treatment includes urgent delivery, addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, and platelet support. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician.<br><br>Hyperemesis gravidarum (option B) is nausea without coagulopathy; ectopic pregnancy (option C) is intra-abdominal bleeding; placenta previa (option D) causes bleeding without DIC typically, none being principal obstetric DIC cause like abruptio placentae.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Laboratory hallmark of DIC:", "a": "Shortened PT", "b": "Elevated fibrin degradation products", "c": "Thrombocytosis", "d": "Increased fibrinogen", "ans": "B", "e": "Elevated fibrin degradation products is DIC laboratory hallmark; widespread fibrinolysis produces fragments including D-dimer.<br><br>Combined with prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, low platelets, and schistocytes. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, and platelet support. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Shortened PT (option A) is opposite (prolonged in DIC); thrombocytosis (option C) is opposite (consumed); increased fibrinogen (option D) is opposite (consumed), none being DIC hallmark like elevated FDPs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Platelet count in DIC is typically:", "a": "Normal", "b": "Variable high", "c": "Increased", "d": "Decreased", "ans": "D", "e": "Platelet count is decreased in DIC; widespread coagulation activation consumes platelets producing thrombocytopenia.<br><br>Combined with prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, and platelets for severe thrombocytopenia with bleeding. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Long-term follow-up is essential. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Normal (option A) is not DIC feature; variable high (option B) is incorrect; increased (option C) is opposite, none being DIC platelet trend like decreased.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Peripheral smear in DIC commonly shows:", "a": "Target cells", "b": "Macrocytes", "c": "Schistocytes", "d": "Spherocytes", "ans": "C", "e": "Schistocytes commonly appear on DIC peripheral smear; microvascular fibrin strands shear red cells producing fragmented erythrocytes.<br><br>Combined with thrombocytopenia, prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, and elevated D-dimer. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, and platelet support. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Target cells (option A) are thalassaemia or liver disease; macrocytes (option B) are megaloblastic; spherocytes (option D) are hereditary spherocytosis or warm AIHA, none being DIC smear finding like schistocytes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Fibrinogen level in DIC is usually:", "a": "Increased", "b": "Decreased", "c": "Extremely high", "d": "Normal", "ans": "B", "e": "Fibrinogen level is decreased in DIC; widespread coagulation activation consumes fibrinogen converting to fibrin.<br><br>Combined with prolonged PT and aPTT, low platelets, elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP for clotting factors, cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen replacement (when under 1 g/L), and platelets for severe thrombocytopenia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Increased (option A) is acute phase reactant without DIC; extremely high (option C) is opposite; normal (option D) is not DIC, none being DIC fibrinogen trend like decreased.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Initial management step in DIC:", "a": "Treat underlying cause", "b": "Anticoagulation immediately", "c": "Splenectomy", "d": "Vitamin K", "ans": "A", "e": "Treating underlying cause is DIC initial management step; without addressing trigger (sepsis, malignancy, obstetric complication, trauma), coagulation activation continues.<br><br>Combined with FFP for clotting factors, cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen replacement, platelets for severe thrombocytopenia with bleeding, and heparin for thrombotic predominance. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Anticoagulation immediately (option B) is reserved for thrombotic DIC; splenectomy (option C) is for hereditary spherocytosis; vitamin K (option D) is for vitamin K deficiency, none being DIC initial step like underlying cause control.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Fresh frozen plasma is given in DIC to:", "a": "Increase RBCs", "b": "Increase platelets", "c": "Replace clotting factors", "d": "Stop fibrinolysis", "ans": "C", "e": "Replacing clotting factors is FFP role in DIC; FFP contains all consumed coagulation factors.<br><br>Standard dose 10-15 mL/kg. Combined with cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen (when under 1 g/L), platelet transfusion for severe thrombocytopenia with bleeding, and addressing underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Increase RBCs (option A) is red cell transfusion; increase platelets (option B) is platelet transfusion; stop fibrinolysis (option D) is tranexamic acid, none being FFP DIC role like clotting factor replacement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Heparin may be used in DIC when:", "a": "Fibrinogen normal", "b": "Severe bleeding present", "c": "Platelets very low", "d": "Predominant thrombosis", "ans": "D", "e": "Predominant thrombosis is heparin indication in DIC; thrombotic phenotype (organ ischaemia, microvascular thrombosis) benefits from anticoagulation.<br><br>Standard low-dose heparin infusion under haematology supervision. Contraindicated in haemorrhagic DIC. Combined with addressing underlying cause and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>Fibrinogen normal (option A) is non-specific; severe bleeding present (option B) contraindicates heparin; platelets very low (option C) contraindicates heparin (bleeding risk), none being heparin DIC indication like thrombosis predominance.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Which condition most commonly triggers DIC in ICU patients:", "a": "Hypertension", "b": "Sepsis", "c": "Diabetes", "d": "Asthma", "ans": "B", "e": "Sepsis most commonly triggers ICU DIC; bacterial endotoxin and inflammatory cytokines activate widespread coagulation.<br><br>Combined with antimicrobial therapy targeting infection, source control, and addressing organ failure. Treatment includes FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Hypertension (option A) is unrelated; diabetes (option C) is not principal trigger; asthma (option D) is unrelated, none being ICU DIC principal trigger like sepsis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A septic patient develops bleeding from IV sites, prolonged PT and aPTT, low platelets and elevated D-dimer after 48 hours in ICU. The most likely diagnosis is:", "a": "DIC", "b": "Hemophilia", "c": "ITP", "d": "Liver cirrhosis", "ans": "A", "e": "DIC is the most likely diagnosis for septic ICU patient with bleeding from IV sites, prolonged PT and aPTT, low platelets, and elevated D-dimer; sepsis-driven coagulation activation produces this classical pattern.<br><br>Combined with low fibrinogen and schistocytes on smear. Treatment includes addressing underlying sepsis, FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, and supportive care. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemophilia (option B) features isolated aPTT prolongation; ITP (option C) features isolated thrombocytopenia; liver cirrhosis (option D) prolongs PT-aPTT but D-dimer not principally elevated, none fitting sepsis-driven panel like DIC.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A trauma patient develops oozing wounds, hypotension and lab evidence of low fibrinogen with schistocytes. This occurs due to widespread:", "a": "Platelet deficiency", "b": "Factor VIII inhibitor", "c": "Microvascular thrombosis", "d": "Vitamin K deficiency", "ans": "C", "e": "Microvascular thrombosis explains trauma DIC with oozing wounds, hypotension, low fibrinogen, and schistocytes; widespread fibrin deposition in small vessels consumes coagulation factors and shears red cells.<br><br>Treatment includes urgent damage control, FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, tranexamic acid in major haemorrhage, and addressing underlying trauma. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Platelet deficiency (option A) alone is ITP; factor VIII inhibitor (option B) is haemophilia inhibitor; vitamin K deficiency (option D) prolongs PT but lacks schistocytes, none being trauma DIC mechanism like microvascular thrombosis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with DIC and severe bleeding should receive:", "a": "Warfarin", "b": "Aspirin", "c": "Desmopressin", "d": "Platelets and FFP", "ans": "D", "e": "Platelets and FFP treat DIC with severe bleeding; combination provides platelets and consumed coagulation factors.<br><br>Combined with cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen under 1 g/L, addressing underlying cause, and tranexamic acid in massive haemorrhage. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Warfarin (option A) worsens bleeding; aspirin (option B) worsens bleeding; desmopressin (option C) is for vWD and mild haemophilia A, none being severe DIC bleeding therapy like platelets-FFP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A postpartum woman with massive hemorrhage develops DIC. Most appropriate first step:", "a": "Control obstetric cause", "b": "Splenectomy", "c": "Give heparin", "d": "Iron therapy", "ans": "A", "e": "Controlling obstetric cause is first step in postpartum massive haemorrhage with DIC; uterine atony, retained placenta, or trauma must be addressed alongside coagulopathy correction.<br><br>Combined with FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, tranexamic acid (high dose), and uterotonics (oxytocin, ergometrine, carboprost). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Splenectomy (option B) is for hereditary spherocytosis; heparin (option C) worsens haemorrhagic bleeding; iron therapy (option D) is supportive not emergency, none being postpartum DIC first step like obstetric cause control.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A cancer patient develops chronic DIC with thrombosis predominance. Best therapy:", "a": "Vitamin K", "b": "Folic acid", "c": "Platelets", "d": "Heparin", "ans": "D", "e": "Heparin is best therapy for cancer-associated chronic DIC with thrombosis predominance; anticoagulation interrupts widespread microvascular thrombosis.<br><br>Common in adenocarcinomas (pancreatic, gastric, prostate). Standard low-molecular-weight heparin therapy. Combined with addressing underlying malignancy and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>Vitamin K (option A) worsens thrombosis; folic acid (option B) is for megaloblastic anaemia; platelets (option C) worsen thrombosis, none being chronic thrombotic DIC therapy like heparin.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "DIC differs from TTP because DIC shows:", "a": "Only thrombocytopenia", "b": "Prolonged PT and aPTT", "c": "Normal fibrinogen", "d": "Normal coagulation tests", "ans": "B", "e": "Prolonged PT and aPTT distinguish DIC from TTP; consumption of coagulation factors in DIC prolongs both screening tests while TTP shows normal coagulation.<br><br>Combined with low fibrinogen, low platelets, elevated D-dimer, and schistocytes in DIC. TTP features normal PT and aPTT with isolated thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolysis. Treatment differs significantly. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Only thrombocytopenia (option A) is ITP or TTP; normal fibrinogen (option C) is TTP feature; normal coagulation tests (option D) is TTP feature, none distinguishing DIC from TTP like prolonged PT-aPTT.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura pentad includes all except:", "a": "Fever", "b": "Neurological symptoms", "c": "Hypercalcemia", "d": "Renal failure", "ans": "C", "e": "Hypercalcaemia is NOT part of TTP pentad; classical TTP pentad includes microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, neurological symptoms, fever, and renal failure.<br><br>Complete pentad uncommon; diagnosis often made with thrombocytopenia plus microangiopathic haemolysis (schistocytes). Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, and rituximab for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Fever (option A) is part of pentad; neurological symptoms (option B) are part of pentad; renal failure (option D) is part of pentad, none being absent from TTP pentad like hypercalcaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Pathogenesis of TTP involves deficiency of:", "a": "Antithrombin", "b": "Protein C", "c": "Factor VIII", "d": "ADAMTS13", "ans": "D", "e": "ADAMTS13 deficiency causes TTP; this metalloprotease normally cleaves ultra-large vWF multimers, and deficiency produces vWF-platelet microthrombi.<br><br>Mechanism includes either autoimmune (acquired TTP, more common) with antibodies against ADAMTS13 or congenital deficiency. Diagnosis by ADAMTS13 activity under 10 percent. Treatment with urgent plasma exchange, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Antithrombin (option A) deficiency causes thrombophilia; protein C (option B) deficiency causes thrombophilia; factor VIII (option C) deficiency is haemophilia A, none being TTP-specific deficiency like ADAMTS13.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Most effective treatment for TTP:", "a": "Plasma exchange", "b": "Heparin", "c": "Vitamin K", "d": "Platelet transfusion", "ans": "A", "e": "Plasma exchange is the most effective TTP treatment; removes ADAMTS13 antibodies and replaces missing enzyme.<br><br>Standard daily plasma exchange (40-60 mL/kg) with FFP replacement until platelet recovery. Combined with corticosteroids and rituximab for refractory disease. Caplacizumab (anti-vWF nanobody) reduces refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Heparin (option B) is for DIC thrombotic predominance; vitamin K (option C) is for vitamin K deficiency; platelet transfusion (option D) worsens TTP thrombosis, none being TTP definitive therapy like plasma exchange.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Platelet transfusion in TTP is avoided because it:", "a": "Causes anemia", "b": "Worsens thrombosis", "c": "Causes leukocytosis", "d": "Raises PT", "ans": "B", "e": "Platelet transfusion in TTP worsens thrombosis; supplied platelets immediately aggregate on ultra-large vWF multimers exacerbating microvascular thrombosis.<br><br>Reserved only for life-threatening bleeding. Standard treatment is urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, and rituximab for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Causes anaemia (option A) is uncommon; causes leukocytosis (option C) is incorrect; raises PT (option D) is incorrect, none being principal platelet-transfusion-in-TTP risk like worsening thrombosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A young woman presents with confusion, fever, petechiae, anemia and renal impairment. Peripheral smear shows schistocytes but PT and aPTT are normal. Diagnosis:", "a": "DIC", "b": "ITP", "c": "TTP", "d": "Hemophilia", "ans": "C", "e": "TTP fits young woman with confusion, fever, petechiae, anaemia, renal impairment, schistocytes, and normal coagulation; pentad of TTP features with microangiopathic haemolysis distinguishes from DIC.<br><br>Diagnosis confirmed by ADAMTS13 activity under 10 percent. Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>DIC (option A) features prolonged PT and aPTT and low fibrinogen; ITP (option B) features isolated thrombocytopenia without schistocytes or renal failure; haemophilia (option D) features prolonged aPTT and male X-linked, none fitting this pentad like TTP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hemolytic uremic syndrome is characterized by triad of:", "a": "Hemarthrosis, anemia, splenomegaly", "b": "Fever, rash, arthritis", "c": "Jaundice, ascites, edema", "d": "Hemolysis, renal failure, thrombocytopenia", "ans": "D", "e": "Haemolysis, renal failure, and thrombocytopenia form the HUS triad; microangiopathic process produces this classical clinical pattern.<br><br>Distinguishing from TTP (pentad includes neurological symptoms and fever, less renal predominance) and DIC (prolonged coagulation tests). Treatment varies: supportive care plus dialysis for typical (Shiga toxin), plasma exchange and eculizumab for atypical. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Haemarthrosis-anaemia-splenomegaly (option A) is not HUS; fever-rash-arthritis (option B) is rheumatological; jaundice-ascites-oedema (option C) is liver disease, none being HUS triad like haemolysis-renal failure-thrombocytopenia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Typical HUS commonly follows infection with:", "a": "E. coli O157:H7", "b": "Staphylococcus aureus", "c": "Salmonella typhi", "d": "Mycoplasma", "ans": "A", "e": "E. coli O157:H7 commonly triggers typical HUS; Shiga toxin-producing strains cause this microangiopathic syndrome after bloody diarrhoea.<br><br>Other Shiga toxin-producing organisms include Shigella dysenteriae. Treatment includes supportive care, dialysis if needed, and avoiding antibiotics (may worsen by releasing more toxin). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus (option B) causes various infections; Salmonella typhi (option C) causes typhoid; Mycoplasma (option D) causes cold agglutinin disease, none being typical HUS principal trigger like E. coli O157:H7.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Primary pathology in HUS involves:", "a": "Vitamin deficiency", "b": "Endothelial damage by Shiga toxin", "c": "Platelet destruction by antibodies", "d": "Factor VIII inhibitor", "ans": "B", "e": "Endothelial damage by Shiga toxin is HUS primary pathology; toxin binds Gb3 receptors on endothelial cells producing damage with platelet aggregation, microthrombi, and microangiopathic haemolysis.<br><br>Particularly affects glomerular endothelium producing acute kidney injury. Combined with thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia. Treatment includes supportive care and dialysis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Vitamin deficiency (option A) is unrelated; platelet destruction by antibodies (option C) is ITP; factor VIII inhibitor (option D) is haemophilia inhibitor, none being HUS primary pathology like Shiga toxin endothelial damage.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Management of typical HUS mainly:", "a": "Steroids", "b": "Plasma exchange", "c": "Supportive care and dialysis if needed", "d": "Heparin", "ans": "C", "e": "Supportive care and dialysis if needed is mainstay of typical HUS management; self-limiting course with renal support during acute phase.<br><br>Antibiotic therapy controversial (may worsen Shiga toxin release). Avoiding antimotility drugs important. Eculizumab not standard for typical HUS. Recovery usually complete with supportive care. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Steroids (option A) are not standard typical HUS therapy; plasma exchange (option B) is for TTP or atypical HUS; heparin (option D) worsens bleeding risk, none being typical HUS standard management like supportive care plus dialysis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Normal coagulation profile helps differentiate TTP/HUS from:", "a": "Hemophilia", "b": "ITP", "c": "vWD", "d": "DIC", "ans": "D", "e": "DIC is distinguished from TTP/HUS by normal coagulation profile in TTP/HUS; TTP/HUS shows normal PT, normal aPTT, and normal fibrinogen with isolated thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic haemolysis.<br><br>DIC features prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, elevated D-dimer, and consumption coagulopathy. Distinguishing guides treatment (plasma exchange for TTP, addressing underlying cause for DIC). Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemophilia (option A) features prolonged aPTT with male X-linked; ITP (option B) features isolated thrombocytopenia without schistocytes; vWD (option C) features mucocutaneous bleeding, none being TTP/HUS differential like DIC.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Schistocytes in TTP result from:", "a": "Microangiopathic hemolysis", "b": "Osmotic fragility", "c": "Immune hemolysis", "d": "Iron deficiency", "ans": "A", "e": "Microangiopathic haemolysis produces schistocytes in TTP; vWF-platelet microthrombi in small vessels mechanically shear red cells.<br><br>Combined with thrombocytopenia, elevated LDH, low haptoglobin, and elevated indirect bilirubin. Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Osmotic fragility (option B) is hereditary spherocytosis; immune haemolysis (option C) produces spherocytes with positive Coombs; iron deficiency (option D) produces pencil cells, none being TTP schistocyte mechanism like microangiopathic haemolysis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Renal involvement is most prominent in:", "a": "TTP", "b": "HUS", "c": "vWD", "d": "Hemophilia", "ans": "B", "e": "HUS features most prominent renal involvement; Shiga toxin particularly damages glomerular endothelium producing acute kidney injury as dominant feature.<br><br>Combined with microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia and thrombocytopenia. Treatment includes supportive care and dialysis if needed. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>TTP (option A) features more prominent neurological involvement; vWD (option C) features mucocutaneous bleeding without renal; haemophilia (option D) features deep tissue bleeds, none being as renal-predominant as HUS.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Neurological symptoms are more severe in:", "a": "ITP", "b": "Hemophilia", "c": "TTP", "d": "HUS", "ans": "C", "e": "TTP features more severe neurological symptoms; ADAMTS13 deficiency-driven microthrombi in cerebral microvasculature produce confusion, headache, seizures, and focal deficits.<br><br>Combined with thrombocytopenia, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, renal involvement, and fever (pentad). Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Risk factor modification supports outcomes.<br><br>ITP (option A) features isolated thrombocytopenia; haemophilia (option B) features deep tissue bleeds without neurological symptoms; HUS (option D) features more renal involvement, none being as neurology-prominent as TTP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Plasma exchange works in TTP by:", "a": "Removing antibodies and supplying ADAMTS13", "b": "Increasing platelets", "c": "Preventing hemolysis", "d": "Increasing fibrinogen", "ans": "A", "e": "Removing antibodies and supplying ADAMTS13 is plasma exchange mechanism in TTP; removes anti-ADAMTS13 antibodies and replaces missing enzyme through FFP.<br><br>Standard daily plasma exchange (40-60 mL/kg) with FFP replacement until platelet recovery. Combined with corticosteroids and rituximab for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Increasing platelets (option B) is consequence not mechanism; preventing haemolysis (option C) is consequence; increasing fibrinogen (option D) is not principal mechanism, none being plasma exchange TTP mechanism like ADAMTS13 supply with antibody removal.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A septic shock patient develops bleeding from gums and IV sites along with hypotension and labs showing thrombocytopenia, prolonged PT/aPTT and elevated D-dimer, indicating systemic consumption of coagulation factors triggered by inflammatory cytokines and endotoxin-mediated tissue factor activation. The condition is:", "a": "Hemophilia", "b": "DIC", "c": "HUS", "d": "TTP", "ans": "B", "e": "DIC fits septic shock with bleeding from gums and IV sites, hypotension, thrombocytopenia, prolonged PT/aPTT, elevated D-dimer; endotoxin-mediated tissue factor activation triggers consumption coagulopathy.<br><br>Treatment includes addressing underlying sepsis, FFP for clotting factors, cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen, platelets for severe thrombocytopenia with bleeding, and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemophilia (option A) features isolated aPTT prolongation; HUS (option C) features renal-predominant microangiopathy with normal coagulation; TTP (option D) features pentad with normal coagulation, none fitting septic consumption coagulopathy like DIC.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child develops acute renal failure, anemia and thrombocytopenia one week after bloody diarrhea; coagulation profile is normal but smear shows fragmented RBCs due to endothelial injury from shiga toxin producing bacteria. Diagnosis:", "a": "DIC", "b": "HUS", "c": "ITP", "d": "Hemophilia", "ans": "B", "e": "HUS is the diagnosis; child with acute renal failure, anaemia, thrombocytopenia after bloody diarrhoea, normal coagulation, and schistocytes from Shiga toxin endothelial injury fits this microangiopathic syndrome.<br><br>Diagnosis by stool culture for Shiga toxin-producing E. coli O157:H7. Treatment includes supportive care, dialysis if needed, and avoiding antibiotics (may worsen by releasing more toxin).<br><br>DIC (option A) features prolonged PT and aPTT, low fibrinogen, elevated D-dimer; ITP (option C) features isolated thrombocytopenia without schistocytes or renal failure; haemophilia (option D) features deep tissue bleeds, none fitting post-diarrhoeal microangiopathy like HUS.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "An adult patient presents with fluctuating neurological deficits, fever, thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic hemolytic anemia while coagulation studies remain normal; the disease results from autoantibodies inhibiting ADAMTS13 causing ultra-large vWF multimers. Diagnosis:", "a": "Vitamin K deficiency", "b": "DIC", "c": "Liver failure", "d": "TTP", "ans": "D", "e": "TTP fits adult with fluctuating neurological deficits, fever, thrombocytopenia, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, normal coagulation, and anti-ADAMTS13 autoantibodies producing ultra-large vWF multimers.<br><br>Diagnosis confirmed by ADAMTS13 activity under 10 percent. Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Vitamin K deficiency (option A) prolongs PT first; DIC (option B) features prolonged PT and aPTT and low fibrinogen; liver failure (option C) prolongs PT and aPTT, none fitting ADAMTS13-deficient microangiopathy with normal coagulation like TTP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with metastatic carcinoma develops chronic low-grade DIC with recurrent venous thrombosis due to ongoing tumor tissue factor release; preferred therapy besides treating cancer is:", "a": "Iron therapy", "b": "Platelet transfusion", "c": "Desmopressin", "d": "Heparin anticoagulation", "ans": "D", "e": "Heparin anticoagulation is preferred therapy for metastatic cancer-associated chronic DIC with recurrent venous thrombosis; anticoagulation interrupts ongoing tumour tissue factor-driven coagulation activation.<br><br>Standard low-molecular-weight heparin therapy. Combined with addressing underlying malignancy and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Iron therapy (option A) is for iron deficiency; platelet transfusion (option B) worsens thrombosis in this scenario; desmopressin (option C) is for vWD and mild haemophilia A, none being chronic thrombotic DIC therapy like heparin.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "During complicated labor a woman develops sudden bleeding from episiotomy site and hypotension with labs showing low fibrinogen, prolonged PT/aPTT and elevated FDP due to release of thromboplastin from placenta into circulation. Diagnosis:", "a": "Hemophilia", "b": "DIC", "c": "HUS", "d": "TTP", "ans": "B", "e": "DIC fits complicated labour with sudden bleeding, hypotension, low fibrinogen, prolonged PT/aPTT, and elevated FDP; thromboplastin release from placenta into circulation triggers consumption coagulopathy.<br><br>Treatment includes urgent delivery, addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, tranexamic acid, and uterotonics. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Haemophilia (option A) features isolated aPTT prolongation with male X-linked; HUS (option C) features microangiopathy without prolonged coagulation; TTP (option D) features pentad with normal coagulation, none fitting obstetric consumption coagulopathy like DIC.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with microangiopathic hemolysis and thrombocytopenia receives platelet transfusion and suddenly worsens neurologically due to increased platelet aggregation in microvasculature; underlying disorder is:", "a": "DIC", "b": "HUS", "c": "TTP", "d": "ITP", "ans": "C", "e": "TTP fits microangiopathic haemolysis and thrombocytopenia patient who worsens neurologically after platelet transfusion; supplied platelets aggregate on ultra-large vWF multimers exacerbating microvascular thrombosis.<br><br>Platelet transfusion contraindicated except for life-threatening bleeding. Standard treatment is urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>DIC (option A) requires platelets for severe bleeding; HUS (option B) does not have this platelet-transfusion-worsening response; ITP (option D) requires platelets for severe bleeding, none worsening with platelet transfusion like TTP.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In severe sepsis, endotoxin activates coagulation cascade causing consumption of clotting factors and simultaneous fibrinolysis leading to bleeding and organ ischemia; lab findings expected:", "a": "Normal platelets", "b": "Increased fibrinogen", "c": "Normal PT", "d": "Prolonged PT and elevated D-dimer", "ans": "D", "e": "Prolonged PT and elevated D-dimer are expected DIC lab findings in severe sepsis; endotoxin activates coagulation cascade with simultaneous fibrinolysis producing consumption coagulopathy.<br><br>Combined with prolonged aPTT, low fibrinogen, low platelets, and schistocytes on smear. Treatment includes addressing underlying sepsis, FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, and supportive care. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Normal platelets (option A) is opposite (consumed in DIC); increased fibrinogen (option B) is opposite (consumed); normal PT (option C) is opposite (prolonged), none being DIC lab findings like prolonged PT with elevated D-dimer.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child with hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia and acute kidney injury after diarrheal illness requires primary management consisting of:", "a": "Heparin", "b": "Plasma exchange", "c": "Supportive therapy", "d": "Vitamin K", "ans": "C", "e": "Supportive therapy is primary management for child with haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, and acute kidney injury after diarrhoea (typical HUS); self-limiting course with renal support during acute phase.<br><br>Combined with dialysis if needed. Antibiotic therapy controversial (may worsen Shiga toxin release). Avoiding antimotility drugs important. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Heparin (option A) worsens bleeding risk; plasma exchange (option B) is for TTP or atypical HUS; vitamin K (option D) is for vitamin K deficiency, none being typical HUS primary management like supportive therapy.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with TTP improves dramatically after daily plasma exchange because removal of autoantibodies restores cleavage of:", "a": "Fibrinogen", "b": "Large vWF multimers", "c": "Prothrombin", "d": "Factor X", "ans": "B", "e": "Large vWF multimers cleavage is restored by plasma exchange in TTP; removing anti-ADAMTS13 antibodies and replacing missing enzyme allows normal cleavage of ultra-large vWF multimers.<br><br>Standard daily plasma exchange (40-60 mL/kg) with FFP replacement until platelet recovery. Combined with corticosteroids and rituximab for refractory disease. Caplacizumab targets vWF-platelet interaction. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Fibrinogen (option A) is not ADAMTS13 substrate; prothrombin (option C) is not ADAMTS13 substrate; factor X (option D) is not ADAMTS13 substrate, none being ADAMTS13 cleavage substrate like large vWF multimers.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In DIC, organ failure such as renal cortical necrosis occurs primarily due to widespread:", "a": "Microthrombi formation", "b": "Hemorrhage alone", "c": "Platelet deficiency only", "d": "Hypotension only", "ans": "A", "e": "Microthrombi formation causes organ failure in DIC; widespread microvascular fibrin deposition produces renal cortical necrosis, hepatic dysfunction, and other organ ischaemia.<br><br>Combined with consumption coagulopathy producing bleeding. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, and heparin for thrombotic predominance. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemorrhage alone (option B) is one feature but not principal organ failure mechanism; platelet deficiency only (option C) is not principal; hypotension only (option D) is contributory not principal, none being DIC principal organ failure mechanism like microthrombi.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A critically ill septic patient develops purpura fulminans with skin necrosis, low platelets and prolonged coagulation times due to systemic coagulation activation and consumption of natural anticoagulants. The diagnosis is:", "a": "Hemophilia", "b": "DIC", "c": "HUS", "d": "TTP", "ans": "B", "e": "DIC fits critically ill septic patient with purpura fulminans, skin necrosis, low platelets, prolonged coagulation, and consumption of natural anticoagulants (protein C, antithrombin).<br><br>Treatment includes addressing underlying sepsis, FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, activated protein C in selected cases, and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Haemophilia (option A) features isolated aPTT prolongation; HUS (option C) features normal coagulation; TTP (option D) features normal coagulation, none fitting purpura fulminans with prolonged coagulation like DIC.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A previously healthy adult presents with fever, confusion and petechiae; labs show thrombocytopenia and hemolytic anemia but normal PT/aPTT. Immediate life-saving treatment is:", "a": "Heparin", "b": "Plasma exchange", "c": "Vitamin K", "d": "Platelet transfusion", "ans": "B", "e": "Plasma exchange is immediate life-saving treatment for healthy adult with fever, confusion, petechiae, thrombocytopenia, haemolytic anaemia, and normal coagulation (TTP); removes ADAMTS13 antibodies and replaces enzyme.<br><br>Standard daily plasma exchange (40-60 mL/kg) with FFP replacement until platelet recovery. Combined with corticosteroids and rituximab for refractory disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Heparin (option A) is for thrombotic DIC; vitamin K (option C) is for vitamin K deficiency; platelet transfusion (option D) worsens TTP thrombosis, none being TTP life-saving therapy like plasma exchange.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Following diarrheal illness, a child develops oliguria and anemia; stool culture grows E.coli O157:H7 and smear shows schistocytes without coagulation abnormality. The pathophysiology involves:", "a": "Autoimmune platelets destruction", "b": "Endothelial toxin injury", "c": "Factor VIII deficiency", "d": "ADAMTS13 deficiency", "ans": "B", "e": "Endothelial toxin injury is pathophysiology of child's post-diarrhoeal HUS; E. coli O157:H7 Shiga toxin binds Gb3 receptors on endothelial cells producing platelet aggregation, microthrombi, and microangiopathic haemolysis.<br><br>Particularly affects glomerular endothelium producing acute kidney injury. Treatment includes supportive care, dialysis if needed, and avoiding antibiotics. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Autoimmune platelet destruction (option A) is ITP; factor VIII deficiency (option C) is haemophilia A; ADAMTS13 deficiency (option D) is TTP, none being HUS pathophysiology like Shiga toxin endothelial injury.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In advanced malignancy a patient develops migratory thrombosis and mild bleeding with labs consistent with chronic consumption of clotting factors due to tumor tissue factor expression; therapy includes:", "a": "Folic acid", "b": "Platelets only", "c": "Anticoagulation with heparin", "d": "Vitamin C", "ans": "C", "e": "Anticoagulation with heparin is the therapy for advanced malignancy with migratory thrombosis and chronic consumption coagulopathy from tumour tissue factor expression; anticoagulation interrupts ongoing coagulation activation.<br><br>Common in adenocarcinomas (pancreatic, gastric, prostate). Standard low-molecular-weight heparin therapy. Combined with addressing underlying malignancy and supportive care. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Folic acid (option A) is for megaloblastic anaemia; platelets only (option B) worsen thrombosis; vitamin C (option D) is for scurvy, none being chronic cancer DIC therapy like heparin anticoagulation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A postpartum hemorrhage patient develops laboratory evidence of consumption coagulopathy with falling fibrinogen and rising D-dimer levels; this occurs due to systemic activation of:", "a": "Renin system", "b": "Platelet production", "c": "Coagulation cascade", "d": "Complement cascade", "ans": "C", "e": "Coagulation cascade activation underlies postpartum consumption coagulopathy with falling fibrinogen and rising D-dimer; placental thromboplastin release triggers widespread coagulation.<br><br>Treatment includes urgent delivery, addressing underlying cause, FFP, cryoprecipitate, platelets, tranexamic acid, and uterotonics. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions including obstetrician. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Renin system (option A) controls blood pressure not coagulation; platelet production (option B) is reactive not activated; complement cascade (option D) is immunological, none being postpartum consumption coagulopathy mechanism like coagulation cascade activation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with TTP is mistakenly given platelets and suddenly deteriorates with stroke due to accelerated platelet aggregation in small vessels; the mechanism involves ultra-large:", "a": "Collagen fibers", "b": "vWF multimers", "c": "Fibrin strands", "d": "Factor X complexes", "ans": "B", "e": "vWF multimers underlie TTP platelet aggregation; ultra-large vWF multimers (uncleaved due to ADAMTS13 deficiency) cause accelerated platelet aggregation when platelets transfused.<br><br>Platelet transfusion contraindicated except for life-threatening bleeding. Standard treatment is urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Collagen fibers (option A) bind platelets via vWF normally; fibrin strands (option C) trap platelets but not ultra-large in TTP; factor X complexes (option D) are coagulation not platelet aggregation, none being TTP platelet-aggregation substrate like ultra-large vWF multimers.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In severe DIC secondary to septic shock, replacement therapy with cryoprecipitate is specifically used to restore:", "a": "Vitamin K", "b": "Platelets", "c": "Leukocytes", "d": "Fibrinogen levels", "ans": "D", "e": "Fibrinogen levels are restored by cryoprecipitate in severe DIC secondary to septic shock; cryoprecipitate contains fibrinogen, factor VIII, vWF, factor XIII, and fibronectin.<br><br>Indications include fibrinogen under 1 g/L. Standard dose 10 units. Combined with FFP for other clotting factors, platelets for severe thrombocytopenia, and addressing underlying sepsis. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Vitamin K (option A) is administered separately; platelets (option B) are in platelet transfusion; leukocytes (option C) are not in cryoprecipitate, none being cryoprecipitate principal component restored like fibrinogen.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "An adult with microangiopathic hemolytic anemia and neurological signs but minimal renal impairment most likely has TTP rather than HUS because TTP preferentially affects:", "a": "Brain", "b": "Kidneys", "c": "Spleen", "d": "Liver", "ans": "A", "e": "Brain is preferentially affected in TTP; ADAMTS13 deficiency-driven microthrombi in cerebral microvasculature produce confusion, headache, seizures, and focal deficits more prominently than renal.<br><br>Combined with microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, and variable fever. Treatment includes urgent plasma exchange with FFP replacement, corticosteroids, rituximab, and caplacizumab. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Kidneys (option B) more prominent in HUS; spleen (option C) is not principally affected; liver (option D) is not principally affected, none being TTP preferential target like brain.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A child recovering from HUS continues to have severe renal failure requiring dialysis due to glomerular endothelial swelling and platelet microthrombi primarily affecting:", "a": "Hepatic sinusoids", "b": "Renal microvasculature", "c": "Coronary arteries", "d": "Pulmonary veins", "ans": "B", "e": "Renal microvasculature is affected in HUS producing severe renal failure; Shiga toxin damages glomerular endothelium with platelet microthrombi.<br><br>Combined with microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia and thrombocytopenia. Treatment includes supportive care, dialysis if needed, and avoiding antibiotics. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Hepatic sinusoids (option A) are not principal HUS site; coronary arteries (option C) are not principal; pulmonary veins (option D) are not principal, none being HUS principal target like renal microvasculature.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "During severe infection, release of tissue factor from damaged endothelium activates coagulation and fibrinolysis simultaneously causing both bleeding and thrombosis with prolonged PT, aPTT and low fibrinogen; this syndrome is:", "a": "TTP", "b": "HUS", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "Disseminated intravascular coagulation", "ans": "D", "e": "Disseminated intravascular coagulation fits tissue factor release from damaged endothelium during severe infection causing simultaneous coagulation and fibrinolysis with prolonged PT/aPTT and low fibrinogen.<br><br>Causes include sepsis, malignancy, obstetric complications, trauma. Treatment includes addressing underlying cause, FFP for clotting factors, cryoprecipitate for fibrinogen, platelets for severe thrombocytopenia, and heparin for thrombotic predominance. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>TTP (option A) features normal coagulation tests; HUS (option B) features normal coagulation; haemophilia (option C) features isolated aPTT prolongation, none describing this consumption coagulopathy like DIC.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 45-year-old man presents with fatigue, pruritus after hot bath and splenomegaly. Hb 19 g/dL and low erythropoietin level. The most likely diagnosis is:", "a": "Chronic leukemia", "b": "Thalassemia", "c": "Secondary polycythemia", "d": "Polycythemia vera", "ans": "D", "e": "Polycythaemia vera fits 45-year-old man with fatigue, post-bath pruritus, splenomegaly, elevated Hb 19 g/dL, and low erythropoietin; this myeloproliferative neoplasm features clonal red cell expansion suppressing EPO.<br><br>Diagnosis by JAK2 V617F mutation (95 percent of cases), elevated Hb (over 16.5 in men, 16 in women), and low EPO. Treatment includes phlebotomy targeting haematocrit under 45 percent, low-dose aspirin, and hydroxyurea for high-risk disease.<br><br>Chronic leukaemia (option A) features leukocytosis; secondary polycythaemia (option C) features elevated EPO not low, none fitting low-EPO erythrocytosis with pruritus like polycythaemia vera.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Mutation most commonly associated with polycythemia vera:", "a": "MYC", "b": "JAK2 V617F", "c": "P53", "d": "BCR-ABL", "ans": "B", "e": "JAK2 V617F mutation is most commonly associated with polycythaemia vera; this tyrosine kinase mutation produces constitutive activation driving clonal erythrocytosis.<br><br>Present in 95 percent of polycythaemia vera cases. Also present in essential thrombocythaemia (50 percent) and primary myelofibrosis (50 percent). Diagnosis by mutation testing alongside elevated Hb, low EPO, and bone marrow findings.<br><br>MYC (option A) is in Burkitt lymphoma; P53 (option C) is tumour suppressor in many cancers; BCR-ABL (option D) is in CML, none being polycythaemia vera principal mutation like JAK2 V617F.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with polycythemia vera is at highest risk for:", "a": "Hemorrhage only", "b": "Thrombosis", "c": "Iron overload", "d": "Neutropenia", "ans": "B", "e": "Thrombosis is the highest risk for polycythaemia vera; elevated haematocrit increases blood viscosity producing arterial and venous thrombosis (including Budd-Chiari syndrome).<br><br>Treatment includes phlebotomy targeting haematocrit under 45 percent, low-dose aspirin, and hydroxyurea for high-risk disease. Combined with addressing thrombotic risk factors. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemorrhage only (option A) is not principal risk; iron overload (option C) is from chronic transfusion; neutropenia (option D) is unrelated to PV, none being PV principal complication like thrombosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "First-line treatment for symptomatic polycythemia vera:", "a": "Platelet transfusion", "b": "Folic acid", "c": "Iron therapy", "d": "Phlebotomy", "ans": "D", "e": "Phlebotomy is first-line treatment for symptomatic polycythaemia vera; reducing haematocrit under 45 percent decreases blood viscosity and thrombotic risk.<br><br>Combined with low-dose aspirin (75-100 mg daily) for additional thrombotic protection. Hydroxyurea for high-risk disease (age over 60, prior thrombosis). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Platelet transfusion (option A) worsens viscosity; folic acid (option B) is for megaloblastic anaemia; iron therapy (option C) contraindicated in PV, none being PV first-line therapy like phlebotomy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with high Hb and high erythropoietin level suggests:", "a": "Secondary polycythemia", "b": "Aplastic anemia", "c": "Polycythemia vera", "d": "Myeloma", "ans": "A", "e": "Secondary polycythaemia is suggested by high Hb with high erythropoietin level; appropriate EPO elevation reflects compensatory response to hypoxia or inappropriate EPO production.<br><br>Causes include chronic hypoxia (COPD, sleep apnoea, high altitude, congenital cyanotic heart disease), renal cell carcinoma, hepatocellular carcinoma, and EPO doping. Treatment addresses underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Aplastic anaemia (option B) features pancytopenia; polycythaemia vera (option C) features low EPO; myeloma (option D) features plasma cell neoplasm, none fitting high-Hb-high-EPO like secondary polycythaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Massive splenomegaly with tear-drop cells on smear suggests:", "a": "Hemophilia", "b": "Myelofibrosis", "c": "DIC", "d": "ITP", "ans": "B", "e": "Myelofibrosis fits massive splenomegaly with tear-drop cells on smear; bone marrow fibrosis displaces haematopoiesis to spleen producing massive splenomegaly with extramedullary haematopoiesis.<br><br>Diagnosis by bone marrow biopsy showing fibrosis (often dry tap), JAK2/CALR/MPL mutations, and leukoerythroblastic blood film with tear-drop poikilocytes. Treatment includes JAK inhibitors (ruxolitinib), supportive care, and allogeneic stem cell transplantation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Haemophilia (option A) features deep tissue bleeds; DIC (option C) features consumption coagulopathy; ITP (option D) features isolated thrombocytopenia, none featuring massive splenomegaly with tear-drop cells like myelofibrosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Leukoerythroblastic blood picture is characteristic of:", "a": "Iron deficiency", "b": "Thrombocytosis", "c": "Bone marrow infiltration", "d": "Hemophilia", "ans": "C", "e": "Bone marrow infiltration characteristically produces leukoerythroblastic blood picture; nucleated red cells and immature white cells appear in peripheral blood when marrow architecture disrupted.<br><br>Causes include myelofibrosis, metastatic carcinoma, granulomatous disease, leukaemia, and severe sepsis. Diagnosis by bone marrow biopsy. Treatment depends on underlying cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) features microcytic anaemia without leukoerythroblastic picture; thrombocytosis (option B) is reactive or essential; haemophilia (option D) is coagulation disorder, none producing leukoerythroblastic picture like marrow infiltration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Primary treatment for symptomatic essential thrombocythemia:", "a": "Hydroxyurea", "b": "FFP", "c": "Iron therapy", "d": "Vitamin K", "ans": "A", "e": "Hydroxyurea is primary treatment for symptomatic essential thrombocythaemia; this myelosuppressive agent reduces platelet count to under 400 x 10^9/L.<br><br>Indications include thrombotic history, age over 60, or platelets over 1500 x 10^9/L. Combined with low-dose aspirin for thrombotic prevention. Anagrelide and interferon alfa are alternatives. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>FFP (option B) is for clotting factor replacement; iron therapy (option C) worsens thrombocytosis if reactive; vitamin K (option D) is for vitamin K deficiency, none being ET first-line therapy like hydroxyurea.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Platelet count >1 million with thrombosis suggests:", "a": "DIC", "b": "Essential thrombocythemia", "c": "Reactive thrombocytosis", "d": "ITP", "ans": "B", "e": "Essential thrombocythaemia fits platelet count over 1 million with thrombosis; this myeloproliferative neoplasm features clonal megakaryocyte proliferation.<br><br>Diagnosis by JAK2 V617F (50 percent), CALR (25 percent), or MPL mutations, persistent platelets over 450 x 10^9/L, and bone marrow showing megakaryocyte hyperplasia. Treatment includes hydroxyurea, low-dose aspirin, and anagrelide.<br><br>DIC (option A) features low platelets with consumption; reactive thrombocytosis (option C) is from inflammation, infection, malignancy, iron deficiency, post-splenectomy; ITP (option D) features low platelets, none fitting platelet over 1 million with thrombosis like ET.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with severe neutropenia (<500) is at highest risk for:", "a": "Polycythemia", "b": "Thrombosis", "c": "Hemorrhage", "d": "Bacterial infections", "ans": "D", "e": "Bacterial infections are highest risk for severe neutropenia under 500/µL; reduced neutrophil count impairs defence against bacterial pathogens.<br><br>Treatment includes broad-spectrum antibiotics for febrile neutropenia, prophylactic antibiotics in some protocols, and growth factors (G-CSF) selectively. Combined with reverse isolation and avoiding contact with infections. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Polycythaemia (option A) is unrelated; thrombosis (option B) is unrelated; haemorrhage (option C) is thrombocytopenia consequence, none being severe neutropenia principal complication like bacterial infection.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A chemotherapy patient develops fever with ANC 300/µL and no obvious infection source. Immediate management:", "a": "Oral iron", "b": "Wait for cultures", "c": "Broad-spectrum IV antibiotics", "d": "Steroids only", "ans": "C", "e": "Broad-spectrum IV antibiotics are immediate management of chemotherapy patient with fever and ANC 300/µL; febrile neutropenia is medical emergency requiring prompt empirical antimicrobial therapy.<br><br>Standard empirical regimens include piperacillin-tazobactam, cefepime, or meropenem within 1 hour of presentation. Add vancomycin for suspected line infection or severe sepsis. Combined with blood cultures and source identification.<br><br>Oral iron (option A) is for iron deficiency; wait for cultures (option B) delays life-saving therapy; steroids only (option D) worsen infection, none being febrile neutropenia management like broad-spectrum IV antibiotics.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient presents with fatigue and spoon-shaped nails; Hb low and ferritin low. Mechanism:", "a": "Impaired heme synthesis due to iron deficiency", "b": "Marrow fibrosis", "c": "B12 deficiency", "d": "Hemolysis", "ans": "A", "e": "Impaired haem synthesis due to iron deficiency is the mechanism for fatigue, koilonychia, low Hb, and low ferritin; reduced iron limits haemoglobin synthesis.<br><br>Treatment includes oral iron (ferrous sulfate) for 3-6 months and addressing underlying cause. IV iron for malabsorption or oral intolerance. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Marrow fibrosis (option B) is myelofibrosis; B12 deficiency (option C) features macrocytosis; haemolysis (option D) features reticulocytosis, none being iron deficiency mechanism like impaired haem synthesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A woman with long-standing rheumatoid arthritis has normocytic anemia, low serum iron and normal ferritin. Diagnosis:", "a": "Thalassemia", "b": "Anemia of chronic disease", "c": "Iron deficiency anemia", "d": "Hemolytic anemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Anaemia of chronic disease fits rheumatoid arthritis patient with normocytic anaemia, low serum iron, and normal ferritin; inflammatory cytokine-driven hepcidin elevates trapping iron in macrophages.<br><br>Mechanism involves elevated hepcidin reducing ferroportin expression decreasing iron release. Treatment addresses underlying inflammatory disease. Iron supplementation usually ineffective. EPO therapy for severe symptomatic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Thalassaemia (option A) features microcytic anaemia and target cells; iron deficiency anaemia (option C) features low ferritin; haemolytic anaemia (option D) features reticulocytosis, none fitting RA-associated normocytic-low-iron-normal-ferritin pattern like ACD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In anemia of chronic disease iron is trapped due to increased:", "a": "Ferritin breakdown", "b": "Transferrin", "c": "Erythropoietin", "d": "Hepcidin", "ans": "D", "e": "Hepcidin elevation traps iron in anaemia of chronic disease; inflammatory cytokines elevate hepcidin which blocks ferroportin retaining iron in macrophages.<br><br>Combined with low serum iron, low TIBC, normal-high ferritin. Treatment addresses underlying inflammatory disease. Iron supplementation usually ineffective unless concurrent iron deficiency. EPO therapy for severe symptomatic anaemia. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Ferritin breakdown (option A) is not principal mechanism; transferrin (option B) is reduced in ACD not elevated; erythropoietin (option C) is reduced in ACD, none being principal ACD iron-trapping mediator like hepcidin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with jaundice, high LDH, low haptoglobin and reticulocytosis most likely has:", "a": "Thalassemia minor", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Hemolytic anemia", "d": "Aplastic anemia", "ans": "C", "e": "Haemolytic anaemia fits jaundice, high LDH, low haptoglobin, and reticulocytosis; classical haemolysis pattern with bone marrow compensation.<br><br>Diagnosis includes Coombs test, peripheral smear, and specific tests depending on cause (G6PD assay, osmotic fragility, Hb electrophoresis, ADAMTS13). Treatment depends on cause (steroids for warm AIHA, trigger avoidance for G6PD, splenectomy for hereditary spherocytosis). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions.<br><br>Thalassaemia minor (option A) features microcytic anaemia without principally elevated LDH; iron deficiency (option B) features low ferritin; aplastic anaemia (option D) features pancytopenia with low reticulocytes, none fitting haemolysis triad like haemolytic anaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Dark urine in intravascular hemolysis is due to:", "a": "Hemoglobinuria", "b": "Myoglobinuria", "c": "Bilirubinuria", "d": "Proteinuria", "ans": "A", "e": "Haemoglobinuria causes dark urine in intravascular haemolysis; free haemoglobin in plasma exceeds haptoglobin binding capacity and filters through glomerulus.<br><br>Causes include G6PD deficiency, PNH, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, transfusion reactions, and severe trauma. Diagnosis by elevated LDH, low haptoglobin, haemoglobinuria, and haemoglobinaemia. Treatment depends on cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Myoglobinuria (option B) is from rhabdomyolysis; bilirubinuria (option C) is from biliary obstruction; proteinuria (option D) is from renal disease, none being intravascular haemolysis dark urine cause like haemoglobinuria.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Direct Coombs test detects:", "a": "Plasma hemoglobin", "b": "Platelet antibodies", "c": "Complement deficiency", "d": "Antibodies on RBC surface", "ans": "D", "e": "Antibodies on RBC surface are detected by direct Coombs test; anti-human globulin reagent agglutinates red cells coated with IgG or C3.<br><br>Positive in warm AIHA (IgG), cold agglutinin disease (C3), drug-induced haemolysis, haemolytic disease of newborn, and transfusion reactions. Indirect Coombs test detects free antibodies in serum. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Plasma haemoglobin (option A) is for haemolysis assessment; platelet antibodies (option B) are for ITP/HIT; complement deficiency (option C) is for immunodeficiency, none being detected by direct Coombs like RBC-bound antibodies.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Warm autoimmune hemolysis is usually mediated by:", "a": "IgM antibodies", "b": "IgE antibodies", "c": "IgG antibodies", "d": "IgA antibodies", "ans": "C", "e": "IgG antibodies mediate warm autoimmune haemolysis; these antibodies bind red cells optimally at 37°C producing extravascular haemolysis in spleen.<br><br>Diagnosis by direct Coombs test positive for IgG with or without C3. Causes include idiopathic, lymphoproliferative disorders (CLL, lymphoma), autoimmune disease (SLE), and drugs (methyldopa). Treatment with corticosteroids first-line, rituximab or splenectomy second-line.<br><br>IgM antibodies (option A) are in cold agglutinin disease; IgE antibodies (option B) are in allergic reactions; IgA antibodies (option D) are in mucosal immunity, none being warm AIHA mediator like IgG.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Cold agglutinin disease is associated with:", "a": "Thrombocytosis", "b": "Mycoplasma infection", "c": "Iron deficiency", "d": "Vitamin deficiency", "ans": "B", "e": "Mycoplasma infection is associated with cold agglutinin disease; this atypical pneumonia produces transient anti-I cold agglutinins.<br><br>Other associations include EBV (anti-i specificity), idiopathic, and lymphoproliferative disorders. Diagnosis by direct Coombs test positive for C3, elevated cold agglutinin titre. Treatment of underlying infection. Cold avoidance and rituximab for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Thrombocytosis (option A) is unrelated; iron deficiency (option C) is unrelated; vitamin deficiency (option D) is unrelated, none being principal cold agglutinin disease association like Mycoplasma infection.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Spherocytes on smear suggest:", "a": "Hereditary spherocytosis or AIHA", "b": "Thalassemia", "c": "Iron deficiency", "d": "Aplastic anemia", "ans": "A", "e": "Hereditary spherocytosis or AIHA fits spherocytes on smear; both conditions produce spherical red cells through different mechanisms.<br><br>Hereditary spherocytosis features membrane skeleton defect (ankyrin, spectrin, band 3, protein 4.2) with negative Coombs. Warm AIHA features antibody-mediated membrane fragment removal with positive Coombs. Treatment differs significantly. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Thalassaemia (option B) features target cells; iron deficiency (option C) features pencil cells; aplastic anaemia (option D) features pancytopenia without spherocytes, none being spherocyte-associated like hereditary spherocytosis or AIHA.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A young man has splenomegaly, jaundice and spherocytes with increased osmotic fragility. Diagnosis:", "a": "Sickle cell disease", "b": "Thalassemia", "c": "G6PD deficiency", "d": "Hereditary spherocytosis", "ans": "D", "e": "Hereditary spherocytosis fits young man with splenomegaly, jaundice, spherocytes, and increased osmotic fragility; autosomal dominant membrane skeleton defect produces this classical pattern.<br><br>Diagnosis by family history, peripheral smear showing spherocytes, increased osmotic fragility, and EMA binding test. Treatment includes folate supplementation, splenectomy for severe disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Sickle cell disease (option A) features sickle cells; thalassaemia (option B) features target cells; G6PD deficiency (option C) features bite cells, none fitting splenomegaly-jaundice-spherocytes-osmotic fragility like hereditary spherocytosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Best definitive treatment for hereditary spherocytosis:", "a": "Plasma exchange", "b": "Iron therapy", "c": "Splenectomy", "d": "Vitamin K", "ans": "C", "e": "Splenectomy is best definitive treatment for hereditary spherocytosis; removes principal site of red cell destruction without correcting membrane defect.<br><br>Indications include severe haemolysis, transfusion dependence, and growth retardation. Pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib vaccinations before splenectomy. Long-term penicillin prophylaxis. Combined with folate supplementation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Plasma exchange (option A) is for TTP; iron therapy (option B) is for iron deficiency and contraindicated risking overload; vitamin K (option D) is for vitamin K deficiency, none being hereditary spherocytosis definitive treatment like splenectomy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with bite cells after antimalarial drug exposure likely has:", "a": "Thalassemia", "b": "G6PD deficiency", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "Aplastic anemia", "ans": "B", "e": "G6PD deficiency is the likely diagnosis for bite cells after antimalarial drug exposure; oxidative stress from primaquine produces Heinz body inclusions removed by splenic macrophages producing bite cells.<br><br>Diagnosis by enzyme assay (may be falsely normal during acute haemolysis as deficient older cells lysed first). Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Thalassaemia (option A) features target cells not bite cells; haemophilia (option C) features deep tissue bleeds; aplastic anaemia (option D) features pancytopenia, none being drug-triggered bite cell cause like G6PD deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "In G6PD deficiency hemolysis occurs due to:", "a": "Iron overload", "b": "Antibody destruction", "c": "Splenic sequestration", "d": "Oxidative stress", "ans": "D", "e": "Oxidative stress causes haemolysis in G6PD deficiency; reduced NADPH production impairs glutathione regeneration making red cells vulnerable to oxidative damage from triggers.<br><br>Common triggers include primaquine, dapsone, sulfa drugs, nitrofurantoin, fava beans, and bacterial infections. Mechanism includes haemoglobin denaturation producing Heinz bodies and bite cells. Treatment with trigger avoidance and supportive care.<br><br>Iron overload (option A) is from transfusion-dependent anaemias; antibody destruction (option B) is autoimmune haemolysis; splenic sequestration (option C) is sickle cell crisis, none being G6PD haemolysis mechanism like oxidative stress.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Heinz bodies consist of:", "a": "DNA fragments", "b": "Iron granules", "c": "Denatured hemoglobin", "d": "Platelets", "ans": "C", "e": "Denatured haemoglobin forms Heinz bodies; oxidative damage produces precipitates of denatured haemoglobin within red cells in G6PD deficiency and unstable haemoglobinopathies.<br><br>Visible on supravital staining (methylene blue or crystal violet) but not on routine Wright stain. Splenic macrophages remove Heinz bodies producing characteristic bite cells. Treatment includes trigger avoidance and supportive care. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>DNA fragments (option A) are Howell-Jolly bodies; iron granules (option B) are Pappenheimer bodies; platelets (option D) are unrelated, none being Heinz body composition like denatured haemoglobin.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Sickle cell crisis is precipitated by:", "a": "Hypothermia", "b": "Hypoxia", "c": "Alkalosis", "d": "Hyperoxia", "ans": "B", "e": "Hypoxia precipitates sickle cell crisis; deoxygenated HbS polymerises producing sickle cell shape with microvascular obstruction.<br><br>Other triggers include acidosis, dehydration, cold exposure, infection, and stress. Treatment includes IV fluids, analgesia, oxygen, and addressing precipitants. Hydroxyurea reduces frequency of crises through HbF induction. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Multidisciplinary team approach optimises outcomes.<br><br>Hypothermia (option A) is contributory but not principal; alkalosis (option C) is opposite (reduces sickling); hyperoxia (option D) is opposite (reduces sickling), none being principal sickling trigger like hypoxia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Hydroxyurea helps sickle cell disease by increasing:", "a": "HbF", "b": "Platelets", "c": "Iron", "d": "HbA", "ans": "A", "e": "HbF induction is hydroxyurea's mechanism in sickle cell disease; fetal haemoglobin interferes with HbS polymerisation reducing sickle cell formation.<br><br>Indications include frequent painful crises, acute chest syndrome, and severe anaemia. Side effects include myelosuppression and rarely teratogenicity. Combined with addressing underlying sickle cell disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Platelets (option B) are not hydroxyurea target; iron (option C) is contraindicated risking overload; HbA (option D) is not produced by hydroxyurea, none being hydroxyurea mechanism like HbF induction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Parvovirus B19 infection in sickle cell causes:", "a": "Sequestration crisis", "b": "Pain crisis", "c": "Hemolytic crisis", "d": "Aplastic crisis", "ans": "D", "e": "Aplastic crisis is caused by parvovirus B19 in sickle cell disease; this virus infects erythroid precursors halting red cell production while haemolysis continues.<br><br>Diagnosis by parvovirus B19 PCR in blood, anti-parvovirus B19 IgM serology, reticulocytopenia, and falling Hb. Treatment with IVIG and supportive care. Bone marrow recovery follows clearance. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Sequestration crisis (option A) is splenic; pain crisis (option B) is vaso-occlusive; haemolytic crisis (option C) features reticulocytosis, none being parvovirus B19 mechanism like aplastic crisis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Target cells are commonly seen in:", "a": "Thalassemia", "b": "ITP", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "DIC", "ans": "A", "e": "Thalassaemia commonly features target cells; ineffective erythropoiesis and increased membrane to volume ratio produce characteristic bullseye appearance.<br><br>Other target cell causes include liver disease, hyposplenism, sickle cell disease (HbS-related), and severe iron deficiency. Combined with microcytic anaemia, elevated RBC count, and HbA2 over 3.5 percent (beta trait) or normal HbA2 (alpha trait). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>ITP (option B) features isolated thrombocytopenia; haemophilia (option C) features deep tissue bleeds; DIC (option D) features schistocytes, none commonly featuring target cells like thalassaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Elevated RDW favors diagnosis of:", "a": "Thalassemia trait", "b": "Iron deficiency anemia", "c": "Aplastic anemia", "d": "Polycythemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Iron deficiency anaemia features elevated RDW; variable red cell sizes from impaired haem synthesis produce anisocytosis.<br><br>Combined with low ferritin, low transferrin saturation, elevated TIBC, and hypochromic microcytic anaemia. Distinguishing from thalassaemia trait (uniform microcytosis with normal RDW). Treatment with oral iron (ferrous sulfate) for 3-6 months. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Thalassaemia trait (option A) features normal RDW; aplastic anaemia (option C) features normal RDW with pancytopenia; polycythaemia (option D) features elevated Hb, none favouring elevated RDW like iron deficiency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A transfusion patient develops fever and flank pain shortly after transfusion due to ABO incompatibility causing intravascular hemolysis. Immediate step:", "a": "Give iron", "b": "Continue slowly", "c": "Stop transfusion", "d": "Give platelets", "ans": "C", "e": "Stopping transfusion is immediate step in suspected ABO incompatibility reaction; fever and flank pain shortly after transfusion suggests acute haemolytic transfusion reaction.<br><br>Combined with IV fluids, urine output monitoring, alkalinisation of urine, and supportive care. Send transfusion bag and patient blood for crossmatch and Coombs testing. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Give iron (option A) does not address acute haemolysis; continue slowly (option B) worsens reaction; give platelets (option D) is for thrombocytopenia, none being immediate ABO incompatibility step like stop transfusion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Delayed transfusion reaction days later is usually due to:", "a": "Minor antigen antibodies", "b": "Infection", "c": "Platelet destruction", "d": "Iron overload", "ans": "A", "e": "Minor antigen antibodies cause delayed transfusion reactions days later; previously sensitised patient develops anamnestic antibody response (commonly anti-Kidd, anti-Duffy, anti-Kell) producing extravascular haemolysis 3-14 days post-transfusion.<br><br>Features include fever, falling haemoglobin, jaundice, and positive direct Coombs test. Treatment includes supportive care and avoiding implicated antigens in future transfusions. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Infection (option B) features systemic features; platelet destruction (option C) is platelet disorder; iron overload (option D) is chronic transfusion complication, none being delayed transfusion reaction cause like minor antigen antibodies.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Febrile non-hemolytic transfusion reaction caused by:", "a": "Coagulation failure", "b": "Cytokines from donor leukocytes", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Iron overload", "ans": "B", "e": "Cytokines from donor leukocytes cause febrile non-haemolytic transfusion reactions; pre-formed cytokines accumulate during storage producing fever, chills, and rigors without haemolysis.<br><br>Prevention with leukoreduced blood products. Treatment with paracetamol and continuation of transfusion (after excluding haemolysis or bacterial contamination). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Coagulation failure (option A) is in DIC; haemolysis (option C) features back pain and haemoglobinuria; iron overload (option D) is chronic, none being febrile non-haemolytic reaction mechanism like donor leukocyte cytokines.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Massive transfusion may lead to:", "a": "Hypercalcemia", "b": "Polycythemia", "c": "Hypocalcemia", "d": "Thrombocytosis", "ans": "C", "e": "Hypocalcaemia complicates massive transfusion; citrate anticoagulant in blood products chelates calcium when transfused rapidly.<br><br>Standard threshold is more than 1 blood volume in 24 hours or rapid transfusion. Treatment includes calcium gluconate replacement (10 mL of 10 percent solution). Combined with monitoring ionised calcium. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Hypercalcaemia (option A) is opposite; polycythaemia (option B) is from RBC excess; thrombocytosis (option D) is from platelet excess, none being massive transfusion complication like hypocalcaemia.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Citrate toxicity during transfusion causes:", "a": "Leukopenia", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "High potassium", "d": "Low calcium", "ans": "D", "e": "Low calcium results from citrate toxicity during transfusion; citrate anticoagulant chelates calcium reducing ionised calcium when transfused rapidly.<br><br>Features include perioral tingling, muscle cramps, Chvostek and Trousseau signs, prolonged QT interval, and arrhythmias. Treatment includes calcium gluconate replacement (10 mL of 10 percent solution). Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Leukopenia (option A) is from chemotherapy or marrow suppression; iron deficiency (option B) is from blood loss; high potassium (option C) is from RBC haemolysis during storage, none being citrate toxicity consequence like hypocalcaemia.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Iron overload in repeated transfusions treated with:", "a": "Vitamin K", "b": "Folic acid", "c": "Deferoxamine", "d": "Heparin", "ans": "C", "e": "Deferoxamine treats iron overload in repeated transfusions; this chelator binds iron facilitating renal excretion.<br><br>Standard regimen subcutaneous infusion 8-12 hours nightly. Indicated when ferritin over 1000 mcg/L or after 10-20 transfusions. Deferasirox and deferiprone are oral alternatives. Combined with monitoring serum ferritin, liver MRI, and cardiac MRI. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Vitamin K (option A) is for vitamin K deficiency; folic acid (option B) is for megaloblastic anaemia; heparin (option D) is anticoagulant, none being iron chelator like deferoxamine.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Graft versus host disease after transfusion prevented by:", "a": "Platelet transfusion", "b": "Irradiated blood products", "c": "Plasma exchange", "d": "Washed RBCs", "ans": "B", "e": "Irradiated blood products prevent transfusion-associated GVHD; gamma irradiation inactivates donor T-lymphocytes that would otherwise engraft and attack recipient tissues.<br><br>Indications include immunocompromised recipients (haematological malignancy, stem cell transplantation, congenital immunodeficiency), intrauterine transfusion, and directed donations from blood relatives. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Platelet transfusion (option A) is for thrombocytopenia; plasma exchange (option C) is for TTP; washed RBCs (option D) reduce plasma proteins but not GVHD, none being GVHD prevention like irradiated products.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "TRALI (transfusion related acute lung injury) presents with:", "a": "Chronic cough", "b": "Jaundice", "c": "Hemarthrosis", "d": "Acute respiratory distress within 6 hours", "ans": "D", "e": "Acute respiratory distress within 6 hours characterises TRALI; donor antibodies against recipient HLA or neutrophil antigens activate recipient neutrophils in pulmonary microvasculature producing non-cardiogenic pulmonary oedema.<br><br>Diagnosis by acute respiratory distress with hypoxaemia and bilateral pulmonary infiltrates within 6 hours of transfusion. Treatment includes supportive care including mechanical ventilation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Chronic cough (option A) is not acute TRALI; jaundice (option B) is from haemolysis; haemarthrosis (option C) is from haemophilia, none being TRALI presentation like acute respiratory distress.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Universal donor for packed RBC transfusion:", "a": "O negative", "b": "B positive", "c": "A negative", "d": "AB positive", "ans": "A", "e": "O negative is the universal donor for packed RBC transfusion; absence of A, B, and Rh antigens prevents recipient antibody-mediated haemolysis.<br><br>Reserved for emergency use when crossmatched blood unavailable, female of childbearing age with Rh-negative status, or trauma resuscitation. Combined with prompt type and crossmatch for definitive blood product selection. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>B positive (option B) has B antigen; A negative (option C) has A antigen; AB positive (option D) has A, B, and Rh antigens, none being universal RBC donor like O negative.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Universal plasma donor:", "a": "A plasma", "b": "O plasma", "c": "B plasma", "d": "AB plasma", "ans": "D", "e": "AB plasma is universal plasma donor; absence of anti-A and anti-B antibodies prevents haemolysis of recipient red cells.<br><br>Used in emergency settings when type-specific plasma unavailable. Combined with prompt type and crossmatch for definitive plasma selection. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management. Distinguishing donor compatibility for plasma versus packed cells.<br><br>A plasma (option A) contains anti-B antibodies; O plasma (option B) contains both anti-A and anti-B (worst plasma donor); B plasma (option C) contains anti-A antibodies, none being universal plasma donor like AB plasma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient with severe anemia has Hb 5 g/dL but stable vitals. Indication for transfusion primarily depends on:", "a": "Clinical symptoms and hemodynamic status", "b": "Age", "c": "Hb number alone", "d": "Gender", "ans": "A", "e": "Clinical symptoms and haemodynamic status primarily determine transfusion indication; restrictive transfusion thresholds (Hb under 7 g/dL or under 8 g/dL with cardiac disease) plus clinical assessment guide decisions.<br><br>Combined with assessment of cardiopulmonary symptoms, ongoing bleeding, and underlying cause. Restrictive strategy reduces transfusion-related complications. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Age (option B) is contributory but not primary; Hb number alone (option C) is one factor among others; gender (option D) is unrelated, none being primary transfusion indication like clinical-haemodynamic assessment.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Reticulocyte count increases in anemia due to:", "a": "Marrow failure", "b": "Iron deficiency only", "c": "Increased marrow response", "d": "Vitamin deficiency only", "ans": "C", "e": "Increased marrow response increases reticulocyte count in anaemia; bone marrow compensates for red cell loss with accelerated erythropoiesis.<br><br>Common in haemolytic anaemias and acute blood loss. Reticulocyte index over 2 percent supports active marrow response. Combined with assessing underlying cause. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Marrow failure (option A) features reticulocytopenia; iron deficiency only (option B) is one cause of anaemia but reticulocytes are low; vitamin deficiency only (option D) is one cause with low reticulocytes, none being elevated reticulocyte mechanism like increased marrow response.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Low reticulocyte count suggests:", "a": "Blood loss", "b": "Hypoproliferative anemia", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Polycythemia", "ans": "B", "e": "Hypoproliferative anaemia is suggested by low reticulocyte count; bone marrow failure to compensate indicates production problem (iron deficiency, B12/folate deficiency, ACD, aplastic anaemia, marrow infiltration).<br><br>Combined with peripheral smear, iron studies, B12, folate, and bone marrow examination as appropriate. Treatment depends on cause. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Blood loss (option A) features reticulocytosis after few days; haemolysis (option C) features reticulocytosis; polycythaemia (option D) features elevated Hb, none being low-reticulocyte pattern like hypoproliferative anaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Macrocytosis with normal B12 and folate suggests:", "a": "Liver disease", "b": "Hemolysis", "c": "Iron deficiency", "d": "Thalassemia", "ans": "A", "e": "Liver disease causes macrocytosis with normal B12 and folate; alcohol toxicity and altered red cell membrane lipid composition produce macrocytic anaemia without megaloblastic features.<br><br>Other causes of macrocytosis with normal B12 and folate include hypothyroidism, myelodysplasia, and reticulocytosis. Treatment addresses underlying liver disease. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential.<br><br>Haemolysis (option B) features reticulocytosis with macrocytosis from reticulocytes but with elevated LDH; iron deficiency (option C) is microcytic; thalassaemia (option D) is microcytic, none fitting macrocytic-normal-B12-folate like liver disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Pancytopenia with hypocellular marrow indicates:", "a": "Leukemia", "b": "Aplastic anemia", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Iron deficiency", "ans": "B", "e": "Aplastic anaemia is indicated by pancytopenia with hypocellular marrow; bone marrow failure produces this combination distinguishing from other pancytopenia causes.<br><br>Causes include idiopathic, drug-induced (chloramphenicol, NSAIDs), toxin exposure (benzene), viral infection (parvovirus B19, hepatitis), and autoimmune. Diagnosis by bone marrow biopsy showing hypocellular marrow with under 25 percent cellularity. Treatment includes immunosuppression, bone marrow transplantation, and supportive care.<br><br>Leukaemia (option A) features hypercellular marrow with blasts; haemolysis (option C) features erythroid hyperplasia not hypocellularity; iron deficiency (option D) features microcytic anaemia without pancytopenia, none being pancytopenia-with-hypocellularity like aplastic anaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Tear drop cells are typical of:", "a": "Hemophilia", "b": "Iron deficiency", "c": "Myelofibrosis", "d": "ITP", "ans": "C", "e": "Myelofibrosis typically features tear-drop cells; bone marrow fibrosis displaces haematopoiesis to spleen producing extramedullary erythropoiesis with characteristic poikilocytes.<br><br>Diagnosis by bone marrow biopsy showing fibrosis (often dry tap), JAK2/CALR/MPL mutations, and leukoerythroblastic blood film with tear-drop poikilocytes. Treatment includes JAK inhibitors (ruxolitinib), supportive care, and allogeneic stem cell transplantation. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Haemophilia (option A) features deep tissue bleeds without tear-drop cells; iron deficiency (option B) features pencil cells; ITP (option D) features isolated thrombocytopenia, none being tear-drop cell-associated like myelofibrosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Basophilic stippling seen in:", "a": "DIC", "b": "ITP", "c": "Hemophilia", "d": "Lead poisoning", "ans": "D", "e": "Lead poisoning features basophilic stippling; lead inhibits pyrimidine 5'-nucleotidase producing RNA accumulation visible as basophilic stippling on smear.<br><br>Combined with microcytic anaemia, elevated free erythrocyte protoporphyrin, and elevated blood lead level. Treatment with chelation (succimer, EDTA, dimercaprol) and removing lead source. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Standard supportive care guides management.<br><br>DIC (option A) features schistocytes not stippling; ITP (option B) features isolated thrombocytopenia; haemophilia (option C) features deep tissue bleeds, none being basophilic stippling-associated like lead poisoning.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "Howell-Jolly bodies indicate:", "a": "Iron deficiency", "b": "Asplenia", "c": "Leukemia", "d": "Hemolysis", "ans": "B", "e": "Asplenia is indicated by Howell-Jolly bodies; absent splenic clearance allows these nuclear remnants to persist in circulating red cells.<br><br>Causes include splenectomy, congenital asplenia, splenic infarction (sickle cell autosplenectomy), and functional asplenia. Combined with target cells, Pappenheimer bodies, and acanthocytes. Indication for pneumococcal, meningococcal, and Hib vaccinations. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) features pencil cells without Howell-Jolly; leukaemia (option C) features blasts; haemolysis (option D) features reticulocytosis, none being principally Howell-Jolly body-associated like asplenia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A patient presents with chronic anemia, bone marrow ring sideroblasts, normal iron stores, and mitochondrial iron accumulation due to defective heme synthesis enzyme; the most likely diagnosis is:", "a": "Hemolytic anemia", "b": "Thalassemia", "c": "Sideroblastic anemia", "d": "Iron deficiency", "ans": "C", "e": "Sideroblastic anaemia is the diagnosis for chronic anaemia, ring sideroblasts, normal iron stores, and mitochondrial iron accumulation from defective haem synthesis; ring sideroblasts on Prussian blue stain are pathognomonic.<br><br>Causes include hereditary (X-linked ALAS2 mutation), drug-induced (isoniazid, chloramphenicol, alcohol), lead toxicity, and myelodysplastic syndrome. Treatment depends on cause (pyridoxine for hereditary and isoniazid-induced).<br><br>Haemolytic anaemia (option A) features reticulocytosis without ring sideroblasts; thalassaemia (option B) features microcytic anaemia with target cells; iron deficiency (option D) features low ferritin, none being ring sideroblast-defining like sideroblastic anaemia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A hematology researcher identifies anemia caused by mutation impairing transferrin receptor recycling leading to ineffective erythropoiesis despite adequate iron, mimicking functional iron deficiency at cellular level. The mechanism best fits:", "a": "Blood loss", "b": "Aplastic anemia", "c": "Hemolysis", "d": "Iron utilization defect anemia", "ans": "D", "e": "Iron utilisation defect anaemia fits transferrin receptor recycling mutation producing ineffective erythropoiesis despite adequate iron; cellular iron incorporation impairment mimics functional iron deficiency.<br><br>Mechanism includes impaired transferrin receptor recycling preventing adequate cellular iron uptake. Treatment depends on specific defect. Multidisciplinary team optimises decisions for individual patients. Long-term follow-up is essential. Patient education supports self-management.<br><br>Blood loss (option A) features depleted iron stores; aplastic anaemia (option B) features pancytopenia; haemolysis (option C) features reticulocytosis, none being adequate-iron-with-impaired-utilisation pattern like iron utilisation defect.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}, {"t": "Haematology", "q": "A 45-year-old patient undergoing heparin therapy develops a sudden drop in platelets from 280,000 to 85,000 on day 8. Most appropriate management:", "a": "Immediately stop all heparin and start argatroban or fondaparinux", "b": "Switch to LMWH only", "c": "Platelet transfusion", "d": "Increase heparin dose", "ans": "A", "e": "Immediately stopping all heparin and starting argatroban or fondaparinux manages heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT); day 8 platelet drop suggests immune-mediated HIT with paradoxical thrombosis risk.<br><br>Diagnosis by 4Ts score, anti-PF4/heparin antibody testing (ELISA), and confirmatory serotonin release assay. Avoid platelet transfusion (worsens thrombosis). Continue alternative anticoagulation until platelets recover and INR therapeutic on warfarin.<br><br>Switch to LMWH only (option B) maintains cross-reactivity risk; platelet transfusion (option C) worsens HIT thrombosis; increase heparin dose (option D) worsens HIT, none being HIT management like heparin cessation with alternative anticoagulant.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>"}];